te": "01/01/1970", "id": "22", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Exporting a Windows Forms control created from Visual Studio 2010 Designer", "parent_id": "10622362", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Jeremy Thompson", "owner_user_id": "495455"},{"body": "eeeeee 555555 vvvvvv  I strongly suspect the problem is simply that the current culture of the thread handling the request isn&#39t set appropriately. \n\n You can either set it for the whole request, or specify the culture while formatting. Either way, I would suggest  not  use  string.Format  with a composite format unless you really have more than one thing to format (or a wider message). Instead, I&#39d use: \n\n  @price.ToString(\"C\", culture)\n  \n\n It just makes it somewhat simpler. \n\n EDIT: Given your comment, it sounds like you may well want to use a UK culture  regardless  of the culture of the user. So again, either set the UK culture as the thread culture for the whole request, or possibly introduce your own helper class with a \"constant\": \n\n  public static class Cultures\n\\{\n    public static readonly CultureInfo UnitedKingdom = \n        CultureInfo.ReadOnly(new CultureInfo(\"en-GB\"));\n\\}\n  \n\n Then: \n\n  @price.ToString(\"C\", Cultures.UnitedKingdom)\n  \n\n In my experience, having a \"named\" set of cultures like this makes the code using it considerably simpler to read, and you don&#39t need to get the string right in multiple places. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/02/2012", "votes_count": 9, "last_edit_date": "05/02/2012", "id": "23", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "String format currency", "parent_id": "10416553", "comment_count": 3, "score": 8