\n\n They match when you print because what is displayed is  comment.id.to_s  \n\n Anyway you&#39d rather do: \n\n  @article.comments.where(:id =&gt; params[:id]).first\n  \n\n Or: \n\n  @article.comments.where(:_id =&gt; params[:id]).first\n  \n\n I&#39m not sure for Mongoid. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/03/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "26", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Rails Controller id Equals", "parent_id": "10428253", "comment_count": 6, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "apneadiving", "owner_user_id": "350087"},{"body": "ffffff 666666 uuuuuu  Any outbound interaction, unless performed through an enricher, will affect the current in-flight message. This is why the call to replacePayloadWithFoo replaces the original message with the result of the outbound interaction. \n\n This said, I can not explain the discrepancy between: \n\n  &lt;expression-transformer evaluator=\"groovy\" expression=\"message.originalPayload\" /&gt;\n  \n\n and: \n\n  &lt;expression-transformer evaluator=\"groovy\" expression=\"originalPayload\" /&gt;\n  \n\n because they both rely on: \n\n  event.getMessage().getPayload()\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/03/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "27", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "what&#39s the scope of a mule message?", "parent_id": "10431912", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "David Dossot", "owner_user_id": "387927"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": "ffffff 666666 uuuuuu  This way is more understandable and uses less processing: \n\n  &lt;!-- this is your php script with your html layout --&gt;\n\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;\n    &lt;?php if($result === true): ?&gt;\n        $(\"#Err\").hide();\n    &lt;?php else: ?&gt;\n        $(\"#Err\").show();\n    &lt;?php endif; ?&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n  \n\n Try not to use echo. It&#39s a good practice for PHP. If you really want to increase your php productivity, I highly recommend  the Codeigniter framework . Give it a try =). \n", "last_activity_date": "05/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/05/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "28", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Display Javascript Code In PHP", "parent_id": "10459361", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "lu1s", "owner_user_id": "645386"},{"body": "ffffff 666666 uuuuuu  Your  q  is submitted from the input in form, so you could just write \n\n  @using (Ajax.BeginForm(MVC.Home.SearchQuery(),\n        new AjaxOptions \\{\n            LoadingElementId = \"loadingGif\",\n            OnSuccess = \"parseResults\",\n            OnFailure = \"searchFailed\"\n        \\})) \\{\n    &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"q\" /&gt;\n    &lt;input type=\"submit\" value=\"Search\" /&gt;\n    &lt;img id=\"loadingGif\" style=\"display:none\" src=\"@Url.Content(\"~/content/images/loading.gif\")\" /&gt;\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/05/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "29", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "T4MVC and Ajax method with parameter", "parent_id": "10463773", "comment_count": 8, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "archil", "owner_user_id": "639343"},{"body": "ffffff 666666 uuuuuu  You should be using the association \"story_rating\" method for your push/append rather than the internal \"rating\" Array.push to get what you want to follow John Nunemaker&#39s \"Array Keys Allow For Modeling Simplicity\" discussion.  The difference is that with the association method, MongoMapper will insert the BSON::ObjectId reference into the array, with the latter you are pushing a Ruby StoryRating object into the Array, and the underlying driver driver cant serialize it. \n\n Here&#39s a test that works for me, that shows the difference.  Hope that this helps. \n\n Test \n\n  require &#39test_helper&#39\n\nclass Object\n  def to_pretty_json\n    JSON.pretty_generate(JSON.parse(self.to_json))\n  end\nend\n\nclass StoryTest &lt; ActiveSupport::TestCase\n  def setup\n    User.delete_all\n    Story.delete_all\n    StoryRating.delete_all\n    @stories_coll = Mongo::Connection.new[&#39free11513_mongomapper_bson_test&#39][&#39stories&#39]\n  end\n\n  test \"Array Keys\" do\n    user = User.create(:name =&gt; &#39Gary&#39)\n    story = Story.create(:title =&gt; &#39A Tale of Two Cities&#39)\n    rating = StoryRating.create(:user_id =&gt; user.id, :rating =&gt; 5)\n    assert_equal(1, StoryRating.count)\n    story.ratings.push(rating)\n    p story.ratings\n    assert_raise(BSON::InvalidDocument) \\{ story.save \\}\n    story.ratings.pop\n    story.story_ratings.push(rating) # note story.story_ratings, NOT story.ratings\n    p story.ratings\n    assert_nothing_raised(BSON::InvalidDocument) \\{ story.save \\}\n    assert_equal(1, Story.count)\n    puts Story.all(:ratings =&gt; rating.id).to_pretty_json\n  end\nend\n  \n\n Result \n\n  Run options: --name=test_Array_Keys\n\n# Running tests:\n\n[#&lt;StoryRating _id: BSON::ObjectId(&#394fa98c25e4d30b9765000003&#39), created_at: Tue, 08 May 2012 21:12:05 UTC +00:00, rating: 5, updated_at: Tue, 08 May 2012 21:12:05 UTC +00:00, user_id: BSON::ObjectId(&#394fa98c25e4d30b9765000001&#39)&gt;]\n[BSON::ObjectId(&#394fa98c25e4d30b9765000003&#39)]\n[\n  \\{\n    \"created_at\": \"05/08/2012T21:12:05Z\",\n    \"id\": \"4fa98c25e4d30b9765000002\",\n    \"ratings\": [\n      \"4fa98c25e4d30b9765000003\"\n    ],\n    \"title\": \"A Tale of Two Cities\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"05/08/2012T21:12:05Z\"\n  \\}\n]\n.\n\nFinished tests in 0.023377s, 42.7771 tests/s, 171.1084 assertions/s.\n\n1 tests, 4 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 skips\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/08/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/08/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "05/08/2012", "id": "30", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "BSON::InvalidDocument: Cannot serialize an object into BSON", "parent_id": "10491322", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "1316225", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Gary Murakami", "owner_user_id": "1316225"},{"body": "gggggg 777777 tttttt  To make sure I understand, your question is how to find out the key names of the subobjects one level down? \n\n In the inner if-statement, calling element.Value.AsBsonDocument should return you a BSON document.  You should then be able to iterate over the fields in that document in the same way that you iterated over the fields of the outer document.  Your resulting code would probably look something like: \n\n  void Print(BsonDocument document)\n\\{\n    foreach (var element in document)\n    \\{\n        if (element.Value.IsBsonDocument)\n        \\{\n            BsonDocument subdoc = element.Value.AsBsonDocument;\n            foreach (var subelement in subdoc)\n            \\{\n                // Code to print the subdocument here\n            \\}\n        \\}\n\n    \\}\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/09/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/09/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "31", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Understanding deeply nested document structure in mongo db", "parent_id": "10521253", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "stbrody", "owner_user_id": "837024"},{"body": "gggggg 777777 tttttt  problem solved. \n\n As it turns out, the idea of running code to recuse through my javascript directories works.  I just had the code incorrect.  Here is the code that dynamically loads my javascript files: \n\n --AppResources.groovy \n\n  import org.codehaus.groovy.grails.web.context.ServletContextHolder as SCH\n\nmodules = \\{\n    core \\{\n        resource url: &#39/resources/css/app.css&#39, disposition: &#39head&#39\n        resource url: &#39/resources/css/myapp.css&#39, disposition: &#39head&#39\n        resource url: &#39/extjs/ext-all-debug.js&#39, dispostion: &#39head&#39\n\n        getFilesForPath(&#39/app&#39).each \\{\n          resource url: it\n        \\}\n    \\}\n\\}\n\ndef getFilesForPath(path) \\{\n\n    def webFileCachePaths = []\n\n    def servletContext = SCH.getServletContext()\n\n    //context isn&#39t present when testing in integration mode. -jg\n    if(!servletContext) return webFileCachePaths\n\n    def realPath = servletContext.getRealPath(&#39/&#39)\n\n    def appDir = new File(\"$realPath/$path\")\n\n    appDir.eachFileRecurse \\{File file -&gt;\n        if (file.isDirectory() || file.isHidden()) return\n        webFileCachePaths &lt;&lt; file.path.replace(realPath, &#39&#39)\n    \\}\n\n    webFileCachePaths\n\\}\n  \n\n The above will cause the Resource plugin to track my javascript files.  Here&#39s what the html looks like when Resources is in debug mode: \n\n  &lt;script src=\"/myapp/extjs/ext-all-debug.js?_debugResources=y&amp;n=1336614540164\" type=\"text/javascript\" &gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"/myapp/app/controller/LogController.js?_debugResources=y&amp;n=1336614540164\" type=\"text/javascript\" &gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"/myapp/app/controller/LoginController.js?_debugResources=y&amp;n=1336614540164\" type=\"text/javascript\" &gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"/myapp/app/controller/ProfileController.js?_debugResources=y&amp;n=1336614540164\" type=\"text/javascript\" &gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n  \n\n ... \n\n Being new to Grails, it is a very welcome fact that one can put executable code within a config file! \n", "last_activity_date": "04/09/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/10/2012", "votes_count": 9, "last_edit_date": "04/09/2013", "id": "32", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Resources Plugin -- How To include all contents in a directory?", "parent_id": "10520693", "comment_count": 3, "score": 8, "last_editor_user_id": "20774", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John Gordon", "owner_user_id": "412099"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": "gggggg 777777 tttttt  Alright, you need to read how  cin  and  cout  works first.  \n\n The solution to your problem will be  \n\n  1) Declare a single string variable eg: var_input\n2) Take input only once (using cin&gt;&gt;var_input)\n3) Check if the string is a number or a word taking help from Link One\n  \n\n Link One:\n How to determine if a string is a number with C++?   \n", "last_activity_date": "07/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/17/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "33", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "checking input type and work according to that", "parent_id": "11517823", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andy Stow Away", "owner_user_id": "1517037"},{"body": "gggggg 777777 tttttt  If you are using the same class for all views this is expected behavior, since splitter wires all views to the same document object. I presume that you are use document object for drawing data storage. \n\n UpdateAllViews is used for to update views if data in the document change. Each view then uses document\u2019s data to render different visual interpretation of this data. Hence each view would be a different type (represented by different classes) knowing how to visualize data. \n\n  For example:  document is used to store number array. Three views are showing those numbers as decimal, hex and binary representation.\nIf one number is changed, all views are notify to update own representation. \n\n In your case working solution would be to move drawing data to the view rather than the document. Most likely your application does not need a document at all. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/10/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "34", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "MFC Application Updating Only Current View", "parent_id": "10514942", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "JohnCz", "owner_user_id": "1364377"},{"body": "gggggg 777777 tttttt  you can implement this appid into your code and then run it...\nonly this way to see your app page....\nor you can use this URL https://www.facebook.com/apps/application.php?id=[Application ID] but this URL gives you only the app name... \n", "last_activity_date": "05/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/10/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "35", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to see Facebook app by it&#39s Facebook APP_ID?", "parent_id": "10528639", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Gaurav Agrawal", "owner_user_id": "807072"},{"body": "hhhhhh 888888 ssssss  You need to join  employees_tasks  to your query a second time: \n\n  SELECT employees.id, employees.name\nFROM employees\n  INNER JOIN employees_tasks AS et1 ON employees.id = et1.employee_id\n  INNER JOIN employees_tasks AS et2 ON employees.id = et2.employee_id\n  INNER JOIN tasks AS t1 ON et1.task_id = t1.id AND t1.name = &#39Programming&#39\n  INNER JOIN tasks AS t2 ON et2.task_id = t2.id AND t2.name = &#39Support&#39\n  \n\n \n\n  UPDATE  \n\n Alternatively, if you filter your results for only the tasks of interest, you can  GROUP BY  employee and only return those who have the desired task count: \n\n  SELECT   employees.id, employees.name\nFROM     employees\n  INNER JOIN employees_tasks ON employees_tasks.employee_id = employees.id\n  INNER JOIN tasks           ON employees_tasks.task_id     = tasks.id\nWHERE    tasks.name IN (&#39Programming&#39, &#39Support&#39)\nGROUP BY employees.id, employees.name\nHAVING   COUNT(DISTINCT tasks.id) = 2\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/10/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "05/10/2012", "id": "36", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "SQL SELECT query with multiple conditions", "parent_id": "10533273", "comment_count": 3, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "623041", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "eggyal", "owner_user_id": "623041"},{"body": "hhhhhh 888888 ssssss  You end up with an  IQueryable&lt;anonymoustype&gt;  with your current query. Since they&#39re anonymous types they&#39re readonly and can&#39t be changed anyway. \n\n Your best option, especially if you intend to have more complex manipulations that can&#39t be done in the query by the database, is to use a class instead. You&#39ll also want to add a  ToList()  at the end of your query so you end up with a  List&lt;YourClass&gt;  and can then loop over it as you usually would and change the objects. \n\n So make a class that has all your properties, for example  MasterQuote , and use that in your query instead: \n\n  var query = from x in cqsDC.MasterQuoteRecs\n                where x.CustomerNumber == accountNumber &amp;&amp; x.DateCreated &gt; DateTime.Now.AddDays(howfar)\n                orderby x.DateCreated descending\n                select new MasterQuote\n                \\{\n                    Customer = x.customername,\n                    Order = x.OrderReserveNumber,\n                    Quote = x.Quote,\n                    Date = Convert.ToDateTime(x.DateCreated).ToShortDateString(),\n                    Project = x.ProjectName,\n                    Total = x.Cost,\n                    Status = x.QuoteStatus\n                \\};\n\nvar orderList = query.ToList();\n\nforeach (var item in orderList)\n\\{\n    if (item.OrderReserveNumber &gt; 0)\n    \\{\n        item.Quote = \"\";\n    \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n Your  MasterQuote  class would look something like: \n\n  public class MasterQuote\n\\{\n    public string Customer \\{ get; set; \\}\n    public int Order \\{ get; set; \\}\n    // and so on\n\\}\n  \n\n Of course for your given example you could probably accomplish the Quote manipulation in your query as  seth mentioned . \n", "last_activity_date": "05/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/10/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "05/10/2012", "id": "37", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Modifying Linq Results", "parent_id": "10538395", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "59111", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Ahmad Mageed", "owner_user_id": "59111"},{"body": "hhhhhh 888888 ssssss  You can create a .csv file.  This is quick and easy, and makes it possible to open it in excel. \n\n This post relates to yours: \n\n  Convert DataTable to CSV stream  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/11/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "38", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Inserting data into an excel sheet from a DataTable", "parent_id": "10547619", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "soberga", "owner_user_id": "919130"},{"body": "hhhhhh 888888 ssssss  As far as i know, in the viewcontroller associated to the 