curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": "jjjjjj 101010101010 qqqqqq  Another use of delegates: \n\n Without the presence of delegates, only the class defining your  private  methods would be able to call those methods. With wrapping of methods inside a delegate, you could pass your delegate instance to other classes and let them invoke the delegate (as a callback) with the proper parameters and that would eventually call your actual private method within the defining class. \n\n \n\n  For Example :  \n\n  namespace DelegatesSample\n\\{\n    public delegate void privateCallbackDelegate(string param1, int param2);\n    public class A\n    \\{\n        private void DelegatedMehod(string param1, int param2)\n        \\{\n            //Code for some action\n        \\}\n\n        private void CallBusinessClass()\n        \\{\n            privateCallBackDelegate del = new privateCallBackDelegate(DelegateMethod);\n\n            B b = new B();\n            b.InvokeBusinessMethod(del);\n        \\}\n    \\}\n\n    public class B\n    \\{        \n        public void InvokeBusinessMethod(privateCallbackDelegate d)\n        \\{\n            //Do Some calculations and when finished, call the callback delegate\n            d(\"Done\", result); //or d.Invoke or d.BeginInvoke\n        \\}\n\n    \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n \n\n In general MSDN has following to say at  This article  : \n\n  Delegates are useful when:  \n\n \n A single method is being called. \n A class may want to have multiple implementations of the method specification. \n It is desirable to allow using a static method to implement the specification. \n An event-like design pattern is desired (for more information, see the Events Tutorial). \n The caller has no need to know or obtain the object that the method is defined on. \n The provider of the implementation wants to \"hand out\" the implementation of the specification to only a few select components. \n Easy composition is desired. \n \n", "last_activity_date": "05/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/22/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "05/22/2012", "id": "50", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Delegate Methods vs General Methods", "parent_id": "10707000", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1118933", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "VS1", "owner_user_id": "885920"},{"body": "kkkkkk 111111111111 pppppp  If you need to use cscript this is IMHO a cool solution \n\n  Const HIDDEN_WINDOW = 0\n\nstrComputer = \".\"\n\nSet objWMIService = GetObject(\"winmgmts:E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39\" &amp; strComputer &amp; \"E&#39\\\\&#39rootE&#39\\\\&#39cimv2\")\n\nSet objStartup = objWMIService.Get(\"Win32_ProcessStartup\")\nSet objConfig = objStartup.SpawnInstance_\nobjConfig.ShowWindow = HIDDEN_WINDOW\n\nSet objProcess = GetObject(\"winmgmts:E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39\" &amp; strComputer &amp; \"E&#39\\\\&#39rootE&#39\\\\&#39cimv2:Win32_Process\")\n\nobjProcess.Create \"Cscript.exe h:E&#39\\\\&#39ScriptE&#39\\\\&#39Test1.vbs\", null, objConfig, intProcessID\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/23/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "51", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "cscript.exe opens a window", "parent_id": "10716682", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "peter", "owner_user_id": "923315"},{"body": "kkkkkk 111111111111 pppppp  \n   Is it the right way of doing it? \n \n\n Absolutely; this is actually no different from widgets the live in the  com.google.gwt.user.User  module.\n(provided  inherits  means  &lt;inherits/&gt; , and putting the GWT-Toolbox JAR in the classpath) \n\n \n   Where do I put my resources files, and how they will be packaged in the GWT-apps ? \n \n\n You can either put them as simple resources in your JAR so that other modules can use them with  ClientBundle  by providing their path in  @Source . \nOr you an put them in a  public  subfolder (to be exact, the  public path  of your module, the subfolder name defaults to  public  but is actually configurable) of your module so they&#39re deployed side-by-side with the  *.cache.*  compiled files (this is how  themes  work in GWT). \n", "last_activity_date": "05/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/24/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "52", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Image resources in shared GWT modules (widgets like)", "parent_id": "10737674", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Thomas Broyer", "owner_user_id": "116472"},{"body": "kkkkkk 111111111111 pppppp  Use the work of hashes. Note there are some checks which could be done to immediately return a false, but I only show the meat of the process. Here it is in handy extension format: \n\n  Updated to Handle Order  \n\n  void Main()\n\\{\n    var first        = new List&lt;int&gt;() \\{ 1, 2, 5 \\};\n    var firstInOrder = new List&lt;int&gt;() \\{ 1, 2, 3 \\};\n    var second       = new List&lt;int&gt;() \\{ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 \\};\n    var third        = new List&lt;int&gt;() \\{ 1, 10, 20 \\};\n\n    Console.WriteLine( first.FoundInOther( second ) );        // False\n    Console.WriteLine( firstInOrder.FoundInOther( second ) ); // True\n    Console.WriteLine( first.FoundInOther( third ) );         // False\n\n\\}\n\npublic static class NumberExtensions\n\\{\n\n    public static bool FoundInOther( this IEnumerable&lt;int&gt; initial, IEnumerable&lt;int&gt; other )\n    \\{\n        int index = -1;\n        var asDictionary = other.ToDictionary( itm =&gt; itm, itm =&gt; ++index );\n\n        index = -1;\n        return initial.All( oth =&gt; asDictionary.ContainsKey( oth ) &amp;&amp; (asDictionary[oth] == ++index));\n    \\}\n\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/24/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "05/25/2012", "id": "53", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "LINQ List Contains Another List (Contiguous)", "parent_id": "10746517", "comment_count": 3, "score": -1, "last_editor_user_id": "285795", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "OmegaMan", "owner_user_id": "285795"},{"body": "kkkkkk 111111111111 pppppp  For others viewing this question and looking for a method, here&#39s what I&#39m using. \n\n  import imp\n\ndef find_dotted_module(name, path=None):\n    res = None\n    for x in name.split(&#39.&#39):\n        res = imp.find_module(x, path)\n        path = [module[1]]\n    return res\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/25/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "54", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Version of `imp.find_module` that works on dotted modules", "parent_id": "5795562", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Michael Waterfall", "owner_user_id": "106244"},{"body": "kkkkkk 111111111111 pppppp  \n Call ListView_GetItem to get the index of the item you want to watch \n Call ListView_EnsureVisible(hWnd, index_you_want_to_watch, TRUE) every time you insert a new row. \n \n", "last_activ