curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": "llllll 121212121212 oooooo  I agree with dystroy; Normally the local storing is harmless if done the right way. Storing  MASSIVE  amounts of data in the browser on the other hand is quite discouraged. It won&#39t slow down the browser performance overall but will slow down the web app using it (as far as I know, Chrome fetches the local storage values dynamically when the &#39owner app&#39 is called). \n", "last_activity_date": "05/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/28/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "57", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "HTML5 local storage and impact/load on browsers", "parent_id": "10780012", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "zakelfassi", "owner_user_id": "1421039"},{"body": "llllll 121212121212 oooooo  In the vector version your data is initialized to zero. In the  new  version it&#39s uninitialized, so different work might be done. \n\n Did you run multiple times, in different orders? \n", "last_activity_date": "07/14/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/14/2011", "votes_count": 6, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "58", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "vector&lt;double&gt; faster than double*: why?", "parent_id": "6698831", "comment_count": 10, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mark B", "owner_user_id": "251738"},{"body": "llllll 121212121212 oooooo  I&#39ve only used   exec()   or   system()   \n\n They&#39re always tricky and tend not to behave as expected. \n\n I would start off with \n\n  ini_set(\"display_errors\", 1);\n\nexec(&#39/var/cpanel/userdata/account/mdssl clone domain.com user.domain.com&#39, $output);\n\nvar_dump($output);\n  \n\n See what the output says or if a PHP error is occurring. \n\n You may also need to escape out of the current directory of whatever default you&#39re in with  ../  and make sure  apache  user has access to mdssl (or whatever user your system uses).  You may need to  sudo  it. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/30/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/30/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "59", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Using PHP to execute ssh/command line properly", "parent_id": "10746720", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Steve Robbins", "owner_user_id": "763468"},{"body": "llllll 121212121212 oooooo  It&#39s the shell that removes the quotes. If you want the shell to pass the quotes to you, you have to escape them: \n\n  $ ./my-program E&#39\\\\&#39\"helloE&#39\\\\&#39 worldE&#39\\\\&#39\"\n  \n\n Note that I escape the space as well, to make it one argument. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/31/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/31/2012", "votes_count": 8, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "60", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to prevent losing double quotes in argv?", "parent_id": "10830418", "comment_count": 6, "score": 8, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Joachim Pileborg", "owner_user_id": "440558"},{"body": "mmmmmm 131313131313 nnnnnn  What I found was that my web.config file either had an error in it or was missing. When this is the case, app_offline.htm does not get processed. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/31/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/31/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "61", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What are possible causes for App_Offline.htm not bringing the site down?", "parent_id": "3545359", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "GolfARama", "owner_user_id": "988530"},{"body": "mmmmmm 131313131313 nnnnnn  Everything is unlimited in my HostGator account. Why not just move to other hosting company? \n\n Also, if you have some client issues ~>  Try Google&#39s Picasa API:  \n\n  https://developers.google.com/picasa-web/  \n\n Regards,\nEliad \n", "last_activity_date": "05/31/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/31/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "62", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is it legitimate to use dropbox as file storage for my site?", "parent_id": "10838988", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Eliad Moshe", "owner_user_id": "1429276"},{"body": "mmmmmm 131313131313 nnnnnn  You could use  lookups which span relationships  \n\n  import operator\ninstances = \\{ &#391&#39:10, &#392&#39:20, &#393&#39:30 \\}\n# note the &#39b__&#39\nqset = reduce(operator.or_, (Q(b__content_type=int(x), b__object_id=y)\n                             for x,y in instances.iteritems()))\nqs = A.objects.filter(qset)\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/02/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "63", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "select_related() with filter() + Q()", "parent_id": "10848671", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "okm", "owner_user_id": "165603"},{"body": "mmmmmm 131313131313 nnnnnn  You can&#39t, not enough data.  Almost all 8bpp pixel formats are indexed formats.  They use a color table that stores the actual RGB color, the byte at the pixel location is an index into that table.  The table contains 256 entries. \n\n You&#39ll also need a pointer to the color table. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/03/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "64", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to read an 8bit bitmap&#39s pixel colour and postion from byte array", "parent_id": "10871879", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Hans Passant", "owner_user_id": "17034"},{"body": "mmmmmm 131313131313 nnnnnn  Here is my solution adapted from an  old another  to a similar question (simply transpose rows/columns): \n\n  %# input cell arrays\na = \\{&#39A&#39, &#39B&#39, &#39C&#39 ; 1, 1, 1; 2, 2, 2 \\};\nb = \\{&#39C&#39, &#39D 3, 3; 4, 4\\};\n\n%# transpose rows/columns\na = a b = b\n\n%# get all key values, and convert them to indices starting at 1\n[allKeys,~,ind] = unique( [a(:,1);b(:,1)] );\nindA = ind(1:size(a,1));\nindB = ind(size(a,1)+1:end);\n\n%# merge the two datasets (key,value1,value2)\nc = cell(numel(allKeys), size(a,2)+size(b,2)-1);\nc(:) = \\{NaN\\};                         %# fill with NaNs\nc(:,1) = allKeys;                     %# available keys from both\nc(indA,2:size(a,2)) = a(:,2:end);     %# insert 1st dataset values\nc(indB,size(a,2)+1:end) = b(:,2:end); %# insert 2nd dataset values\n  \n\n Here is the result (transposed to match original orientation): \n\n  &gt;&gt; c&#39\nans = \n    &#39A&#39      &#39B&#39      &#39C&#39    &#39D&#39  \n    [  1]    [  1]    [1]    [NaN]\n    [  2]    [  2]    [2]    [NaN]\n    [NaN]    [NaN]    [3]    [  3]\n    [NaN]    [NaN]    [4]    [  4]\n  \n\n \n\n Also here is the solution using the  DATASET  class from the Statistics Toolbox: \n\n  aa = dataset([cell2mat(a(2:end,:)) a(1,:)])\nbb = dataset([cell2mat(b(2:end,:)) b(1,:)])\ncc = join(aa,bb, &#39Keys&#39,\\{&#39C&#39\\}, &#39type&#39,&#39fullouter&#39, &#39MergeKeys&#39,true)\n  \n\n with \n\n  cc = \n    A      B      C    D  \n      1      1    1    NaN\n      2      2    2    NaN\n    NaN    NaN    3      3\n    NaN    NaN    4      4\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/04/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "65", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Joining data from different cell arrays in Matlab", "parent_id": "10877772", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Amro", "owner_user_id": "97160"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " You could use something like: \n\n  public static IEnumerable&lt;int&gt; GetIndices&lt;T&gt;(this IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; items, Func&lt;T, bool&gt; predicate)\n\\{\n    return items.Select( (item, index) =&gt; new \\{ Item = item, Index = index \\})\n                     .Where(p =&gt; predicate(p.Item))\n                     .Select(p =&gt; p.Index);\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/04/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "06/04/2012", "id": "66", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Find the position of a List Item in a List based upon specifice criteria using LINQ", "parent_id": "10887290", "comment_count": 0, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "68015", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Reed Copsey", "owner_user_id": "65358"},{"body": " I don&#39t think that you can easily pack the libraries into the dist-package. I see some workaroauns \n\n \n Rename them dll.jar or so.jar so they would be part of the dist-package.  \n Create your own sbt-task which do the packaging for you. \n Pack the dll/so in a separate zip together with a special start-script which unpack the dist and copy the dll/so to the correct place.  \n \n\n Sorry this are only workarounds, but I fear there is no clean solution. You can create a ticket for that but I fear you must solve it your selves. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/06/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "67", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to include native librairies in Play2 project?", "parent_id": "10914984", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "niels", "owner_user_id": "432115"},{"body": " You want to implement  \n\n  protected void onPostExecute (Result result) \n  \n\n on your AsyncTask implementation.  The result parameter will be whatever you return from the doInBackground method. Since this runs in the UI thread you can modify the UI how you want at that time. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/06/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "68", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Android Static functions", "parent_id": "10883383", "comment_count": 5, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "NKijak", "owner_user_id": "258676"},{"body": " Looks like your Customer hasmany association is assigning Appointments when it should be appointment which is the name of that model.  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/22/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/19/2011", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "08/22/2011", "id": "69", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Problem displaying nested model data in Sencha Touch XTemplate", "parent_id": "6222071", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "27615", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John Bond", "owner_user_id": "247117"},{"body": " I have just the solution :) \n\n  &lt;html&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button onclick=\"confirmNav() ? (doubleConfirmNav() ? navigate() : cancelled() ): cancelled();\"&gt;Contact Us&lt;/button&gt;\n\n\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;\n\nfunction confirmNav() \\{\n    var r=confirm(\"Do you really want to navigate to &#39Contact Us&#39?\");\n    if (r==true) \\{\n      return true;\n    \\} else \\{\n      return false;\n    \\}\n\\}\n\nfunction doubleConfirmNav() \\{\n    var r=confirm(\"Are you 100% sure?\");\n    if (r==true) \\{\n      return true;\n    \\} else \\{\n      return false;\n    \\}\n\\}\n\nfunction cancelled() \\{\n    alert(\"cancelling navigation\");   \n\\}\n\nfunction navigate() \\{\n    // purposely delay the redirect to give the image of a high traffic site\n     setTimeout(function() \\{   \n         window.location = \"contact_us.php\";\n     \\}, 5000);   \n \\}\n\n&lt;/script&gt;\n\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/07/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "06/07/2012", "id": "70", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Navigating pages in php", "parent_id": "10934975", "comment_count": 2, "score": -1, "last_editor_user_id": "403682", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Kenny Cason", "owner_user_id": "403682"},{"body": " The documentation contradicts itself (my bold): \n\n \n   The system keeps a cached version of the most recent  registry file mapping  to improve performance. If all parameters are NULL, the function flushes the cache. While the system is editing the  cached version of the file , processes that edit the file itself will use the original file until the cache has been cleared. \n \n\n Is Windows caching the mapping or a file (what file)?  But the comment in the sample code makes it clear: \n\n  // Force the system to read the mapping into shared memory \n// so that future invocations of the application will see it \n// without the user having to reboot the system\n  \n\n It is the registry file  mapping  that is cached.  If you alter the mapping in the registry then you need to tell Windows to refresh its cache. \n\n This is also consistent with usage of the API in Windows 3.1, where you didn&#39t need to flush anything.  It&#39s unlikely that Windows would fundamentally change the usage of the API. \n\n To double-check, I called  WritePrivateProfileString  while running  Process Monitor .  As expected, Windows opens the INI file, updates it and closes it again. \n\n No flushing required. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/07/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "71", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Does Windows NT cache or flush INI-file writings?", "parent_id": "10912352", "comment_count": 8, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "arx", "owner_user_id": "292432"},{"body": " I&#39ve just fixed such issue for myself. \n\n Note, that you need to put this code inside  parent in Android Manifest.xml file: \n\n      &lt;receiver\n        android:name=\".ScreenLockerDeviceAdminReceiver\"\n        android:permission=\"android.permission.BIND_DEVICE_ADMIN\" &gt;\n        &lt;meta-data\n            android:name=\"android.app.device_admin\"\n            android:resource=\"@xml/device_admin_policies\" /&gt;\n\n        &lt;intent-filter&gt;\n            &lt;action android:name=\"android.app.action.DEVICE_ADMIN_ENABLED\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/intent-filter&gt;\n    &lt;/receiver&gt;\n  \n\n and it works :) \n", "last_activity_date": "06/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/07/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "72", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Run intent DevicePolicyManager.ACTION_ADD_DEVICE_ADMIN from a service", "parent_id": "8686033", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "ViliusK", "owner_user_id": "517381"},{"body": " If you&#39re targeting the web player, no. Web player builds run in a sandbox and cannot load external code, so with the possible exception of writing a Lua interpreter in C# (!), you&#39re out of luck. \n\n If you&#39re targeting a desktop build or mobile device, then you can include  external plugins  and call out to them through scripts. This means you can import Lua and tell it to run your Lua script(s). \n\n However, this may still be more trouble than it&#39s worth, since you&#39ll have to load and initialize the Lua runtime yourself, and therefore you might be better off just rewriting the code. \n\n Note that for desktop platforms, a Pro license is required. For mobile platforms (iOS/Android), you may need to jump through some hoops to actually have your Lua script files available to load into the Lua runtime. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/07/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "73", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is possible to use lua code in Unity3D", "parent_id": "10940715", "comment_count": 1, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Michael Madsen", "owner_user_id": "27528"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " It looks to me like it&#39s because you are instantiating your TabListener every time... so the system is recreating your fragment from the savedInstanceState and then you are doing it again in your onCreate. \n\n You should wrap that in a  if(savedInstanceState == null)  so it only fires if there is no savedInstanceState. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/11/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "74", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Fragment onCreateView and onActivityCreated called twice", "parent_id": "10983396", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Barak", "owner_user_id": "1105376"},{"body": " I think you are right. You really only have 2 options: \n\n \n Manually create an array (unless someone else has already done the leg work for you somewhere..) which holds the Twitter API time_zone strings and indices and the PHP equivalent as values, or \n Use a simple JavaScript to modify the standardised time string on the client end. \n \n\n I know what I&#39d prefer. \n\n The second answer on this post has a nice example for the javascript \n Parsing Twitter API Datestamp  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/13/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/13/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "75", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Twitter API - Determining local time in PHP", "parent_id": "10981443", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John David Ravenscroft", "owner_user_id": "1412863"},{"body": " If you know what your column data will end in, then this is a surefire way to do it: \n\n  sed &#39s|E&#39\\\\&#39(.*[a-zA-Z0-9]E&#39\\\\&#39) *|E&#39\\\\&#391|g&#39  \n\n The character class would be where you put whatever your data will end in.   \n\n Otherwise, if you know more than one space is not going to come in your fields, then you could use what user1464130 gave you. \n\n If this doesn&#39t solve your problem, then get back to me. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/27/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "76", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Removing spaces from columns of a CSV file in bash", "parent_id": "11228691", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "twmb", "owner_user_id": "884347"},{"body": " Another possible solution is that the firewall between you and the Oracle database thinks your connection is dead and closes it underneath you. You will only find out when you try to execute a query and get the ORA-12571 error. \n\n This is caused by having connections open for a long time with no activity. \n\n The solution is to add the SQLNET.EXPIRE_TIME to the sqlnet.ora file on the server and set it to some interval (10). This will cause the connections to be pinged every 10 minutes to ensure they are still alive. \n\n The result of this is that your firewall will see network activity and not close the connection. \n\n  SQLNET.EXPIRE_TIME=10\n  \n\n  ORA-12571: TNS:packet writer failure - One of the hardest problems I&#39ve had to resolve  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/13/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/13/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "77", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ORA-12571: TNS:packet writer failure with ASP.NET", "parent_id": "7151175", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "BigTuna", "owner_user_id": "611610"},{"body": " Thanks for the suggestions. They guided me here.  \n\n This is almost same as other answers, just a bit simplified. \n\n To summarize, I need to compare the input string with a set of 20 strings and \n\n if they match, do something. Else, do something else. \n\n Static set of strings to which input needs to be compared : \nis on,is not on,is before,is after, etc 20 entries \n\n I created an enum \n\n  public enum dateRules\n\\{\n   is_on\n   ,is_not_on\n   ,is_before\n   ,is_after\n   .\n   .\n   .\n\\}\n  \n\n and switching on formatted value of input \n\n  if(isARule(in = input.replace(\" \",\"_\"))\n\\{\n   switch(dateRule.valueOf(in))\n   \\{\n      case is_on,\n      case is_not_on,\n      case is_before, ...\n   \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n I copied the formatted value of &#39input&#39 to &#39in&#39 so that I can reuse input without another replace of &#39_&#39 with &#39 &#39. \n\n  private static boolean isARule(String value)\n  \\{\n    for(dateRule rule : dateRule.values())\n    \\{\n      if(rule.toString().equals(value))\n      \\{\n        return true;\n      \\}\n    \\}\n    return false;\n  \\}\n  \n\n Problem solved.  \n\n Reference :  http://stackoverflow.com/a/4936895/1297564  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/15/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "06/15/2012", "id": "78", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "complex if( ) or enum?", "parent_id": "11032255", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1297564", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "1234", "owner_user_id": "1297564"},{"body": " For the proxy solution you suggest, I recommend  Charles . In Charles you can  rewrite  both the request and the response from the server. \n\n \n   The Rewrite tool enables you to create rules that modify requests and responses as they pass through Charles. Rules such as adding or changing a header or search and replace some text in the response body. \n \n", "last_activity_date": "06/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/15/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "79", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to make session time out from client side", "parent_id": "3475827", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Langtind", "owner_user_id": "921183"},{"body": " Don&#39t use   __proto__  , it&#39s a Mozilla proprietary property (copied by a few others) and is deprecated. Assign to construtor.prototpye. \n\n The line: \n\n  &gt; __proto__:subSection;\n  \n\n is not assigning anything to anything, it is a label ( __proto__ ) followed by a statement  subSection  that is a reference to the subSection function that is not assigned to anything. \n\n You seem not to understand prototype inheritance, try Douglas Crockford&#39s  Prototypal Inheritance in JavaScript  \n\n The following might be something like what you are trying to do, there must be a thousand similar questions here: \n\n  function SubSection(pattern) \\{\n    this.pattern = pattern;\n    this.total = 0;\n    this.distance=0;\n\\}\n\n// Add a method to subSection.prototype\nSubSection.prototype.getDistance = function() \\{\n  return this.distance;\n\\}\n\nfunction Enhancer(pattern) \\{\n    this.pattern = pattern;\n\\}\n\n// To make enhancer inherit from subSection, make its prototype\n// an instance of subSection\nEnhancer.prototype = new SubSection();\n\nvar a = new Enhancer(\"aaa\");\n\ndocument.write(a.getDistance()); // 0\n  \n\n Oh, and by convention, constructor names start with a capital letter. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/18/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/18/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "06/18/2012", "id": "80", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "simple javascript delegation using __proto__", "parent_id": "11075847", "comment_count": 3, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "257182", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "RobG", "owner_user_id": "257182"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Your issue here in your first example is that a  for  loop doesn&#39t give indices, it gives the values from the list. This means that your example doesn&#39t really make any sense at all. \n\n The second example takes the second item in the row, splits it on commas (which should all be dealt with by the  csv  module anyway) and then takes the second through second to last item of the resulting list. As I imagine there were no commas in the value this will take  [1:-1]  of a list with one element, returning an empty list. I can&#39t really understand the intent here. You also then only store the data from the last row (overwriting  float_list  each time). You appear to be second-guessing the  csv  module and making this a lot harder than it is. \n\n You need to stop overcomplicating it: \n\n  with open(&#39unemp.csv&#39, &#39rb&#39) as data:\n    rows = csv.reader(data)\n    next(rows) #Skip the headers.\n    floats = [[float(item) for number, item in enumerate(row) if item and (1 &lt;= number &lt;= 12)] for row in rows]\n\nprint(floats)\n  \n\n To explain, first we use the  with  statement to open the file in a readable and pythonic way (which ensures the file is closed properly, even on exceptions). We then make a  csv.reader  to get our data from the CSV file. We skip the headers by advancing the iterator by one, meaning we start on the second row. We then use a list comprehension to produce a new list from the iterator, containing another list comprehension generating the floats of the values if those values exist, and are not in the  Year  or  Annual  column. To do this we use the  enumerate()  builtin to get the number of the column we are in, then do a check to ensure it&#39s not  0  ( Year ) or  13  ( Annual ). \n\n As J.F.Sebastian points out in the comments, the best solution is to allow the  csv  module to handle dealing with the numbers for you, by adding the named argument  quoting  to the  csv.reader()  call with the value  csv.QUOTE_NONNUMERIC . E.g: \n\n  with open(&#39unemp.csv&#39, &#39rb&#39) as data:\n    rows = csv.reader(data, quoting=csv.QUOTE_NONNUMERIC)\n    next(rows) #Skip the headers.\n    floats = [[item for number, item in enumerate(row) if item and (1 &lt;= number &lt;= 12)] for row in rows]\n\nprint(floats)\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/18/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/18/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "06/18/2012", "id": "81", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "converting a list of strings(csv) to a list of floats", "parent_id": "11076138", "comment_count": 9, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "722121", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Lattyware", "owner_user_id": "722121"},{"body": " Parag, congratulations on a good self-answer! \n\n Although this may not be any better, for your interest, here is another solution from a different perspective. Building on Empo&#39s solution, it takes a functional view, asking the question, what is the output expressed as a function of input, rather than a procedural (for-each, call-template etc.) view. \n\n  &lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\" standalone=\"no\" ?&gt;\n&lt;xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform\"  xmlns:plm=\"http://www.tcxml.org/Schemas/TCXMLSchema\" version=\"1.0\"&gt;\n&lt;xsl:output method=\"xml\" indent=\"yes\" omit-xml-declaration=\"yes\"/&gt;\n\n&lt;xsl:template match=\"node()|@*\"&gt;\n &lt;xsl:copy&gt;\n  &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=\"node()|@*\"/&gt;\n &lt;/xsl:copy&gt;\n&lt;/xsl:template&gt;\n\n&lt;xsl:template match=\"plm:DrawingSheet\"&gt;\n &lt;xsl:variable name=\"Sec_Id\" select=\"plm:GSIdentity/@elemId\" /&gt;\n &lt;xsl:variable name=\"Pri_id\" select=\"\n    substring(\n       ../plm:IMAN_Drawing[$Sec_Id=substring(@secondary_object,2)]\n       /@primary_object,2)\" /&gt;\n &lt;xsl:copy&gt;\n  &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=\"@*\"/&gt;\n   &lt;xsl:attribute name=\"object_name\"&gt;\n     &lt;xsl:value-of select=\"concat(\n        ../plm:UGPART[plm:GSIdentity/@elemId=$Pri_id]/@object_name,\n       &#39_&#39,\n       @object_name)\" /&gt; \n   &lt;/xsl:attribute&gt;\n  &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=\"node()\"/&gt;\n &lt;/xsl:copy&gt;  \n&lt;/xsl:template&gt;\n\n&lt;/xsl:stylesheet&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/19/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "82", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "change xml attributes based on condition via XSLT", "parent_id": "11079399", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sean B. Durkin", "owner_user_id": "10823"},{"body": " This doesn&#39t answer your question, but it&#39s a different way to edit with gvim from the context menu. \n\n Create a .reg file with the contents below (adjusting your path to gvim.exe) and execute it.  Then whenever you right-click on a file in explorer you will have an \"Open with GVIM\" option. \n\n  REGEDIT4 \n\n[HKEY_CLASSES_ROOTE&#39\\\\&#39UnknownE&#39\\\\&#39shell] \n@=\"Open with GVIM\" \n\n[HKEY_CURRENT_USERE&#39\\\\&#39SOFTWAREE&#39\\\\&#39ClassesE&#39\\\\&#39*E&#39\\\\&#39shell] \n\n[HKEY_CURRENT_USERE&#39\\\\&#39SOFTWAREE&#39\\\\&#39ClassesE&#39\\\\&#39*E&#39\\\\&#39shellE&#39\\\\&#39Open with &amp;GVim] \n@=\"Open with GVIM\" \n\n[HKEY_CURRENT_USERE&#39\\\\&#39SOFTWAREE&#39\\\\&#39ClassesE&#39\\\\&#39*E&#39\\\\&#39shellE&#39\\\\&#39Open with &amp;GVimE&#39\\\\&#39command] \n@=\"C:E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39VimE&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39gvim.exe E&#39\\\\&#39\"%1E&#39\\\\&#39\"\"\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/20/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "83", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "&quot;Registering&quot; GVim in Windows XP", "parent_id": "11127399", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "TimK", "owner_user_id": "708333"},{"body": " This might be because proguard obfuscates your code and if you use some external libraries you should make the obfuscation rules accordingly... you should check this  http://developer.android.com/guide/developing/tools/proguard.html  \n\n  EDIT:  \n\n The rules I have in my project are: \n\n  -libraryjars library_used.jar\n  \n\n And also if you get some class not found exception then you might want to remove that class from the obfuscation process like this: \n\n  -keep public class org.package.YourClassHere \n  \n\n Note that I am not 100% if this is the best way to do this but at least it works :) \n", "last_activity_date": "06/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/21/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "06/21/2012", "id": "84", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Android application is not working properly when enable proguard", "parent_id": "11135055", "comment_count": 5, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "449310", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Cata", "owner_user_id": "449310"},{"body": " As a side note -- I&#39m not sure that I believe your bash array will group things the way you want it to ... for me, your quotations get stripped.   try: \n\n  GPPARS=( \"xlabel &#39Time&#39\" \"ylabel &#39value1&#39\" \"y2label &#39value2&#39\" \"format x &#39%H:%M&#39\")\n  \n\n instead.  (interior double quotes replaced with single quotes) \n\n This is a tricky one -- It&#39s a good thing you&#39re using gnuplot 4.6, otherwise I&#39m not sure how to go about solving it.   (EDIT -- using gnuplot 4.4, you could use a combination of  word ,  words ,  if ,  reread ,  exists  and macros, but it&#39s quite a messy solution)  \n\n Note that what you have doesn&#39t work because it is akin to: \n\n  MYLABEL=&#39xlabel \"foo\"&#39\nset MYLABEL\n  \n\n Gnuplot doesn&#39t expand MYLABEL prior to doing the set command so that you can do things like: \n\n  MYLABEL=\"totally cool X label here!\"\nset xlabel MYLABEL\n  \n\n What you want  could  be accomplished using macros (but alas, not with iteration): \n\n  set macro \nMYLABEL=&#39xlabel \"foo\"&#39\nset @MYLABEL\n  \n\n But that doesn&#39t quite work here either because macro expansion happens before anything else (e.g. function evaluation).  What you need here is gnuplot&#39s more general iteration introduced in 4.6 combined with  eval  \n\n  do for [ var in gpvars ] \\{\n    eval( &#39set &#39.replace(var,&#39#_#&#39,&#39 &#39) )\n\\}\n  \n\n  EDIT -- gnuplot 4.2+ solution  \n\n  #top of script -- Nothing should go here.\nreplace(S,C,R)=(strstrt(S,C)) ? E&#39\\\\&#39\n     replace( S[:strstrt(S,C)-1].R.S[strstrt(S,C)+strlen(C):] ,C,R) : S\nif( ! exists(\"N\") ) N=1\nTODO=\"$\\{GPPARS_MOD[@]\\}\"\nset macro\ndo_set=replace(word(TODO,N),&#39#_#&#39,&#39 &#39)\nset @do_set\nN=N+1\nif( N &lt;= words(TODO) ) reread\n#rest of script here ...\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/21/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "06/22/2012", "id": "85", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "setting variables with gnuplot&#39s for cycle", "parent_id": "11138742", "comment_count": 6, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "748858", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "mgilson", "owner_user_id": "748858"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " These two approaches may solve your problem: \n\n \n  Put a dark rectangle behind your bitmap and set the Bitmap&#39s\nopacity.  \n  Use ColorFilter on your Paint when you draw the bitmap. To darken your bitmap use a semi-transparent black color  \n \n", "last_activity_date": "06/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/24/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "86", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "changing the intensity of lighten/darken on bitmaps using PorterDuffXfermode in the Android Paint class", "parent_id": "11174583", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "K_Anas", "owner_user_id": "1327899"},{"body": " try: \n\n  $(document).ready(function() \\{\n  $(\"input[type=&#39submit&#39]\").click(function() \\{\n    $(this).closest(&#39form&#39).submit(function (evt) \\{\n           //evt.preventDefault();\n           alert(1);\n           return false;\n    \\});\n  \\});\n\\});\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/24/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "06/24/2012", "id": "87", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "this input submit selector with closest form submit", "parent_id": "11175520", "comment_count": 3, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "350858", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sudhir", "owner_user_id": "350858"},{"body": " i use a JEditorPane for exact the same pupose. \nJust set the ContentType to \"text/html\" as you allready do and you are good to go.  \n\n To include some predefined stylesheets i use this code:  \n\n  editorPane.setContentType(\"text/html\");\nHTMLEditorKit kit = new HTMLEditorKit();\neditorPane.setEditorKit(kit);\nFile cssfile = new File(\"src/Assets/code.css\");\n\nStyleSheet styleSheet = kit.getStyleSheet();\nstyleSheet.importStyleSheet(cssfile.toURI().toURL());\n\neditorPane.setText(\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;\");\n  \n\n You can use setEditable(false) so the HTML cant be changed. \n\n Just tryed it with Netbeans 7.2 beta and it works the same way with an JTextPane. \n\n Here is some more Docu about it:\n http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/components/editorpane.html#recap  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/24/2012", "votes_count": 6, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "88", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "text/html in a jTextPane, NetBeans", "parent_id": "11177126", "comment_count": 4, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "C. Holzberger", "owner_user_id": "1186432"},{"body": " Going by the now-deleted comments to the question that the check is meant to be for the variables being  None  rather than being falsey, change  func  so that it handles the arguments being  None : \n\n  def func(a=None, b=None):\n   if a is None:\n      a = 0\n   if b is None:\n      b = 10\n  \n\n And then just call  func(a, b)  every time. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/25/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "89", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Pythonic solution for conditional arguments passing", "parent_id": "11185516", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "lvc", "owner_user_id": "779200"},{"body": " The initialization of the member variables of a class will happen in the order that you specify them in the class declaration. \n\n Note that gcc will warn (given -Wall) when the order in the initializer list does not correspond to the order of declaration of the member variables. The declaration order in the class is authoritative. \n\n \nclass A \\{\npublic:\n    A(std::istream const&);\n\\}\n\nclass B \\{\npublic:\n  B(std::istream const&);\n\\}\n\nclass MyClass \\{\n  std::istream is;\n  A a;\n  B b;\npublic:\n  MyClass() : is(\"path\"), a(is), b(is) \\{\n  \\}\n\\}\n \n", "last_activity_date": "07/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/05/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "90", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Constructor that depends on object not yet constructed", "parent_id": "11343702", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user52875", "owner_user_id": "52875"},{"body": " Using: \n\n  import java.util.regex.Matcher;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\nclass Main\n\\{\n  public static void main (String[] args) throws java.lang.Exception\n  \\{\n     String formula = \"BMI = ( Weight / ( Height * Height ) ) * 703\";\n     String pattern = \"(?:^|(?&lt;=[=+E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39-*/()]))E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39s*([a-z]+)E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39s*(?:$|(?=[=+E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39-*/()]))\";\n     Pattern p = Pattern.compile(pattern, Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE);\n     Matcher m = p.matcher(formula);\n     while(m.find()) \\{\n       System.out.println(m.group(1));\n     \\}\n  \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n you will get: \n\n  BMI\nWeight\nHeight\nHeight\n  \n\n So all you need to do after that is just  remove duplicates , which is a simple task. \n\n \n\n See and test the code  here . \n", "last_activity_date": "06/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/26/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "06/26/2012", "id": "91", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Java regex , matching variables in a math expression", "parent_id": "11199126", "comment_count": 8, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1215106", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "\u2126mega", "owner_user_id": "1215106"},{"body": " If you know that this collection only contains one value you could do it like this: \n\n  String result = null;\nCollection collection = (Collection)table.getValue();\nfor(Object o : collection) \\{\n   result = o.toString();\n   break;\n\\}\n  \n\n If the collection cannot contain more than one value, you could remove the  break  after  result = o.toString();  \n\n Hope that helps. \n\n \n\n  Edit : Modified, collection is now retrieved from table. Added cast to Collection and added break \n", "last_activity_date": "06/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/26/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "06/26/2012", "id": "92", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Getting the value of an object that is a collection", "parent_id": "11202288", "comment_count": 7, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "663130", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "pushy", "owner_user_id": "663130"},{"body": " Possible duplicate of  Python: Behaviour of increment and decrement operators . \n\n Although I cannot find documentation for the exact reasoning for the operator I&#39ll quote a portion from the accepted answer in the linked question that I believe is the case: \n\n \n   \n   Simpler language. ++ is nothing more than a synonym for += 1. It was    a shorthand invented because C compilers were stupid and didn&#39t\n  know    how to optimize a += 1 into the inc instruction most computers\n  have.    In this day of optimizing compilers and bytecode interpreted \n  languages, adding operators to a language to allow programmers to \n  optimize their code is usually frowned upon, especially in a language \n  like Python that is designed to be consistent and readable. \n   \n \n", "last_activity_date": "06/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/26/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "93", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "in python, ++x is correct syntax. What does &quot;++x&quot; mean?", "parent_id": "11209899", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "PenguinCoder", "owner_user_id": "1209423"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Your code blocks a ThreadPool thread for 5 seconds. If you execute this code for a large number of events you may exhaust all threadpool threads and effectively block your application until all the Sleep statements finish. \n\n Both the code samples execute using the default thread scheduler. The difference is that the second sample uses the TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning which instructs the scheduler to create new threads rather than wait for a pool thread. This may overcome the initial problem, it&#39s still not the right solution, as you are still wasting threads and may leave no thread available for other tasks.  \n\n A correct implementation is to use a TaskSource that will be signalled when a timer expires. This way you are not blocking any threads. \n\n C# 5 already supports this with the  Task.Delay  method. You can use this in .NET 4.0 if you use the  async targeting pack  for Visual Studio 2012 or the  Async v3 CTP  for 2010 \n\n You can also find a similar method in the ParallelExtensionExtras library. The  TaskFactory.StartNewDelayed  extension method works in almost the same way. The sample code  from Stephen Toub&#39s article  provides a simplified version: \n\n  public static Task StartNewDelayed(int millisecondsDelay, Action action) \n\\{ \n// Validate arguments \nif (millisecondsDelay &lt; 0) \n    throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(\"millisecondsDelay\"); \nif (action == null) throw new ArgumentNullException(\"action\"); \n\n// Create a trigger used to start the task \nvar tcs = new TaskCompletionSource&lt;object&gt;(); \n\n// Start a timer that will trigger it \nvar timer = new Timer( \n    _ =&gt; tcs.SetResult(null), null, millisecondsDelay, Timeout.Infinite); \n\n// Create and return a task that will be scheduled when the trigger fires. \nreturn tcs.Task.ContinueWith(_ =&gt; \n\\{\n    timer.Dispose();\n    action();\n\\}); \n\\}\n  \n\n Using the version from the ParallelExtensionsExtras you can rewrite your code as follows: \n\n  Task.Factory.StartNewDelayed(5000).ContinueWith(_ =&gt;\n\\{\n    lblStatus.Text = \"Done\";\n\\}, TaskScheduler.FromCurrentSynchronizationContext());\n  \n\n  EDIT:  \n\n It seems the actual code does not have a Thread.Sleep after all. It performs some heavy DB related operations. The effect is the same though. Starting a new task after each BindingSource event can lead to so many running tasks that the threadpool gets exhausted. \n\n One solution is again to use the TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning flag with the  TaskFactory.StartNew(Action,TaskCreationOptions)  override to instruct the scheduler to create more threads. \n\n An even better solution is to execute the database operations asynchronously, using the BeginExecuteXXX,EndExecuteXXX methods combined with  TaskFactory.FromAsync  to convert the asynchronous calls to tasks. This way the database operations will not block any threads at all. \n\n You could write something like this: \n\n  Task&lt;SqlDataReader&gt; task = Task&lt;SqlDataReader&gt;.Factory.FromAsync(\n    cmd.BeginExecuteReader(CommandBehavior.CloseConnection),\n    cmd.EndExecuteReader)\n.ContinueWith(reader=&gt;\n\\{\n    //do some processing\n    reader.Close();\n\\});\n.ContinueWith(_ =&gt; \n\\{\n    lblStatus.Text=\"Done\";\n\\},TaskScheduler.FromCurrentSynchronizationContext());\n  \n\n to read and process the data asynchronously and update the UI once processing finishes. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/27/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "06/27/2012", "id": "94", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Parallel Task blocks when run from BindingSource.PositionChanged", "parent_id": "11209893", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "134204", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Panagiotis Kanavos", "owner_user_id": "134204"},{"body": " use mysql_fetch_array() instead of mysql_fetch_assoc() \n\n the mysql_fetch_assoc() will return an associative array and only accessable via $row[&#39name&#39].\nWith mysql_fetch_array() you can fetch an associative array, a numeric array, or both. \n\n take a look here:  http://www.php.net/manual/en/function.mysql-fetch-array.php  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/28/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "95", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "PHP can&#39t print array elements without using print_r", "parent_id": "11248339", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Wolv3r", "owner_user_id": "1317864"},{"body": " If you drop the DLL you want the code to reference into the bin folder of the website, then open the web.config and locate the following section  configuration -&gt; system.web -&gt; compilation -&gt; assemblies . \n\n You need to add the display name of the assembly to that list - so that the compiler will reference that assembly during it&#39s late-bound build process. \n\n Now you should be able to use the stuff that&#39s in it on those pages. \n\n If you don&#39t the know the display name of the assembly (typically  yourassembly, version=*.*.*.*, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null  for culture-invariant, non-strong-named assemblies) you can open it in a tool like  ILSpy  (there are others, it&#39s just become my favourite) and it tells you when you select it in it&#39s UI: \n\n   \n\n  sorry for the poor highlighting - jerky hand following far too much coffee  \n\n If all the code in that assembly is in a single namespace, also, you can also add a default  using  to all the .cs or .aspx code in the project by adding that namespace to  configuration -&gt; system.web -&gt; pages -&gt; namespaces  - making it simpler to use that code in the pages. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/28/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "06/28/2012", "id": "96", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Getting C# to recognize a dll outside of Visual Studio", "parent_id": "11253267", "comment_count": 1, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "157701", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andras Zoltan", "owner_user_id": "157701"},{"body": " have you tried this way ? \n\n  private int move;\npublic void fight() throws InterruptedException\n\\{\n    final Random g = new Random();\n    runOnUiThread(new Runnable() \n    \\{\n        public void run() \\{\n            while(makeACondition) \\{\n            move = g.nextInt(8);\n\n            toggleButtonState(buttons[move]);\n          \\} \n       \\}\n   \\});\n\\}\n\nprivate void toggleButtonState(final Button button)\n\\{\n    new Handler().postDelayed(new Runnable() \\{\n\n        @Override\n        public void run() \\{\n            if(button.isEnabled())\n                button.setVisibility(View.GONE);\n            else \n                button.setVisibility(View.VISIBLE);\n\n        \\}\n    \\}, 5000);\n\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/29/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/29/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "97", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Make button appear and then disappear after a few seconds in Android", "parent_id": "11254876", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "sunil", "owner_user_id": "474193"},{"body": " It sounds like you need  KissFFT . Simple, easy to use, lightweight, written in C, quite efficient, free, doesn&#39t have all the baggage of the heavyweights like FFTW. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/19/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "98", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "FFT with Accelerometer Data", "parent_id": "11568583", "comment_count": 5, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Paul R", "owner_user_id": "253056"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I guess he&#39s referring to the following line: \n\n  import Prelude hiding ((.))\n  \n\n which disables the normal  (.)  operator for functional composition. Instead, another operator with the same name is used, probably imported from the utility module  T.T . This operator behaves like in OOP languages: \n\n  pretty_output solution = solution.elems.map(show).in_group_of(9)\n    .map(unwords).unlines\n  \n\n which (I think) would normally look like \n\n  pretty_output solution = (unlines . map unwords . in_group_of 9 . map show . elems) solution\n  \n\n That operator works the same like the   |&gt;   operator in F#: \n\n  (|&gt;) :: a -&gt; (a -&gt; b) -&gt; b\nx |&gt; f = f x\n  \n\n which is used to  pipe  a value through functions (and is more readable and better functional style, imo): \n\n  pretty_output solution = solution |&gt; elems |&gt; map show |&gt; in_group_of 9 |&gt; map unwords |&gt; unlines\n  \n\n  (|&gt;)  is also the same as  flip ($) . \n\n Edit: This \"hacked\" operator already exists in Haskell, somehow. The same composition behavior can be achieved by the left-to-right composition operator from   Control.Category  : \n\n  g x = x |&gt; (f1 &gt;&gt;&gt; f2 &gt;&gt;&gt; f3)\n  \n\n This pipes only functions, though, and is actually just  f &gt;&gt;&gt; g = g . f . \n", "last_activity_date": "08/26/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/29/2012", "votes_count": 6, "last_edit_date": "08/26/2013", "id": "99", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Haskell &quot;Dot Hack&quot;", "parent_id": "11258364", "comment_count": 1, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "1346276", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "phg", "owner_user_id": "1346276"},{"body": " After loading data, just add the following statement: \n\n  sampler.setInputFormat(data);\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "06/29/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/29/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "06/29/2012", "id": "100", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to use Weka Supervised Resample Filter in Java Code?", "parent_id": "4473058", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "463723", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "resay", "owner_user_id": "463723"},{"body": " EDIT: \n\n In Cocoa, afaik, each control has a kind of \"fixed\" event it responds to. To manage double clicks, you should override the methods  mouseUp  or  mouseDown , where you will get the information about the number of clicks. \n\n  - (void)mouseUp:(NSEvent*)event \\{\n    NSInteger count = [event clickCount];\n    &lt;do_something_depending_on:count];\n\\}\n  \n\n OLD ANSWER: \n\n You can define multiple IBActions associated to the same control by displaying the actions tab for your control in Interface Builder and then connecting the proper event type to your controller action. Have a look at the attached image, hope it makes clearer. It displays the events available for button. \n\n   \n", "last_activity_date": "06/30/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/30/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "06/30/2012", "id": "101", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How can I know which event caused the call to my IBAction?", "parent_id": "11273610", "comment_count": 3, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "671858", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "sergio", "owner_user_id": "671858"},{"body": " You can try running a second instance of the IDE in the debugger. \n\n \n Create an empty dll or package project. \n Open Run >  Parameters \n Set the host application to $(BDS)E&#39\\\\&#39binE&#39\\\\&#39BDS.exe \n \n\n Then just hit  F9  to run the second instance of the IDE in the debugger. After that just follow the steps to reproduce the problem and wait for the exception. If all goes well you&#39ll get a complete call stack to step through. \n\n Note: You may see various other exceptions occurring as the IDE loads. These are normal and can usually be ignored. \n\n Also you didn&#39t mention what version of Windows was on your old machine. If it was Windows XP Uwe could be right. XP was a little more lax on security by default than Vista or 7. The new default is to restrict write access to any folder under  Program Files . If that turns out to be the problem you can adjust the write permissions for $(BDS) for whatever user account you use for development. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/02/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "07/02/2012", "id": "102", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "New TFrame and TDataModule crashing Delphi IDE", "parent_id": "11294842", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "71200", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Kenneth Cochran", "owner_user_id": "71200"},{"body": " This is how you could do this.  \n\n  import sqlite3\n\ncon = sqlite3.connect(&#39database&#39)\ncur = con.Cursor()\n\ncur.execute(&#39select table1.column, table2.column, table3.column from table1, table2, table3&#39)\n# result should look like ((25, 30, 20), (30,)), if I remember correctly\nresults = cur.fetchall()\n\noutput = &#39E&#39\\\\&#39n&#39.join(&#39,&#39.join(str(i) for i in line) for line in results)\n  \n\n Note: this code is untested, written out of my head, but I hope you get the idea. \n\n \n\n  UPDATE:  apparently I made some mistakes in the script and somehow sql &#39magically&#39 pads the result (you might have guessed now that I&#39m not a sql guru :D). Another way to do it would be: \n\n  import sqlite3\nconn = sqlite3.connect(&#39database.db&#39)\n\ncur = conn.cursor()\n\ntables = (&#39table1&#39, &#39table2&#39, &#39table3&#39)\nresults = [list(cur.execute(&#39select column from %s&#39 % table)) for table in tables]\n\ndef try_list(lst, i):\n    try:\n        return lst[i]\n    except IndexError:\n        return (&#39&#39,)\n\nmaxlen = max(len(i) for i in results)\nresults2 = [[try_list(line, i) for line in results] for i in xrange(maxlen)]\n\noutput = &#39E&#39\\\\&#39n&#39.join(&#39,&#39.join(str(i[0]) for i in line) for line in results2)\nprint output\n  \n\n which produces \n\n  25,30,20\n30,,\n  \n\n This is probably an overcomplicated way to do it, but it is 0:30 right now for me, so I&#39m not on my best... \nAt least it gets the desired result. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/02/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "07/03/2012", "id": "103", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "don&#39t get duplicated values when exporting sqlite3 file to csv using python?", "parent_id": "11300146", "comment_count": 6, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "1248554", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "BrtH", "owner_user_id": "1248554"},{"body": " Seems you need a   trimRight   function. its not available until Javascript 1.8.1. Before that you can use prototyping techniques. \n\n   String.prototype.trimRight=function()\\{return this.replace(/E&#39\\\\&#39s+$/,&#39&#39);\\}\n // Now call it on any string.\n var a = \"a string \";\n a = a.trimRight();\n  \n\n See more on  How do I trim a string in javascript?  And the compatibility  list   \n", "last_activity_date": "07/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/03/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "104", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Javascript and regex: remove space after the last word in a string", "parent_id": "11306008", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "shiplu.mokadd.im", "owner_user_id": "376535"},{"body": " \n Right click on Project and choose Team ->  Share Project  \n Select a repository type(for your needs CVS)  \n  Create new/use existing repository location and do accoriding to a wizard \n\n  see this!   \n \n", "last_activity_date": "07/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/04/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "105", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to add new CVS in eclipse?", "parent_id": "11324211", "comment_count": 4, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "tostao", "owner_user_id": "865448"},{"body": " I&#39ve submitted an issue to request a feature in PlayMorphia to solve this problem: \n\n  https://github.com/greenlaw110/play-morphia/issues/94  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/19/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "106", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "In Play Morphia how do I manage updates?", "parent_id": "10663633", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "green", "owner_user_id": "391227"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Instead of returning the value of x from the function, you can assign the value of \n\n  position.coords.latitude\n  \n\n to a variable which can be accessed by the calling function. That way the assigned value to that variable will persist.\nSome thing like this:\n EDIT  \n\n  var b;\nfunction callingFunction()\\{\n    findLocation();\n    //your stuff\n\\}\nfunction floc(position)\\{\n    b = position.coords.longitude;\n\\}\nfunction findLocation()\\{\n    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(floc);\n\\}\n\ncallingFunction();\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/06/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "07/06/2012", "id": "107", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Using JavaScript with GWT to get user location, but variable does not get passed", "parent_id": "11355728", "comment_count": 3, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1065489", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Digvijay Yadav", "owner_user_id": "1065489"},{"body": " in FilderScript find variable m_ShowTTLB and  m_ShowTimestamp and set all to true.\nShow the result into Custom column \n\n      // Show the duration between the start of Request.Send and Response.Completed in Milliseconds\n    public static RulesOption(\"&amp;Show Time-to-Last-Byte\", \"Per&amp;formance\")\n    var m_ShowTTLB: boolean = true;\n\n    // Show the time of response completion\n    public static RulesOption(\"Show Response &amp;Timestamp\", \"Per&amp;formance\")\n    var m_ShowTimestamp: boolean = true;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/06/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "108", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to get the transfer time in a custom Fiddler inspector", "parent_id": "10437347", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Herv\u00e9C", "owner_user_id": "1171238"},{"body": " If values and keys won&#39t contain  \\}\\{ , you could simply add commas to make it valid JSON (and add square brackets to make it an array): \n\n  var json = &#39[&#39 + json.replace(/\\}\\{/g, &#39\\},\\{&#39) + &#39]\n  \n\n This would even work if you only get a single object as response. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/10/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "109", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Parsing stuck-together json in javascript", "parent_id": "11417817", "comment_count": 1, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Felix Kling", "owner_user_id": "218196"},{"body": " With appending a question mark to it you allow a type to be  nullable .\nIn your case, this means that MyValue can now be either: a valid double value or  null . \n\n For more information on this, check:  http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/1t3y8s4s(v=vs.80).aspx  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/06/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "110", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Differences between get set with question mark and without", "parent_id": "11364390", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Gerald Versluis", "owner_user_id": "1506387"},{"body": "  -XX:DefaultMaxRAMFraction=1\n  \n\n  bugs.sun.com  \n Sun&#39s 1.5 JVM  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/07/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "111", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Java -Xmx, Max memory on system", "parent_id": "1190837", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mykhaylo Adamovych", "owner_user_id": "448078"},{"body": " Here&#39s mine if anyone&#39s interested. It performs in the same sort of manner as Jeff&#39s, but seems to be slightly faster (assuming those ToArrays() are necessary). There&#39s no visible loops or temporaries, and it&#39s much more compact: \n\n  public static IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; Transpose&lt;T&gt;(\n    this IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; source)\n\\{\n    return source\n        .Select(a =&gt; a.Select(b =&gt; Enumerable.Repeat(b, 1)))\n        .Aggregate((a, b) =&gt; a.Zip(b, Enumerable.Concat));\n\\}\n  \n\n If you need it to handle empty lists too, then it becomes this: \n\n  public static IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; Transpose&lt;T&gt;(\n    this IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; source)\n\\{\n    return source\n        .Select(a =&gt; a.Select(b =&gt; Enumerable.Repeat(b, 1)))\n        .DefaultIfEmpty(Enumerable.Empty&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt;())\n        .Aggregate((a, b) =&gt; a.Zip(b, Enumerable.Concat));\n\\}\n  \n\n I noticed that the asker wrote that the matrix would always be square. This implementation (and jeffs) will evaluate an entire row at a time, but if we know that the matrix is square we can rewrite the zip function in a more suitable manner: \n\n  public static IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; Transpose&lt;T&gt;(\n    this IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; source)\n\\{\n    return source\n        .Select(a =&gt; a.Select(b =&gt; Enumerable.Repeat(b, 1)))\n        .DefaultIfEmpty(Enumerable.Empty&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt;())\n        .Aggregate(Zip);\n\\}\n\npublic static IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; Zip&lt;T&gt;(\n    IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; first, \n    IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; second)\n\\{\n    var firstEnum = first.GetEnumerator();\n    var secondEnum = second.GetEnumerator();\n\n    while (firstEnum.MoveNext())\n        yield return ZipHelper(firstEnum.Current, secondEnum);\n\\}\n\nprivate static IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; ZipHelper&lt;T&gt;(\n    IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; firstEnumValue, \n    IEnumerator&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; secondEnum)\n\\{\n    foreach (var item in firstEnumValue)\n        yield return item;\n\n    secondEnum.MoveNext();\n\n    foreach (var item in secondEnum.Current)\n        yield return item;\n\\}\n  \n\n This way, each element won&#39t be evaluated until it&#39s returned. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/07/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "112", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "&quot;Turning&quot; an IEnumerable&lt;IEnumerable&lt;T&gt;&gt; 90 degrees", "parent_id": "5039617", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "07/07/2012", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "YellPika", "owner_user_id": "349384"},{"body": " In your move_uploaded_file you are using the whole  $_FILE[&#39uploaded&#39]  array as the name, not just the filename. A small tweak: \n\n  if (move_uploaded_file($_FILES[\"uploaded\"][\"tmp_name\"],\n        $directory . $_FILES[\"uploaded\"][\"name\"] . $newfn))\n        \\{\n  \n\n And you should be all good. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/08/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/08/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "113", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ARRAY is preceding renamed filenames after upload - PHP", "parent_id": "11381088", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John C", "owner_user_id": "628267"},{"body": " How is Clojure&#39s \n\n  (println \"Hello world!\")\n  \n\n any different than the \n\n  println(\"Hello world!\")\n  \n\n of other languages? Same number of parentheses only at different positions. \n\n The parens delimit a function call (as a list). In C-like languages the parens enclose only the parameters and in LISP-like languages they include the function name. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/09/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/09/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "07/09/2012", "id": "114", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why does the Clojure language use so many parenthesis?", "parent_id": "11391731", "comment_count": 2, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "21734", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "EricSchaefer", "owner_user_id": "8976"}]'
