": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Apache Derby: Create SQL Dump with data", "parent_id": "3076672", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Axel", "owner_user_id": "341291"},{"body": " Adding to Ben&#39s answer: \n\n The runtime bundles a lot of features for each respective version of Visual Studio. The main advantage of using the DLL version of the runtime is that you get (security) updates \"for free\" whenever the system updates the DLLs in question. \n\n Another advantage that some people will point out is that it saves resources to use the DLL version  if  many processes use the runtime via the DLL. This is because Windows has a mechanism to share DLLs in memory across processes (or the major part of them). \n\n You will notice that bundling the runtime into your binary - also called  static linking  - will make your binary bigger, because each of your binaries now carries its own version of the runtime (that cannot be replaced without linking the program anew). \n\n Also beware of mixing (your own) DLLs that statically link to either different versions of the runtime (i.e. Debug vs. Release) or that dynamically and statically link to the runtime depending on the DLL. The problem here is allocators. The functions to allocate ( malloc ,  calloc ,  new ) and free memory are incompatible across these. The best method in such a case is to use an independent mechanism such as  IMalloc  - or carry the deallocator inside your object instances always, ensuring that the call to  free / delete  doesn&#39t cross module boundaries, even if the instance is handled in another module. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/10/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "118", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why do I need to install MSVC++ redist.?", "parent_id": "11405506", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "0xC0000022L", "owner_user_id": "476371"},{"body": " If I am not mistaken Function.prototype is a prototype for all inherited objects. Because you set  Function.prototype.foo = &#39bar  all objects inherit the  foo  property. That is why the third line of code returns true. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/10/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "119", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Function.prototype.propertyname === Object.propertyname is true?", "parent_id": "11405635", "comment_count": 3, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "reagan", "owner_user_id": "1450278"},{"body": " No, you don&#39t want to do this. \n\n What you should do, if you really need to do this, is to use promises or futures to delay evaluation of those expressions. This is because even if the variable  var  exists, the expression  var.func  will only evaluate without exception if  var  holds an object with a member  func . There are a number of promise or future libraries for python - I suggest that you google them yourself, in order to choose the one that suits you best. \n\n However, a better way to do this is simply to not perform any of these operations until the class exists, or the global variables are set. \n\n Unfortunately, as you have provided almost no details of what you are doing, it is impossible to provide any more concrete advice. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/11/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "120", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Preventing a class instance from being evaluated until it&#39s parameters have been set", "parent_id": "11438082", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Marcin", "owner_user_id": "21640"},{"body": " Standard javascript: \n\n  document.getElementById(&#39foo&#39).className += &#39 class_two&#39\n  \n\n or JQuery: \n\n  $(&#39#foo&#39).addClass(&#39class_two&#39);\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/12/2012", "votes_count": 13, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "121", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Add a class to a DIV with javascript", "parent_id": "11444640", "comment_count": 1, "score": 12, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "jezternz", "owner_user_id": "685404"},{"body": " Biggest mistake is not knowing where code is executed: \n\n \n Code inside  &lt;%= ... %&gt;  ( Erb markers ) is executed on the server, before clients see any HTML. \n JS is executed on the client, after being sent from a server. \n \n\n There are a number of options, including creating the JS variable values using Ruby variables&ndash;whether that&#39s the  best  option depends. For example: \n\n  function f1() \\{\n  var user_name = \"&lt;%= escape_javascript(a_ruby_variable) %&gt;\";\n  // Or, more concisely:\n  var user_uid = \"&lt;%=j another_ruby_variable %&gt;\";\n  \n\n The Ruby variable could be initialized in the template, the controller, etc. \n\n Again, whether it  should  be is debatable. \n", "last_activity_date": "03/05/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "c