"11554190", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "potong", "owner_user_id": "967492"},{"body": " Here is an issue track which have brought some light to me:\n https://github.com/symfony/symfony/issues/3323  \n\n After reading that I researched and I&#39ve found that the problem raises in PHP CLI configuration (php.ini file). The register_argc_argv directive must be enabled: \n\n  register_argc_argv=On\n  \n\n Or if you cannot modify the php.ini file, you can change it in time execution pasing as an argument to php: \n\n  php -d register_argc_argv=On your_script.php\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/19/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "10/11/2012", "id": "136", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Symfony2: error deploying", "parent_id": "9230334", "comment_count": 1, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "1712294", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "chk", "owner_user_id": "1538221"},{"body": " I&#39ve now managed to get this to work using a relatively straightforward approach. Fortunately, the code generated from the XML Schemas by  xsd  marks all the classes as partial with no constructors. I&#39ve added my own partial class to define a default constructor that overrides the namespaces, as follows: \n\n  public partial class DataEventSet \n\\{\n    [XmlNamespaceDeclarations]\n    public XmlSerializerNamespaces _xmlns;\n\n    /// &lt;summary&gt;\n    /// Constructor for DataEventSet that sets up default namespaces\n    /// &lt;/summary&gt;\n    public DataEventSet()\n    \\{\n        _xmlns = new XmlSerializerNamespaces();\n        _xmlns.Add(\"\", \"http://www.thirdparty.org/thirdapp\");\n        _xmlns.Add(\"o\", \"http://www.thirdparty.org/thirdapp\");\n    \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n This now serialises as follows: \n\n  &lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?&gt;\n&lt;s:Body xmlns:s=\"http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope\"&gt;\n  &lt;serviceNotifyDataEventSet xmlns=\"http://theircompany.co.uk/theirapp/v1\"&gt;\n    &lt;dataSet xmlns=\"http://www.thirdparty.org/thirdapp\" xmlns:o=\"http://www.thirdparty.org/thirdapp\"&gt;\n      &lt;dataEvents xsi:type=\"o:DABool\" xmlns=\"\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"&gt;\n        &lt;id&gt;47245361157&lt;/id&gt;\n        &lt;value&gt;true&lt;/value&gt;\n      &lt;/dataEvents&gt;\n      &lt;id xmlns=\"\"&gt;0&lt;/id&gt;\n      &lt;site xmlns=\"\"&gt;\n        &lt;category&gt;SITE_SPECIFIC&lt;/category&gt;\n      &lt;/site&gt;\n      &lt;time xmlns=\"\"&gt;\n        &lt;tick_time&gt;396106152171&lt;/tick_time&gt;\n        &lt;time&gt;07/20/2012T13:29:12.171Z&lt;/time&gt;\n        &lt;time_type&gt;OSACBM_TIME_MIMOSA&lt;/time_type&gt;\n      &lt;/time&gt;\n    &lt;/dataSet&gt;\n  &lt;/serviceNotifyDataEventSet&gt;\n&lt;/s:Body&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/20/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "07/20/2012", "id": "137", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Adding Root xmlns Using XmlSerializer with WCF SOAP", "parent_id": "11242038", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "429541", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Adam Rodger", "owner_user_id": "429541"},{"body": " Depends on the structure of your page. \n\n  span.error \\{ color: #fff; \\}  would shorten it more, or if the ancestor is required to  be in the rule and follows a pattern you could write something this  div[id*=&#39pattern&#39] span.error .\nIn this example the ancestor is a  div  that id contains the text \"pattern\". You can modify it to fit your needs. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/21/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "138", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "CSS styling multiple ID&#39s", "parent_id": "11592508", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sotiris", "owner_user_id": "407382"},{"body": " You cannot. Groups always correspond to capturing groups in the regular expression. That is, if you have one capturing group, there cannot be more than one group in the match. It is irrelevant how often a portion (even a capturing group) is repeated during the match. The expression itself defines how many groups the final match can have. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/22/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "139", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "exactly n times - group", "parent_id": "11599271", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "\u0408\u03bf\u0435\u0443", "owner_user_id": "73070"},{"body": " The  &amp;  means that the function accepts the  address  (or reference) to a variable, instead of the  value  of the variable. \n\n For example, note the difference between this: \n\n  void af(int&amp; g)\n\\{\n    g++;\n    cout&lt;&lt;g;\n\\}\n\nint main()\n\\{\n    int g = 123;\n    cout &lt;&lt; g;\n    af(g);\n    cout &lt;&lt; g;\n    return 0;\n\\}\n  \n\n And this (without the  &amp; ): \n\n  void af(int g)\n\\{\n    g++;\n    cout&lt;&lt;g;\n\\}\n\nint main()\n\\{\n    int g = 123;\n    cout &lt;&lt; g;\n    af(g);\n    cout &lt;&lt; g;\n    return 0;\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/22/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "140", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "&quot;&amp;&quot; meaning after variable type", "parent_id": "11604190", "comment_count": 6, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "cegfault", "owner_user_id": "1010175"},{"body": " In order to require that the generic parameter have a default constructor, specify  new()  as part of the generic constraint. \n\n  public static void funcName&lt;T&gt;() where T : IofMine, new()\n\\{\n    T a = new T();\n\\}\n  \n\n You can only use this to require a default (i.e., no parameters) constructor. You can&#39t require a constructor taking a string parameter, for example. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/23/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "07/23/2012", "id": "141", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to pass to a generic function class type that implements certan interface?", "parent_id": "11606041", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "480937", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "David Yaw", "owner_user_id": "480937"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Steppers only move accurately if you don&#39t exceed the maximum acceleration the system can accept - if you do, you will either miss steps or jump a drive belt tooth or similar and then you don&#39t know where you are. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/23/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "142", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Embedded C motion control: Line path step generation in 3 axis for stepper motors", "parent_id": "4631530", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John U", "owner_user_id": "1389218"},{"body": " I&#39d recommend simply targeting the textareas and changing their background colour and giving them a border. \n\n  textarea \\{\n    background-color:#FFF;\n    border:1px solid #224f5f;\n    color:#000;\n\\}\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "07/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/23/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "07/23/2012", "id": "143", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How do I create a white background for my text area (change it from a different colour)?", "parent_id": "11611611", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1494505", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Billy Moat", "owner_user_id": "1501096"},{"body": " No, there&#39s no way of doing this at compile-time. It&#39s a pretty odd requirement too, IMO. \n\n You can do it the co-operation of the abstract class of course, as Sheik&#39s answer shows. But you can&#39t  force  an abstract class to do that by virtue of putting something specific in the interface. \n\n You could potentially try to find all the relevant classes and validate your requirements in a unit test. \n", "last_activity_date": "07/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/25/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "144", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Force a method specified in an interface to only be defined outside of an abstract class", "parent_id": "11647488", "comment_count": 1, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Jon Skeet", "owner_user_id": "22656"},{"body": " Referenced relationships require multiple db lookups; embedded relationships dont. But referenced relationships are easier to work with (especially if you are just starting out with your app and/or with mongo). I would recommend that you stay with referenced relationships until you have a better sense of the shape of your app and your data needs; at that point you can denormalize your data by switching some of those referenced relationships to embedded. \n\n I would also recommend  https://github.com/dzello/mongoid_alize  to help with denormalization. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/04/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "145", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "when associations should be embedded or referenced Mongodb", "parent_id": "11808645", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Shailen Tuli", "owner_user_id": "638061"},{"body": " If you are limited to STL you could use STL Set and constantly erasing and re-inserting the elements (with new priority). \n\n  Set&lt; pair&lt;int,int&gt; &gt; s; // &lt; priority,value &gt;\ns.insert( make_pair(0,5) );\n\n// Decrease Key operation //\ns.erase( s.find( make_pair(0,5) ) );\ns.insert( make_pair(1,5) );\n  \n\n Time complexity is still O(log N) but it will probably take more time for large sets. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/11/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "146", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "C++ A-star implementation -- determining whether a node is already in the priority queue of open items", "parent_id": "11912736", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "compileGuy", "owner_user_id": "814219"},{"body": " To find the rotation between to images you need to know orientation of both, and therefore,  the pose . To calculate the camera pose you need to find  homography  transformation from  keypoints matches .  \n\n Imagine you know the orientation of the first frame and position, because you decide it arbitrarily. You have the keypoints extracted by SIFT. From here you have next steps: \n\n  1-  Extract keypoints from next frame. \n\n  2-  Find matches of the keypoints on both frames. \n\n  3-  Use RANSAC to find the best set of inliers/outliers of that matches for next step \n\n  4-  Use DLT (Direct Lienar Transform) with that set, this will use 4 matches to find homography between images. \n\n  5-  Once you have homography, you can extract the pose, and the rotation. \n\n You have openCV functions for all the steps except for  pose from homography . \n", "last_activity_date": "07/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/26/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "147", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "