curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " You can run the command wrapped in a batch file. The Batch file could produce a header file like version.h containing the version string as: \n\n  #define SVN_REV 12345\n  \n\n \"#define SVN_REV \" is echod  by the batch script. The SVN rev is from the command which you have. \n\n Now you can include this header in the code and use the #define as you want. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/21/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "188", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "use svn revision number in application version", "parent_id": "12057237", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "gammay", "owner_user_id": "957057"},{"body": " The reason it only prints the first item in the list is because there is no \"Jacob Francis\" in FLIST. \n\n As a side note, make sure the capitalization of FLIST stays constant.   \n\n Heres a possible implementation using a single list comprehension. \n\n  FLIST = [\"Mary Smith\", \"Kevin Bacon\"]\nJG = [[3928, \"Mary Smith\"], [2920, \"Jacob Francis\"]]\n\nultralist = [x for x in JG if x[1] in FLIST]\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/14/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/14/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "189", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Iterating over two lists, the first list is only going through the first value", "parent_id": "11955069", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Madison May", "owner_user_id": "1460123"},{"body": " The proposed solution wont work in 4.1+. There the private key is not exportable and it is not possible to put it in the in-memory key store.\nCheck  How to make client certificate authentication from Android 4.1 with Apache client and the KeyChain API \non how to do it in 4.1 \n", "last_activity_date": "11/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/28/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "190", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Android 4.0 SSL Authentication", "parent_id": "11581208", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "vap78", "owner_user_id": "1238844"},{"body": " In this case,  VAR  contains the  output  of the command. \n\n You have to use  $? , which contains the exit status of the last command executed. Setting a variable doesnt alter  $? , so it will still contain the exit status of the subshell  $(...) . \n\n Example: \n\n  x=$(expect -c send \"hello\"; exit 5;)\necho $?; echo $x\n5\nhello\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/15/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "191", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to set bash variable in expect or return variable from expect to bash", "parent_id": "11970608", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Karoly Horvath", "owner_user_id": "650405"},{"body": " What you seem to be asking for is a \"lookahead\" iterator. You could write a class to \"adapt\" an iterator to have lookahead, where the adaptor just stays one step ahead of your code: \n\n  template&lt;class FwdIter&gt;\nclass lookahead_iterator\n&123;\npublic:\n    lookahead_iterator(const FwdIter&amp; begin): cur_iter(begin), next_iter(++begin) &123;&125;\n    operator FwdIter() const &123; return cur_iter; &125;\n    lookahead_iterator&lt;FwdIter&gt;&amp; operator ++() &123; cur_iter = next_iter++; return *this; &125;\n    // Other methods as needed.\nprivate:\n    FwdIter cur_iter;\n    FwdIter next_iter;\n&125;;\n  \n\n Needless to say, this gets a lot more complicated if you need more than a forward iterator. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/16/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/16/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "192", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to check if simple C++ standard library iterator can be advanced?", "parent_id": "11971308", "comment_count": 5, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mike DeSimone", "owner_user_id": "2624511"},{"body": " Try  mysql_num_rows($sql);  \n\n  http://php.net/manual/en/function.mysql-num-rows.php  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/16/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/16/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "193", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Can&#39;t count array returned by mysql_fetch _row", "parent_id": "11987793", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "William", "owner_user_id": "397322"},{"body": " Add: \n\n  @using Microsoft.Web.Helpers\n  \n\n to your view. Or if you dont want to add this namespace to all views, simply add it to the  ~/views/web.config   &lt;namespaces&gt;  section: \n\n  &lt;add namespace=\"Microsoft.Web.Helpers\" /&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/16