kins is best (with Ant). \n", "last_activity_date": "08/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/20/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "196", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Would it be a bad practice to manage deployments through Jenkins?", "parent_id": "12033988", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Aura", "owner_user_id": "1498240"},{"body": " Executing exec(\"kill -9 \".$procStatus[pid]) should definitely kill that process.\nYou could firstly try kill without the -9 parameter to allow a nicer killing and then\nmaxbe check again if the process is still there, -9 parameter is to force the kill. \n\n Under Windows (at least Version 7) you could use exec(\"taskkill /PID \".$procStatus[pid])\nfor testing, it should do quite the same. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/20/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "197", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Force kill runaway java exec from PHP", "parent_id": "12040998", "comment_count": 1, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user1182609", "owner_user_id": "1182609"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Make sure you have a strong property to your navigation controller. (Like Below:) \n\n  @property (strong, nonatomic) UINavigationController *navcon;\n  \n\n Then synthesize it in your app delegate implementation file. \n\n  @synthesize navcon = _navcon;\n  \n\n And yes, then you can have: \n\n  self.navcon = [[UINavigationController alloc] initWithRootViewController:yourViewController];\n[self.window addSubview:self.navcon.view];\n  \n\n (Assuming you have ARC enabled) \n", "last_activity_date": "08/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/20/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "198", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "navigationController is nil", "parent_id": "12042622", "comment_count": 4, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "mvb", "owner_user_id": "849007"},{"body": " Putting forms inside forms doesnt make sense, how would you differentiate the fields inside each form now?  Are they part of the master form?  The child form?  Both? \n\n Separate forms for each area that you will need to read input from is best practice.  If you have a login area, make a form for it.  If you also have a comment area on that page, a separate form should handle that event. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/21/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "199", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "multiple form tags in page or one form tag?", "parent_id": "12064557", "comment_count": 3, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mash", "owner_user_id": "1567281"},{"body": " The \"commands\" are interpreted by the bash shell.  They arent bytes to be fed to the terminal.  What happens is that csh runs interactively, and once it exits bash will source the two (presumably csh) script files. \n\n It looks like youre simply trying to change your shell to csh (why, I have no idea).  Have you tried using  chsh  for that? \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "200", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why commands in .bashrc are not executed?", "parent_id": "12085101", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andy Ross", "owner_user_id": "9555"},{"body": " The quotes around  $CMD  mean that the entire variable value is  a command, including embedded spaces.  Here is a simple example to illustrate: \n\n  /home/user1&gt; CMD=echo hello\n/home/user1&gt; $CMD\nhello\n/home/user1&gt; \"$CMD\"\n-bash: echo hello: command not found\n/home/user1&gt; \n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "201", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Shell script command not found", "parent_id": "12085779", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "cdarke", "owner_user_id": "736308"},{"body": " Its explained right on this page:  https://agiletoolkit.org/doc/dsql/how  \n\n you can probably define it through config file but under a different key. \n\n  config.php:  \n\n  $config[dsn2]=mysql://user:user@localhost/test1;\n  \n\n  Application class:  \n\n  $this-&gt;api-&gt;db2=$this-&gt;api-&gt;add(DB)\n    -&gt;connect($this-&gt;api-&gt;getConfig(dsn2));\n  \n\n Because youre using 4.1, you should use DBlite class instead, but other than than its the same syntax. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "202", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Connect to more than one database", "parent_id": "12062079", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "romaninsh", "owner_user_id": "204819"},{"body": " Add a file  robots.txt  in your website root directory with the following contents: \n\n  User-agent: *\nDisallow: /users/download/id\n  \n\n This approach basically tells the Search Engine not to index  /users/download/id . \n\n This doesnt mean every Search Engine will do that, but most of the modern Search Engines will take in consideration that file. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 6, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "203", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to Hide a Particular website page URL from Search engine?", "parent_id": "12089157", "comment_count": 1, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mihai Iorga", "owner_user_id": "204701"},{"body": " It appears that GeoIP  do  update the IPv4 database and they are made available  here . They state that they update it on the first Tuesday of every month and it is available for free. \n\n I was probably using an old version of the binary database, and after updating it the IPs were returning the correct country code. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "204", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "GeoIP IPv4 database returning incorrect country codes - GeoIP update required?", "parent_id": "12088516", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "crmpicco", "owner_user_id": "691505"},{"body": " \n   Normally, Id worry about random Hashing everything in there, but... do I still need to do that? if theres NO personal information tied in to their facebook ID, i dont see a reason to change anything... \n \n\n So your basic question is, whether it\u2019s considered \u201csafe\u201d from a privacy protection standpoint, to use the Facebook user id to identify an account in your system? \n\n If you don\u2019t tie any other (personal) information to it, then about the only info that the hacker who gets access to your database will get is,  \u201c1234567890123 has connected to Youhan\u2019s app/website using their Facebook account.\u201d  Up to you to decide, how \u201cbad\u201d this would actually be. \n\n If you have any doubts, you could use the  third_party_id  Facebook provides (in the Graph API user object and the FQL user table) instead of the Facebook user id \u2013  \u201cA string containing an anonymous, but unique identifier for the user. You can use this identifier with third-parties.\u201d  \n\n This  third_party_id  is tied to your app \u2013 every app will get it\u2019s own third party id from Facebook for the same user account, so the only way to track that back to the actual user is if an attacker actually manages to get your app\u2019s credentials or a valid access token into his hands. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/24/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "205", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "creating user table in MySql populated with only the Facebook ID?", "parent_id": "12102185", "comment_count": 1, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "CBroe", "owner_user_id": "1427878"},{"body": " I will post the comment as an answer as this is not getting much traffic. \n\n TPL allocates threads based on CPU it is not going to deal with slow connections that dont put a load on CPU well. \n\n An easy start is WithDegreeOfParallelism to throttle.  enter link description here  \n\n You may find 100 is a good WithDegreeOfParallelism. \n\n The next level of optimization gets a lot more complex.  If it is async, thread pool, or combination.   It is going to depend so much on the latency of the websites.   And I am not sure you would buy a lot with async as an idle thread is not that much overhead. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/25/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "206", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": ".net multithread webclient.DownloadString, or use DownloadStringAsync?", "parent_id": "12098069", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Blam", "owner_user_id": "607314"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " The return value of  OrderBy  simply is no instance of  MyCustomList , and neither is the return value of  ToList . Therefore, you  cannot  cast it to  MyCustomList . \n\n The only options you have are: \n\n \n You create a new instance of  MyCustomList  and add the elements returned by  OrderBy . \n You replace the current contentes of your  MyCustomList  instance with the elements returned by  OrderBy . \n \n\n Without knowing more about your  MyCustomList  class, it is impossible to tell more. As it inherits from  List&lt;MyCustomList&gt; , however, it can be assumed that both of the above options are feasible. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/26/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "207", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Convert IOrderedEnumerable back to Custom List&lt;T&gt;", "parent_id": "12132175", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "O. R. Mapper", "owner_user_id": "1430156"},{"body": " I personally feel like its desirable to display the \"iPhone\" layout at smaller browser window sizes, as your content has likely been optimized for that layout, HOWEVER, if you really want to prevent this you can play around with the  device-width  property in your  @media  declaration. Something like  @media only screen and (max-device-width: 720px) &123; ... &125;  will target device width rather than viewport width. Compare the behavior of  this  (viewport width) vs  this  (device width). Play around with the values (change  min  to  max , change the pixel sizes, etc.) and observe the behavior. Also, dont forget that you can combine  @media  rules, e.g.  @media (min-width: 400px) and (max-width: 600px) &123; ... &125; . See what works for you. \n\n The problem with this method is that mobile devices come in all shapes and sizes, so you might be serving undesirable styles on a different mobile device (lets just say an Android phone...) that you hadnt planned on. However, depending on your needs, this might not matter to you. \n\n Here is a list of example media queries and sizes to guide you, if you do decide to go this route:  http://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/media-queries-for-standard-devices/  (sorry for the lack of a working link; apparently Im not cool enough on StackOverflow to post multiple links yet)... \n", "last_activity_date": "08/29/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/29/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "208", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Ensuring monitor does not pick up @media query for mobile", "parent_id": "12183283", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "chrisjlebron", "owner_user_id": "1157427"},{"body": " In my opinion, you can do this in a document data store, such as MongoDB, but not easily in a key-value data store such as Cassandra. If you were to do it in a key-value data store, the composite key would have to identify all the queried data elements (columns). In other words, one instance would have to have all the query columns. This is possible. In a vanilla key-value store, there is one data element (column) per key but you can do it to support many. A key value store permits this because the value is just a string value and can contain what you want. I recommend multiple data elements (columns) per key but you would have to program for this. If instead you have the columns in different column instances, it would be very slow to search through the data vertically, even though the columns are ordered. The sample in your question has only one table. If you have multiple tables in relational, in key-value stores you would have to create a new column family to store the joined data and you would still have to have multiple data elements per key.  However, it would have to be pre-loaded horizontally in one instance in one family by an ETL-like process. In other words, join the data before it is loaded into the key value store, and design the Cassandra data store to store the already-combined data in a column with multiple values. Or use data mining. I believe \"big data analytics\" are currently addressing this problem in key-value stores. Another example, less sophisticated than yours, is how in key-value stores can you produce a simple report of sales revenue and volume by customer by product by week? \n", "last_activity_date": "08/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/27/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "209", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is it possible to construct complex queries against noSQL DB", "parent_id": "2351040", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user1626551", "owner_user_id": "1626551"},{"body": " This is what I used in my webiste I had to do for IPT:  JQuery Effects from W3Schools . This site has \"try it yourself\" where you can fiddle with the code and get to know and understand the workings of this jquery effect better. In order for it to work, you will need to either download or link to the jquery file ( http://www.w3schools.com/jquery/jquery.js ) \n\n you can use the  slideXX()  (where XX = direction) and use the speed parameter to animate it. to your liking.\n  \n \n UPDATE:  If you want to make something grow/shrink, you can use the same jquery file, but a different command (specifically either the  animate  or the  toggle  commands) \n\n the syntax is:  $(selector).animate(&123;params&125;,duration,easing,callback); \nfor the hide/show commands, the syntax is  $(selector).toggle(speed_in_milliseconds); \nEDIT: oh, and I almost forgot: use the  hide  command to hide the buttons on page load \n\n Further information for this can also be found at  jquery effects - w3schools . \n\n Hope it helps! If not, just comment and I will see what else can be done \n", "last_activity_date": "08/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/27/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "08/28/2012", "id": "210", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What will be the Java Script Function To implement sliding animation on a &lt;div&gt; on MouseOver Event", "parent_id": "12139557", "comment_count": 6, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1265811", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sylvester the Cat", "owner_user_id": "1265811"},{"body": " Except the things in previous answers you can consider adding following code if you want to make your app fullscreen: \n\n  requestWindowFeature(Window.FEATURE_NO_TITLE);\n        getWindow().setFlags(WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_FULLSCREEN, WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_FULLSCREEN);\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/28/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "211", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to fit my android application for any phone or tablet screen?", "parent_id": "12155300", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "krltos", "owner_user_id": "1221494"},{"body": " Another, perhaps not