e. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/11/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "235", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Lookup route in symfony 2", "parent_id": "12371927", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Thomas K", "owner_user_id": "597389"},{"body": " It might look like a big overhead at first, but I would suggest using an   IProgressMonitor   which shows the progress of your task. \n\n The user will know whats going on when he/she sees a progress bar, rather than a dialog that looks like the gui is frozen. \n\n  Here  is an article by Eclipse on how to use progress monitors correctly. \n\n If you really want to go for your idea (which I would not suggest), you can try the following: \n\n  public static void main(String[] args) &123;\n    final Display display = new Display();\n    final Shell shell = new Shell(display);\n    shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());\n\n    BazMessageDialog dialog = new BazMessageDialog(shell, \"Information\", null, \"Getting List From Server\", MessageDialog.INFORMATION, new String[]&123;\"OK\", \"Cancel\"&125;, 0);\n    dialog.open();\n\n    /* Do your stuff */\n\n    dialog.reallyClose();\n\n    shell.dispose();\n    while (!shell.isDisposed()) &123;\n        if (!display.readAndDispatch()) &123;\n            display.sleep();\n        &125;\n    &125;\n    display.dispose();\n&125;\n\npublic static class BazMessageDialog extends MessageDialog\n&123;\n\n    public BazMessageDialog(Shell parentShell, String dialogTitle,\n            Image dialogTitleImage, String dialogMessage,\n            int dialogImageType, String[] dialogButtonLabels,\n            int defaultIndex) &123;\n        super(parentShell, dialogTitle, dialogTitleImage, dialogMessage,\n                dialogImageType, dialogButtonLabels, defaultIndex);\n        setBlockOnOpen(false);\n    &125;\n\n    public void reallyClose()\n    &123;\n        cancelPressed();\n    &125;\n\n&125;\n  \n\n This however, will not block your remaining gui, so the user will be able to use it in the meantime. \n\n  EDIT : \n\n Just found out, that  Opal  has something called an  InfiniteProgressPanel , which might be something for you. Have a look... \n", "last_activity_date": "09/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/11/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "09/11/2012", "id": "236", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "SWT - MessageBox opening and closing", "parent_id": "12375469", "comment_count": 4, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "1449199", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Baz", "owner_user_id": "1449199"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Here is the simplest way of sorting... \n\n  function sort($arr) &123;\n  for ($i=0; $i&lt;count($arr); $i++) &123;\n    for ($j=0; $j&lt;count($arr)-1-$i; $j++) &123;\n        if ($arr[$j+1] &lt; $arr[$j]) &123;\n            swap($arr, $j, $j+1);\n        &125;\n     &125;\n  &125;\n  return $arr;\n&125;\n\nfunction swap(&amp;$arr, $a, $b) &123;\n   $tmp = $arr[$a];\n   $arr[$a] = $arr[$b];\n   $arr[$b] = $tmp;\n&125;\n\n//using sorting functions\n$arr = array(1,13,2,9,5,7,0,3);\n\n echo(\"Before sorting\");\n print_r($arr);\n\n sort($arr);\n\n echo(\"Sorted array\");\n print_r($arr);\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/13/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/13/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "237", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "sorting array value without using built in php like sort() etc", "parent_id": "12409040", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Anton Sementsov", "owner_user_id": "1128268"},{"body": " in android sdk window go to: \n\n tools > >  options \n\n will be open a new window and check the option force https:// .... \n\n disable this checkbox \n\n if your network is using proxy conigure it in this window too. \n\n reload or restart the android sdk window and try download again. :) \n", "last_activity_date": "10/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/24/2012", "votes_count": 10, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "238", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Unable to resolve target &#39;android-8&#39;", "parent_id": "13053353", "comment_count": 0, "score": 9, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "ademar111190", "owner_user_id": "794365"},{"body": " Put the file in assets folder and access it like this: \n\n  InputStream is = null;\n        try &123;\n            is = context.getAssets().open(\"JBDB.xls\");\n            workbook = Workbook.getWorkbook(is);\n\n        &125; catch (IOException e) &123;\n\n            e.printStackTrace();\n        &125; catch (BiffException e) &123;\n\n            e.printStackTrace();\n\n        &125;\n        if(workbook!=null)\n        sheet = workbook.getSheet(\"Frame-bore\");\n  \n\n  context  is your main activity context. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/13/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/13/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "239", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Java- Error with Eclipse reading excel file", "parent_id": "12224326", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "mojorisinify", "owner_user_id": "1028986"},{"body": " I recommend you use the  configChanges  and override the  onConfigurationChanged(Configuration newConfig)  method. Ignore the orientation if it is not the one you support. \n\n  @Override\npublic void onConfigurationChanged(Configuration newConfig) &123;\n    super.onConfigurationChanged(newConfig);\n    if (newOrientation == ActivityInfo.SCREEN_ORIENTATION_PORTRAIT) &123;\n         ...\n         setContentView(R.layout.main);\n    &125; else if (newOrientation == ActivityInfo.SCREEN_ORIENTATION_REVERSE_PORTRAIT) &123;\n         ...\n         setContentView(R.layout.main_reverse_portrait);\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n\n This answer might further help you. \n\n  Android: Detect Orientation Changed  \n\n Update: \n\n There is a method   getChangingConfigurations()   that you can use in  onStop()  to determine what configuration change is causing the activity to be destroyed. In this case you dont need to use the  onConfigurationChanged()  callback. \n\n Update 2: \n\n Use  sensorPortrait  and check rotation angle manually in  onCreate . \n\n  @Override\nprotected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) &123;\n    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    ...\n    Display display = ((WindowManager)  \n          context.getSystemService(Context.WINDOW_SERVICE)).getDefaultDisplay();\n    int rotation = display.getRotation();\n    if (rotation == Surface.ROTATION_180) &123; // reverse portrait\n       setContentView(R.layout.main_reverse_portrait);\n    &125; else &123;  // for all other orientations\n       setContentView(R.layout.main);\n    &125;\n    ...\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/19/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "09/25/2012", "id": "240", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "sensorPortrait: How to catch orientation changing?", "parent_id": "12448205", "comment_count": 10, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "857361", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "userSeven7s", "owner_user_id": "857361"},{"body": " you might look at visual and/or vpython.  http://www.vpython.org/ \nVpython claims to be 3-d programming for ordinary mortals. Its based on visual which I have used before and found easy to pick up. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/21/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "241", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Simple 2d surface with arrow in python?", "parent_id": "12529938", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/197