curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I also used the tutorial mentioned by wjl ( http://www.developer.nokia.com/Community/Wiki/QtDbus_quick_tutorial ), but had trouble until I realized the demoifadaptor.* files are the interface to Dbus and the mydemo.* files are the part of your application that does the work.  Those roles werent clear to me at first (perhaps due to some inexperience with Qt). \n\n Anyway, once I created the following mydemo.c file, things worked: \n\n  #include \"mydemo.h\"\n#include &lt;QObject&gt;\n#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nMyDemo::MyDemo(QObject *parent)\n&123;\n    // Do nothing\n&125;\n\nvoid MyDemo::SayBye()\n&123;\n    std::cout &lt;&lt; \"Bye\" &lt;&lt; std::endl;\n\n&125;\n\nvoid MyDemo::SayHello(const QString &amp;name, const QVariantMap &amp;customdata)\n&123;\n    std::cout &lt;&lt; \"Hello\" &lt;&lt; std::endl;\n&125;\n\n// end of file\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/20/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "245", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "QtDbus c++ minimal example", "parent_id": "8626941", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "GrandAdmiral", "owner_user_id": "299344"},{"body": " You could adapt the example you linked, to do what you want, like this: \n\n CSS: \n\n  .Highlighted a&123;\n   background-color : Green !important;\n   background-image :none !important;\n   color: White !important;\n   font-weight:bold !important;\n   font-size: 12pt;\n&125;\n  \n\n Javascript: \n\n  $(document).ready(function() &123;\n    $(#datepicker).datepicker(&123;\n        beforeShowDay: function(date) &123;\n            var day = date.getDay();\n            if (day == 2 || day == 4) &123;\n                return [true, \"Highlighted\", date];\n            &125;\n            return [true, , ];\n        &125;\n    &125;);\n&125;);\u200b\n  \n\n that should do it. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/24/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "246", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Highlight specific days of a week in jQuery datepicker", "parent_id": "12567794", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Nelson", "owner_user_id": "352672"},{"body": " Your assumption is correct. This is how it works. But keep in mind that each plugin can be assigned a certain content type, or a set of content types. For example the parse-pdf plugin will not parse msword documents. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/25/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "247", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "nutch configuration nutch-site.xml", "parent_id": "12305101", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "mana", "owner_user_id": "12016"},{"body": " Heres an extension: \n\n  public static bool ContainsNTimes&lt;T&gt;(this IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; sequence, T element, int duplicateCount)\n&123;\n    if (element == null)\n        throw new ArgumentNullException(\"element\");\n    if (!sequence.Any())\n        throw new ArgumentException(\"Sequence must contain elements\", \"sequence\");\n    if (duplicateCount &lt; 1)\n         throw new ArgumentException(\"DuplicateCount must be greater 0\", \"duplicateCount\");\n\n    bool containsNTimes = sequence.Where(i =&gt; i.Equals(element))\n                            .Take(duplicateCount)\n                            .Count() == duplicateCount;\n    return containsNTimes;\n&125;\n  \n\n Usage: \n\n  var list = new List&lt;int&gt;() &123; 1,2,2,3,4,3,3 &125;;\n\n// list contains 2 for 3 times?\nbool contains2ThreeTimes = list.ContainsNTimes(2, 3);\n\n// any element in the list iscontained 3 times (or more)?\nbool anyContains3Times = list.Any(i =&gt; list.ContainsNTimes(i, 3));\n\nConsole.WriteLine(\"List contains 2 for 3 times? \" + contains2ThreeTimes); // false\nConsole.WriteLine(\"Any element in the list is contained 3 times (or more)? \" + anyContains3Times); // true (3)\n  \n\n Demo:  http://ideone.com/Ozk9v  \n\n Should be quite efficient since it uses deferred execution. It enumerates the sequences until n-items were found. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/21/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "09/21/2012", "id": "248", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Selecting 3 identical items from list", "parent_id": "12530410", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "284240", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Tim Schmelter", "owner_user_id": "284240"},{"body": " Id say the issue is that you defined  command_history  as an object  &123;&125;  instead of an array  [] , since you are using it as an array. \n\n Also, I think you want to pre decrement with  --history_counter   \n\n see this working fiddle: \n\n  http://jsfiddle.net/5DZxs/1/  \n\n So your javascript looks like: \n\n  command_history = []; //&lt;-- Change here\ncommand_counter = -1;\nhistory_counter = -1;\n\n$(#term-command).keydown(function(e)&123;\n    code = (e.keyCode ? e.keyCode : e.which);\n    // Enter key - fire command\n    if(code == 13)&123;\n        var command = $(this).val();\n        command_history[command_counter++] = command;\n        history_counter = command_counter;\n        alert(Run Command: +command); \n        $(this).val().focus(); \n    // Up arrow - traverse history\n    &125;else if(code == 38)&123;\n        if(history_counter&gt;=0)&123;\n            $(this).val(command_history[--history_counter]); //&lt;-- Change here\n        &125;\n    &125;\n&125;);\u200b\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/21/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/21/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "249", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "JavaScript Array Command History", "parent_id": "12531249", "comment_count": 4, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "CaffGeek", "owner_user_id": "54746"},{"body": " Neither unsigned type can accommodate a signed type; the documentation quoted is consistent with your examples - it just says nothing about how the compiler will treat them. On the other hand a signed type can accommodate an unsigned type (SmallInt accomodates Byte, LongInt accomodates Word, Int64 accomodates Cardinal): \n\n  program IntegerOverloadsPart3;\n&123;$APPTYPE CONSOLE&125;\n\nprocedure Test(Value: ShortInt); overload;\nbegin\n  Writeln(Short);\nend;\n\nprocedure Test(Value: SmallInt); overload;\nbegin\n  Writeln(Small);\nend;\n\nprocedure Test(Value: LongInt); overload;\nbegin\n  Writeln(Long);\nend;\n\nprocedure Test(Value: Int64); overload;\nbegin\n  Writeln(64);\nend;\n\nprocedure Main;\nvar\n  _byte: Byte;\n  _word: Word;\n  _cardinal: Cardinal;\n  _uint64: UInt64;\nbegin\n  Writeln(Unsigned variables passed as parameters:);\n  Test(_byte);\n  Test(_word);\n  Test(_cardinal);\n  Test(_uint64);\n  Writeln;\nend;\n\nbegin\n  Main;\n  Readln;\nend.\n  \n\n Delphi XE output: \n\n  Small\nLong\n64\n64\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/22/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "250", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How does Delphi resolve overloaded functions with integral parameters?", "parent_id": "12526786", "comment_count": 4, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user246408", "owner_user_id": "246408"},{"body": " Try this: \n\n  while(keys.length &gt; 0)\n&123;\n    var k = Math.floor(Math.random()*keys.length);\n    $(\"&lt;div&gt;\"+keys[k]+\"&lt;/div&gt;\").appendTo(.slideshow);\n    keys.slice(k, 1);\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/23/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "251", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Dynamically add divs into another div in random order", "parent_id": "12549112", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "manuFS", "owner_user_id": "1541758"},{"body": " Try this: \n\n  http://jsfiddle.net/VeaVh/1/  \n\n There are better selectors you can write, this just an example. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/24/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "252", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to disable a combo box with radiobutton (javascript)", "parent_id": "12560043", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "rizwaniqbal", "owner_user_id": "1156254"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " 1) Constructor with no argument is called default Constructor.\n2) If user have not provided any of the following constructor, then the compiler declares\n   the default constructor for you.  \n\n    2a) Copy Constructor\n  2b) Non-default constructor\n  2C) default constructor. \n  \n\n 3) If compilers declares the default constructor, then it is said to be implicitly declared default constructor,  \n\n 4) The implicitly declared default constructor are of two types  \n\n     4a) **trivial** Constructor\n   4b) **non-trivial** Constructor. \n  \n\n 5) Implictly declared default constructor is said to be trivial, when  there is \n      5a) No reference variable \n      5b) No Virtual Function\n      5c) No Virtual Base Class.\n      5d) Parent class has trivial constructor,  \n\n  Else, it is said to be non-trivial.\n  \n\n Hope this helps.  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/25/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "253", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Copy Constructor and default constructor", "parent_id": "1585708", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Whoami", "owner_user_id": "916439"},{"body": " Dueto various cryptic problems like this when our service complexity grew we moved away from the add service reference method completely. The reason was lack of control , gloat and errors. If you are primarily using the service from .net world then watch the following video  \n\n  http://www.dnrtv.com/default.aspx?showNum=122  \n\n This will also give you a lot of internals info and help debug wcf issues. Once you make the move you will never come back! \n", "last_activity_date": "09/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/26/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "254", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "WCF error: Need to exclude all but one of the following types. Only matching types can be valid references", "parent_id": "12594253", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user544550", "owner_user_id": "544550"},{"body": " There are two errors in your code: \n\n \n When printing the text   \"There are # is.\"  , you are using the  index  variable  i  as a counter. The index will give you the current iteration position, not a count of matches. \n Your  content  variable is not consistent throughout the code, being present as both   Tittle Case / Capitalized   (  Content  ) and   lowercase   (  content  ). Java is case-sensitive, so its effectively two different variables (one is not currently declared, even). \n \n\n Regarding the second, you should respect  Javas conventions for variable naming . In particular the following:   \n\n \n    --  \"If the name you choose consists of only one word, spell that word in all lowercase letters. If it consists of more than one word,\n  capitalize the first letter of each subsequent word. The names\n    gearRatio   and   currentGear   are prime examples of this convention.\"  \n  \n    --  \"If your variable stores a constant value, such as   static final int NUM_GEARS = 6  , the convention changes slightly,\n  capitalizing every letter and separating subsequent words with the\n  underscore character. By convention, the underscore character is never\n  used elsewhere.\"  \n \n\n \n\n As for your regex pattern, although clarity can be improved, there is nothing really wrong with it. \n\n There are some unnecessary  capturing groups  on your  pattern string , and  content[i].matches(\".*E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\" + keyword + \"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b.*\")  would be cleaner while achieving the same result. \n\n Fixing the actual errors mentioned in the first section, and applying what I say above, your code would be this: \n\n  String[] content = &123;\"is,\", \"his\", \"fish\", \"ish\", \"its\", \"is\"&125;;\nString keyword = \"is\";\nint count = 0;\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; content.length; i++) &123;\n  if (content[i].matches(\".*E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\" + keyword + \"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b.*\")) &123;\n    System.out.println(\"Matched: E&#39\\\\&#39\"\" + content[i] + \"E&#39\\\\&#39\"\");\n    count++;\n  &125;\n&125;\nSystem.out.println(\"There are \" + count + \" E&#39\\\\&#39\"\" + keyword + \"E&#39\\\\&#39\".\");\n  \n\n \n\n  There are two additional things you should consider:  \n\n  1)  If your paragraph is already split, and the elements were obtained with predictable ways such as  content.split(\"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\") , you should consider if the use of regex  for the matching  is even needed in the first place. \n\n For example, the following code would work fine for your purposes: \n\n  String content = \"is, his fish ish its is\";\nString keyword = \"is\";\nint count = 0;\nfor (String sub : content.split(\"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\")) &123;//&lt;-Decompose: Regex or something else.\n  if (sub.equals(keyword)) &123; //&lt;-Matching: No regex.\n    count++;\n  &125;\n&125;\nSystem.out.println(\"There are \" + count + \" E&#39\\\\&#39\"\" + keyword + \"E&#39\\\\&#39\".\");\n  \n\n \n\n  2)  If you want to actually  list  your matches, or something that involves  retrieving them specifically , then you are best-set using a  Matcher  to \"catch\" the matches: \n\n  String content = \"is his fish ish its is\";\nString keyword = \"is\";\nList&lt;String&gt; matches = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\nMatcher m = Pattern.compile(\"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\" + Pattern.quote(keyword) + \"E&#39\\\\&#39E&#39\\\\&#39b\").matcher(content);\nwhile (m.find()) &123;\n  matches.add(m.group());\n&125;\n  \n\n In your example, its kinda useless though: The code above gets you a list of multiple (2) duplicates of  \"is\" . But the principle applies to a scenario where the match wouldnt be a single word, or if you want to list or map the different words present in  content . \n", "last_activity_date": "11/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/06/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "11/07/2012", "id": "255", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "String Matches, Java", "parent_id": "13253221", "comment_count": 0, "score": -1, "last_editor_user_id": "1253136", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "TheLima", "owner_user_id": "1253136"},{"body": " An expression can be evaluated to return a value. Any expression can also be used as a statement. \n\n To put it another way, if you can write  a = ... , then  ...  is an expression. So  2*3  and  zip(x,y)  are expressions. \n\n Something like  raise Exception  is a statement but not an expression: you cant write  a = (raise Exception) . \n\n yield being an expression means that  b = (yield a)  is valid code in a generator. If you use the generators  send()  method,  b  is set to the value you pass in. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/26/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "256", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What&#39;s the difference between expression and statement using Python yield", "parent_id": "12600754", "comment_count": 0, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Thomas K", "owner_user_id": "434217"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I think the best way is to provide a repository for Male and another for Female\nusing: \n\n  repository jpa --interface ~.repository.MaleRepository --entity ~.domain.Male\nrepository jpa --interface ~.repository.FemaleRepository --entity ~.domain.Female\n  \n\n you get: \n\n  @RooJpaRepository(domainType = Female.class)\npublic interface FemaleRepository &123;\n&125;\n\n@RooJpaRepository(domainType = Male.class)\npublic interface MaleRepository &123;\n&125;\n  \n\n then you create the service layer for the application for these models (a service for each model) \n\n  service --interface ~.service.MaleService --entity ~.domain.Male\nservice --interface ~.service.FamaleService --entity ~.domain.Female\n  \n\n and then you get: \n\n  @RooService(domainTypes = &123; Male.class &125;)\npublic interface MaleService &123;\n&125;\n\n@RooService(domainTypes = &123; Female.class &125;)\npublic interface FemaleService &123;\n&125;\n  \n\n This is assuming that your Male and Female objects have different responsibility so is needed to separate it in different classes, by the name you gave them (Male and Female) i think they dont, but i dont know your business logic and of course this is just an example (but how faithful is to your real problem?).  \n\n The idea of inheritance is not only to share common functionality to \"is-a\" descendants but preserve the sense of the OO logic, when i say that i mean, in this case for example, you could resolve the problem with an attribute called sex if Male and Female have the same attributes; if this is not the case then wont be painful to create different repositories and services for those specialized objects.  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/26/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "257", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Design issue with JPA inheritance, Spring Roo and Spring Data JPA", "parent_id": "12455893", "comment_count": 4, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Carlos Castellanos", "owner_user_id": "829928"},{"body": " You need to add your bitbucket repository as a remote to your local one. You can do this by running  \n\n \n   git remote add origin git@bitbucket.org: userName/repositoryName.git .  \n \n\n You then need to push your local files to the remote repo by running \n\n \n   git push origin master \n \n\n Note that this will push them to the master branch on the bitbucket repo. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/24/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "258", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How do I add an existing XCode (4.5) project to BitBucket", "parent_id": "13048197", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "NikosM", "owner_user_id": "1770568"},{"body": " Id recommend using  grep  for this (especially  fgrep  since there are no regexps involved), so \n\n  fgrep -v -f keys.txt test.txt \n  \n\n does it fine. With  sed  quickly this works: \n\n  sed -i.ORIGKEYS.txt ^-e s_^_/_ -e s_$_/d_ keys.txt\nsed -f keys.txt test.txt\n  \n\n (This modifies the original  keys.txt  in place - with backup - to a sourceable sed script.) \n", "last_activity_date": "09/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/26/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "259", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to use result from a pipe in the next sed command?", "parent_id": "12607101", "comment_count": 5, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Zsolt Botykai", "owner_user_id": "11621"},{"body": " You can use: Broadcast Receivers for this. Please see following link: \n\n  http://www.vogella.com/articles/AndroidBroadcastReceiver/article.html  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/27/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "260", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Android: how to send notifications to many activities", "parent_id": "12619724", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Shrikant", "owner_user_id": "1352969"},{"body": " You can use JBOSS for your server, and do a Java Server with Webservices. \n\n In your webservices youll have a service that get all the feeds, and maybe another that request the complete feed... \n\n Your \"language\" between the Android app and the Server, you can use XML with SOAP (ksoap2 for Android), or you can try JSON (I never used, but I will cause we goona need use in my service). \n\n You can try find another free server side, but I think the SOAP is important in most of the servers to \"talk\" with your app. \n\n I hope helped you. \n\n []s\nBertan \n", "last_activity_date": "09/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/27/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "261", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Set up a server and get feed from it in android", "parent_id": "12619765", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "William Bertan", "owner_user_id": "1646222"},{"body": " Here is some good discussion for  allowing multiple values to be selected in the telerik combobox. \nIt uses  checkbox within combobox  \n\n  http://codedotnets.blogspot.in/2012/02/checkboxes-in-comboxes-to-allow.html  \n\n Thanks :) \n", "last_activity_date": "09/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/27/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "262", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to select all checkbox inside telerik combox on checbox Checked event?", "parent_id": "9413791", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "suyog", "owner_user_id": "1697309"},{"body": " Those arent errors, theyre warnings. Your code should have still compiled. \n\n The first warnings is because youre passing  &amp;command  to  scanf , which is of type  char (*)[100] , and the specifier  %s  expects an argument of type  char * . All you simply need to do is pass  command  to  scanf  (without the  &amp; ), since a  char  array will decay into a  char*  when passed to a function. \n\n Youll probably find that the code still works, with  command  and  &amp;command  both referring to the same address ( printf(\"%p %p\", command, &amp;command); ). \n\n  \nThe second warning is due to you forgetting to include  &lt;string.h&gt; , which declares  strchr . Since the compiler cant find the declaration, it implicitly generates one, which doesnt turn out to match the real one. \n\n  \nLastly,  strchr  returns a  char* , and the specifier  %i  is intended to be used for  int s. If you want to print out an address using  printf , use the  %p  specifier. \n\n  \nYou should also probably avoid  system(\"PAUSE\");  (which wont work on Linux), and replace it with a function that waits for user input. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/29/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/29/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "263", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to fix unusual error while compiling c program on linux mint?", "parent_id": "12653238", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "AusCBloke", "owner_user_id": "998299"},{"body": " I came across this post while I was searching for a solution to add a local repository to my Maven project using IntelliJ Idea. \n\n Since Sonatype changed their paths and reorganized the downloads since the last post, here is an updated step-by-step tutorial to get your repository indexed for use with IntelliJ Idea: \n\n \n Download the latest stand-alone indexer from  here . \n Extract it somewhere and go into this directory \n From the console, run this command:  export REPODIR=/path/to/your/local/repo/ &amp;&amp; java org.sonatype.nexus.index.cli.NexusIndexerCli -r $REPODIR -i $REPODIR/.index -d $REPODIR/.index -n localrepo  \n In the directory .index within the repository directory, some files will be created including the file \"nexus-maven-repository-index.gz\" which is the file IntelliJ looks out for. \n \n", "last_activity_date": "10/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/02/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "264", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to index a Maven repo without Nexus/Artifactory/etc?", "parent_id": "5349261", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Bj\u00f6rn Jacobs", "owner_user_id": "736868"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " It is my understanding that you cannot have an index of an array unless you have and object there. What I would suggest is to set all indexes in the array to  [NSNull null]  and then in your if statement check to see if the object at that index is an NSNull object.  if([[self.myArray objectAtIndex:index] isKindOfClass:[NSNull class]])  then if that returns true, have it replace the null object with your object \n", "last_activity_date": "10/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/02/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "265", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ios how to check if object in array in particular index exist?", "parent_id": "12697150", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Clint Warner", "owner_user_id": "1469683"},{"body": " simply use the  rememberMe()  method on the  SessionManager  to set a cookie \n\n See  SessionManager Code  on line 260 \n\n there also is  forgetMe()  to remove the cookie \n\n additionally you can configure the defaults for your session manager like this: \n\n  Module.php  \n\n  public function onBootstrap(E&#39\\\\&#39ZendE&#39\\\\&#39EventManagerE&#39\\\\&#39EventInterface $e)\n\n    $config = $e-&gt;getApplication()\n        -&gt;getServiceManager();\n        -&gt;get(Configuration);\n\n    $sessionConfig = new SessionConfig();\n    $sessionConfig-&gt;setOptions($config[session]);\n    $sessionManager = new SessionManager($sessionConfig, null, null);\n    Session::setDefaultManager($sessionManager);\n&125;\n  \n\n  module.config.php  \n\n  return array(\n    session =&gt; array(\n        remember_me_seconds =&gt; 2419200,\n        use_cookies =&gt; true,\n        cookie_httponly =&gt; true,\n    ),\n);\n  \n\n See  this class  for a complete list of configuration options: \n", "last_activity_date": "10/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/03/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "10/03/2012", "id": "266", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to use cookie in Zend Framework 2?", "parent_id": "12707532", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "412395", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andreas Linden", "owner_user_id": "412395"},{"body": " To add to Mikes answer (since I cant comment), I created this wrapper  def  if you want to get the output as a string: \n\n  def fileutil_out\n    out = StringIO.new\n    FileUtils.fileutils_output = out\n    yield\n    return out.string\nend\n\nmylog.info fileutil_out &123; FileUtils.chmod_R(0664, file.txt, :verbose =&gt; isVerbose) &125;\n  \n\n I ended up not using it since I wanted to revert back to  @fileutils_output ||= $stderr  afterwards. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/11/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "10/12/2012", "id": "267", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Getting the executed command from FileUtils?", "parent_id": "3163585", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1691769", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Brad", "owner_user_id": "482608"},{"body": " In general? No. \n\n A specific... \"workaround\"... which might be acceptable in your case? Make the optional parameter a  bool? , not a  bool . \n\n  new MyClass&lt;bool&gt;(false)  will call your  defaultValue  overload. \n\n  new MyClass&lt;bool&gt;(someFlag: false)  will call the other overload. \n\n That said, if you have any existing  new MyClass&lt;bool?&gt;(false)  calls, this will change  them  over instead. \n\n You can overcome  this  by creating an class specifically for making your flags not be bools: \n\n  public struct FakeBool\n&123;\n    private readonly bool val;\n    private FakeBool(bool val) &123; this.val = val; &125;\n    public static implicit operator bool(FakeBool f) &123; return f.val; &125;\n    public static implicit operator FakeBool(bool f) &123; return new FakeBool(f); &125;\n&125;\n\npublic MyClass(FakeBool someFlag = default(FakeBool)) &123; ... &125;\npublic MyClass(T defaultValue, FakeBool someFlag = default(FakeBool)) &123; ... &125;\n\nvar b2 = new MyClass&lt;bool&gt;(true);            // calls two-argument constructor\nvar b1 = new MyClass&lt;bool&gt;(someFlag: true); // calls one-argument constructor\n  \n\n but this is getting silly. (Also, I cant figure out how to get a default value of  true  - any ideas, anyone?) \n", "last_activity_date": "10/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/03/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "10/03/2012", "id": "268", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Forcing a preference for an overload in class definition?", "parent_id": "12706158", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "215380", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Rawling", "owner_user_id": "215380"},{"body": " You would have a better chance using Regex with your problem. \n\n But here is quick a solution : \n\n  $string = \"28 - 100 mm\";\n$arr = explode(\" \",$string);\n$numbers = array();\nforeach($arr as $value)\n&123;\n    if(intval($value))\n        $numbers[] = intval($value);\n&125;\n  \n\n Which results in  array(2) &123; [0]=&gt; int(28) [1]=&gt; int(100) &125;  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/04/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "269", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "PHP - Remove characters and separate numbers", "parent_id": "12730150", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Lkrups", "owner_user_id": "1715014"},{"body": " Thanks to Larry, I simply misunderstood what a covering index is. SQLite  is  using the indices I created. After thinking about it in the shower, I think its just because the database is so large that there are a non-trivial number of operations necessary to generate my answer. \n\n Kansas has ~2.6 million people. Missouri has ~5.4 million people. Selecting contacts where person1 is in Kansas takes 2.6 million * log(3 billion) = 2.6 million * 10 = 26 million lookups. Then, I need to do another 54 million lookups to find contacts where person2 is in Missouri. \n\n  sqlite&gt; SELECT count(*) FROM contacts, people, states WHERE contacts.person1_id=people.id AND people.state_id=states.id AND states.name=Kansas;\n31665994\nsqlite&gt; SELECT count(*) FROM contacts, people, states WHERE contacts.person2_id=people.id AND people.state_id=states.id AND states.name=Missouri;\n69436970\n  \n\n I now have to perform a set intersection between a set of size ~31.7 million and a set of size ~70 million. \n\n So the slowdown has nothing to do with the database or query design. Its simply a lot of stuff to do. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/05/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "270", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why is SQLite3 using covering indices instead of the indices I created?", "parent_id": "12739115", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Geoff", "owner_user_id": "1269634"},{"body": " The problem was caused by using a different driver in the  ODBC Data Source Administrator  when setting up the connection. \n\n Previously we were using the  Microsoft ODBC for Oracle  driver, however when we manually set up this connection on the new server we mistakenly selected a different one (provided by the Oracle client). \n\n The resolution is to ensure youre using the exact same driver. \n\n   \n", "last_activity_date": "10/08/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/08/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "10/08/2012", "id": "271", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Fatal Error when using ADODB in VB6 on Windows Server 2003 SP2", "parent_id": "12638516", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "436028", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "m.edmondson", "owner_user_id": "436028"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Besides the error pointed out by @DyP, you are assuming that  CreatePipe  opened the handle in overlapped mode.   Your assumption is incorrect .  Microsoft  documents it : \n\n \n   Asynchronous (overlapped) read and write operations are not supported\n  by anonymous pipes. This means that you cannot use the ReadFileEx and\n  WriteFileEx functions with anonymous pipes. In addition, the\n  lpOverlapped parameter of ReadFile and WriteFile is ignored when these\n  functions are used with anonymous pipes. \n \n\n (Indeed, if you look inside  kernel32.dll , on Windows XP for example,  CreatePipe  does not set the lower bit on the seventh parameter to  NtCreateNamedPipeFile ; that bit  is  set when  CreateNamedPipe  is called with  FILE_FLAG_OVERLAPPED .) \n\n  Look for Dave Harts   MyCreatePipeEx    implementation; it can be used as a drop-in replacement for  CreatePipe  when overlapped I/O is needed.  Simply change  PipeSerialNumber++  to  InterlockedIncrement(&amp;PipeSerialNumber)  to avoid race conditions in MT code. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/09/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/09/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "10/09/2012", "id": "272", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Overlapped ReadFileEx on Child Process&#39 Redirected STDOUT Never Fires", "parent_id": "3661106", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "66516", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "vladr", "owner_user_id": "66516"},{"body": " dojox.charting.Chart is not a widget, try using dojox.charting.widget.Chart instead.  I think registry.byId would work with that. \n\n  var chart1_widget = new Chart(&123;&125;, \"chartId\");\nvar chart1 = chart1_widget.chart;\nchart1.setTheme(theme);\n...\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/11/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/10/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "10/11/2012", "id": "273", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How can i get access to a dojox-chart?", "parent_id": "12816132", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1368626", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "opiethehokie", "owner_user_id": "1368626"},{"body": " ATL and WTL, I love those frameworks, no MFC mess, small executables and very flexible. \n", "last_activity_date": "03/22/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/22/2011", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "274", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ActiveX in VC++ without MFC?", "parent_id": "5393699", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Coder", "owner_user_id": "459930"},{"body": " You have to difine ChangedEventArgs class as Generic. \n\n Try this: \n\n  public class ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt; : EventArgs\n&123;\n    public readonly T ChangedItem;\n    public readonly ChangeType ChangeType;\n    public readonly T ReplacedWith;\n\n    public ChangedEventArgs(ChangeType change, T item,\n        T replacement)\n    &123;\n        ChangeType = change;\n        ChangedItem = item;\n        ReplacedWith = replacement;\n    &125;\n&125;\n\npublic enum ChangeType\n&123;\n    Added,\n    Removed,\n    Replaced,\n    Cleared\n&125;;\n\nclass CollectionChangeTracked&lt;T&gt; : Collection&lt;T&gt; \n&123;\n    public event EventHandler&lt;ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;&gt; Changed;\n\n    protected override void InsertItem(int index, T newItem)\n    &123;\n        base.InsertItem(index, newItem);\n\n        EventHandler&lt;ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;&gt; temp = Changed;\n        if (temp != null)\n        &123;\n            temp(this, new ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;(\n                ChangeType.Added, newItem, default(T)));\n        &125;\n    &125;\n\n    protected override void SetItem(int index, T newItem)\n    &123;\n        T replaced = Items[index];\n        base.SetItem(index, newItem);\n\n        EventHandler&lt;ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;&gt; temp = Changed;\n        if (temp != null)\n        &123;\n            temp(this, new ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;(\n                ChangeType.Replaced, replaced, newItem));\n        &125;\n    &125;\n\n    protected override void RemoveItem(int index)\n    &123;\n        T removedItem = Items[index];\n        base.RemoveItem(index);\n\n        EventHandler&lt;ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;&gt; temp = Changed;\n        if (temp != null)\n        &123;\n            temp(this, new ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;(\n                ChangeType.Removed, removedItem, default(T)));\n        &125;\n    &125;\n\n    protected override void ClearItems()\n    &123;\n        base.ClearItems();\n\n        EventHandler&lt;ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;&gt; temp = Changed;\n        if (temp != null)\n        &123;\n            temp(this, new ChangedEventArgs&lt;T&gt;(\n                ChangeType.Cleared, default(T), default(T)));\n        &125;\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/12/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "10/12/2012", "id": "275", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Extend the Collection with Generic Types", "parent_id": "12860758", "comment_count": 4, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "944474", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mt. Schneiders", "owner_user_id": "944474"},{"body": " There isnt any option to hide work items that are already in a sprint/iteration or change the backlog query.  I also checked the TFS 2012 Update 1 CTP that includes a number of enhancements too.  I think this would be a very useful feature.  I created a Visual Studio UserVoice feature suggestion.  If you have any votes available, feel free to vote for it so it will get more attention. \n\n  http://visualstudio.uservoice.com/forums/121579-visual-studio/suggestions/3257889-hide-iteration-work-items-in-web-access-backlog-or  \n\n Mike \n", "last_activity_date": "10/14/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/14/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "276", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "TFS2012 sprint planning: Can I modify the &quot;Backlog Query&quot;?", "parent_id": "12855738", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "MikeDouglasDev", "owner_user_id": "930602"},{"body": " Agree with @Anthony_Hatzopoulos (+1) \n\n CDN compliments Caching, also in some cases it will help optimize Caching directives. \n\n For example, a company I work for integrated behavior learning algorithms into its CDN to identify and Cache dynamically generated objects. \n\n Ordinarily these object would be un-Cachable (i.e. [Cache-Control: max-age=0] Http header) but in this case the system is able to identify Caching possibilities and override original HTTP Header directions. (for example: a Dynamically generated popular product that should be Cached or popular Search result page that, while being generated dynamically, is still presented time over time in the same form to thousands of users).  \n\n And yes, before you ask, the system can also identify personalized data and very freshness, to prevent false positives... :) \n\n Implementing such an algorithm was only possible due to a reverse proxy CDN technology and this is an example of how CDN and Caching can complement each other to create a better and smarter acceleration solutions. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/17/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "277", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is better use Cache or CDN?", "parent_id": "12916430", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Igal Zeifman", "owner_user_id": "1410093"},{"body": " Sounds like something you can do using expect. \n\n  http://linux.die.net/man/1/expect  \n\n \n   Expect is a program that \"talks\" to other interactive programs according to a script. Following the script, Expect knows what can be expected from a program and what the correct response should be. \n \n", "last_activity_date": "10/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/17/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "278", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Run scripts remotely via SSH", "parent_id": "12937634", "comment_count": 3, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "andrux", "owner_user_id": "1741861"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " This is basically a  PIVOT  that you are trying to perform. Unfortunately, MySQL does not have a  PIVOT  function.  There are two ways to do this static or dynamic.  If you know the values that you want to transform into columns, then you can use a static version but if the values are unknown then you can use a prepared statement to generate this dynamically: \n\n  SET @sql = NULL;\nSELECT\n  GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT\n    CONCAT(\n      sum(case when v = ,\n      v,\n       then c end) AS as_c,\n      v\n    )\n  ) INTO @sql\nFROM table1;\n\nSET @sql = CONCAT(SELECT p, , @sql,  \n                    FROM table1 \n                    GROUP BY p);\n\nPREPARE stmt FROM @sql;\nEXECUTE stmt;\nDEALLOCATE PREPARE stmt;\n  \n\n See  SQL Fiddle with Demo  \n\n The static version would be similar to this: \n\n  select p,\n  sum(case when v=1 then c end) as_c1,\n  sum(case when v=2 then c end) as_c2,\n  sum(case when v=3 then c end) as_c3\nfrom table1\ngroup by p\n  \n\n See  SQL Fiddle with Demo  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/17/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "279", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "mysql group by with multi rows from one table", "parent_id": "12943142", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "bluefeet", "owner_user_id": "426671"},{"body": " You can actually achieve that easily by using iScroll 4. visit here  for reference. \n\n All you need is to implement it on a webview with javascript enable... \n\n  webview.getSettings().setJavaScriptEnabled(true);      \nwebview.getSettings().setPluginsEnabled(true);\n  \n\n Another Implementation is called the SwipeView, also found on the same site.   \n\n Take a look at the site, lots of examples...might not be as pretty as cover flow, but i bet it will save you a lot of time. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/19/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "10/19/2012", "id": "280", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how do i obtain images (url) online and place it in horizontal scroll view?", "parent_id": "12966458", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "1353243", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Gildow", "owner_user_id": "1757888"},{"body": " In case you use auto incremental IDs for your records, you can use: \n\n  SELECT * FROM [table] ORDER BY [id column] DESC LIMIT [number of records]\n  \n\n Otherwise you should add a TIMESTAMP colum to your records for this purpose and select by this column. \n\n Personally, if there is an option, I wouldnt use the record IDs for this, as it is not what they are for. Record IDs can change throughout the lifetime of an application and they dont necessarily represent the order in which the items were added. Especially in data import/export scenarios. Id prefer to create special columns to store such information, e.g. \"CreatedAt\", \"ModifiedAt\". \n", "last_activity_date": "10/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/19/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "10/19/2012", "id": "281", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to get the newly added records", "parent_id": "12968131", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "681785", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "famousgarkin", "owner_user_id": "681785"},{"body": " You need a subquery \n\n  select * from (\n                 select ..... order by .... limit 50\n               ) as t\norder by something_else\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/08/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/08/2011", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "282", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Problem with multiple ORDER BY that must respect the first clause", "parent_id": "5601299", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "nick rulez", "owner_user_id": "344491"},{"body": " This works fine but it would be IMO clearer to use $$/$4: \n\n  con_statement:\nIF exp DO\n&123;\n  $$ = ifNum++;\n  if($2 == BOOLEAN_TYPE || $2 == INTEGER_TYPE)\n    &123;\n      utstring_printf(code, \"E&#39\\\\&#39tpopE&#39\\\\&#39teaxE&#39\\\\&#39n\");\n      utstring_printf(code, \"E&#39\\\\&#39tcmpE&#39\\\\&#39teax, 0E&#39\\\\&#39n\");\n      utstring_printf(code, \"E&#39\\\\&#39tjeE&#39\\\\&#39tIF_END_%dE&#39\\\\&#39n\", $$);\n    &125;\n  if($2 == FLOAT_TYPE)\n    &123;\n      utstring_printf(code, \"E&#39\\\\&#39tnopE&#39\\\\&#39n\");\n    &125;\n&125;\nprogram FI\n&123;\n  utstring_printf(code, \"IF_END_%d:E&#39\\\\&#39n\", $4);\n&125;\n;\n  \n\n The first action is generating a value (which it puts into  $$ ), and then later actions can access that value. \n\n Alternately (and particularly if you want to support ELSE), it may make sense to split this initial action onto a separate production: \n\n  con_statement:\n  if_head program FI\n    &123; utstring_printf(code, \"IF_FALSE_%d:E&#39\\\\&#39n\", $1); &125;\n| if_head program ELSE\n    &123; utstring_printf(code, \"E&#39\\\\&#39tjmpE&#39\\\\&#39tIF_END_%dE&#39\\\\&#39n\", $1);\n      utstring_printf(code, \"IF_FALSE_%d:E&#39\\\\&#39n\", $1); &125;\n  program FI\n    &123; utstring_printf(code, \"IF_END_%d:E&#39\\\\&#39n\", $1); &125;\n;\n\nif_head:\n  IF exp DO\n    &123; $$ = ifNum++;\n          :\n;\n  \n\n This allows using the same action for plain if and if/else, avoiding a grammar conflict, since at the point you are parsing the  IF..DO  you dont know whether there will be an  ELSE  or not. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/24/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "10/25/2012", "id": "283", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is this safe programming for Bison?", "parent_id": "13057991", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "16406", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Chris Dodd", "owner_user_id": "16406"},{"body": " Try using  try : \n\n  for t = 1:T\n   arg = (do some calculation)\n   try\n       func(arg)\n   catch\n       z = 1;\n   end\nend\n  \n\n Then just set your debug point on the line  z = 1; . When the error in  func  trips, the program will jump to the  z = 1;  line, where your debug point will halt things and allow you to examine the workspace. Done! \n", "last_activity_date": "10/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/26/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "284", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Step out to caller when error occurs in function with Matlab debugger", "parent_id": "13093968", "comment_count": 3, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Colin T Bowers", "owner_user_id": "1667895"},{"body": " You have it all small in  var=\"player\" , but in the expression you have it capitalized  $&123;Player.first_Name&125; . \n\n  &lt;c:forEach items=\"$&123;players&125;\" var=\"player\"&gt;\n     &lt;tr&gt;\n          &lt;td&gt;$&123;player.first_Name&125;&lt;/td&gt;