curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Usually when one gets session variables being shared between client instances it is because a \"web garden\" is being used and the session state is held in-process. \n\n In that case, you need to use an out-of-process state server; theres more explanation at  ASP.NET: Moving Session Out-of-Process with StateServer , and the documentation is at  Session-State Modes . If your state server is on the same machine, the web.config entry would look something like  &lt;sessionState mode=\"StateServer\" stateConnectionString=\"tcpip=127.0.0.1:42424\" cookieless=\"false\" timeout=\"40\" /&gt; . \n\n On the other hand, if the same session state is being used in two tabs in a browser, then this looks like a useful solution:  asp.net - session - multiple browser tabs - different sessions? . \n", "last_activity_date": "10/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/27/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "287", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ASP.NET - Session variables and Overlapped recycle", "parent_id": "13102347", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andrew Morton", "owner_user_id": "1115360"},{"body": " How about \n\n  string workGroupIdStringValue = ((List&lt;string&gt;)session[\"WorkGroupIds\"]).Last();\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/29/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/29/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "288", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to select second string in a list using C#?", "parent_id": "13119585", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Justin Harvey", "owner_user_id": "1212335"},{"body": " MSVCs link cannot link directly to a DLL - youll need to use the  kernel32.lib  import library instead: \n\n  link.exe \"C:E&#39\\\\&#39UsersE&#39\\\\&#39JonE&#39\\\\&#39DesktopE&#39\\\\&#39eulerE&#39\\\\&#39asmE&#39\\\\&#39test.obj\" kernel32.lib\n  \n\n You will need to make sure that the environment is set up correctly so  link.exe  can find the import library.  Thats often done by the  vcvarsall.bat  (or similar) script/batch file that configures the command line window used to run the tools.  If you dont have something configuring the environment for the build tools, youll need to pass in the location of the library, either by using the full path or by passing in a directory with the  /libpath  linker option. \n\n I dont know what GoLink is, so I cant comment on what its doing right or wrong... \n", "last_activity_date": "11/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/07/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "11/07/2012", "id": "289", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Cannot link with system32.dll using visual studio command prompt", "parent_id": "13261881", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "12711", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Michael Burr", "owner_user_id": "12711"},{"body": " Just add like this in case 1: like this \n\n   case 0:\n     list = DBAdpter.requestUserData(assosiatetoken);\n     Collections.sort(list, byDate);\n     for (int i = 0; i &lt; list.size(); i++) &123;\n         if (list.get(i).lastModifiedDate != null) &123;\n             lv.setAdapter(new MyListAdapter(\n                     getApplicationContext(), list));\n         &125;\n     &125;\n     break;\n  \n\n and put this method at end of the your class \n\n  static final Comparator&lt;All_Reque