curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I dont think you need a javascript function to do go home you can just do this: \n\n  &lt;a accesskey=\"h\" id=\"home\" href=\"../index.html\"&gt;Home&lt;E&#39\\\\&#39/a&gt;\n  \n\n if you dont want it to show on the home page though you can do something like this assuming the home page is example.com/index.html \n\n  if(window.location.pathname==\"/index.html\")&123;\n document.getElementById(home).style.display = none;\n&125;\n  \n\n Not in the function, but just called sometime after the link in the source code or in the head. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/31/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/31/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "295", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to return to home page using javascript?", "parent_id": "13158786", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Ian Overton", "owner_user_id": "1038053"},{"body": "  child.listChildren()  will return a generator object and not the actual children. So you probably want to do something like: \n\n  def listChildren(self):\n  yield self\n  for child in self.children:\n    for c in child.listChildren():\n      yield c\n  raise StopIteration # PS: you dont need to do that explicitly\n  \n\n Alternatively if you use Python 3.3 you could do: \n\n  def listChildren(self):\n  yield self\n  for child in self.children:\n    yield from child.listChildren()\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/07/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "296", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Convert recursive generator object to list", "parent_id": "13275479", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Qlaus", "owner_user_id": "1388435"},{"body": " You can just use a different prefix for messages on each of the channels. For example, if you want to send \"hello\" on channel 1, you send \"1hello\" instead. Then you have an web socket handler that parses these messages and dispatches them to other actors or iteratees according to the prefix. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/08/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/08/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "297", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to setup sub channels on web socket", "parent_id": "13285233", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Kim Stebel", "owner_user_id": "46450"},{"body": " \n   @aleguna strings are ids for functions, some examples are \"single_channel_subtract_abs\", \"multi_channel_random_add\", \"multi_channel_random_subtract_abs\". There are 5 keys in total \n \n\n Then you should not be using a string, nor a  unordered_map : \n\n  // Function.hpp\n\nenum FunctorName &123;\n    single_channel_subtract_abs,\n    multi_channel_random_add,\n    multi_channel_random_substract_abs,\n    ...\n&125;;\n\nSTFRandomTreeFunctor const&amp; get(FunctorName name);\n\n// Function.cpp\nstatic STFRandomTreeFunctor const Functors[] = &123;\n    ...\n&125;;\n\nSTFRandomTreeFunctor const&amp; get(FunctorName name) &123;\n    size_t const index = name;\n\n    assert(index &lt; sizeof(Functors) &amp;&amp; \"Need to update Functors\");\n\n    return Functors[index];\n&125; // get\n  \n\n You may drop the  const&amp;  in  get  altogether if  STFRandomTreeFunctor  is a  typedef  for a function type and not a full blown functor. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/31/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/31/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "298", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "using boost::unordered_map as a look up table appears to be extremely slow", "parent_id": "13162735", "comment_count": 0, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Matthieu M.", "owner_user_id": "147192"},{"body": " Use  favNum.equals(\"3\")  instead of  favNum == \"3\" .  You should almost never use  ==  to compare objects; use  .equals  instead.  (There are a few rare exceptions, but you wont need to worry about them until you learn a fair bit more Java.) \n", "last_activity_date": "02/07/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "02/07/2013", "votes_count": 8, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "299", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "BufferedReader.readLine is not working", "parent_id": "14741733", "comment_count": 2, "score": 7, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Louis Wasserman", "owner_user_id": "869736"},{"body": " Try this: \n\n       SELECT DATE_FORMAT(STR_TO_DATE(substr(\"FALL94\", 5), %y), %Y) AS LONG_YEAR;\n  \n\n Here  STR_TO_DATE  with  %y  converts the 2 digit string into date and  DATE_FORMAT  with  %Y  converts date back into 4 digit year. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/26/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/26/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "300", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Two digit Year in YYYY year", "parent_id": "14046776", "comment_count": 0, 