curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Rebase is most useful when pushing a single commit or a small number of commits developed in a short time frame (hours or minutes). \n\n Before pushing to a shared server, one must first pull the commits made to the origins HEAD in the meantime\u2014failing to do so would create a non-fast-forward push. In doing so, one can choose between a merge ( git pull ) or a rebase ( git pull --rebase ) operation. The merge option, while technically more appealing, creates an additional merge commit. For a small commit, the appearance of two commits per change actually makes the history  less  readable because the merge operation distracts from the commits message. \n\n In a typical shared development tree, every developer ends up pushing to a shared branch by doing some variation of  git pull; &lt;resolve conflicts&gt;; git push . If they are using  git pull  without  --rebase , what happens is that almost  every  commit ends up being accompanied by a merge commit, even though no parallel development was really going on. This creates an intertwined history from what is in reality a linear sequence of commits. For this reason,  git pull --rebase  is a better option for small changes resulting from short development, while a merge is reserved for integration of long-lived feature branches. \n\n All this applies to rebasing  local  commits, or rebasing a short-lived feature branch shared by closely connected coworkers (sitting in the same room). Once a commit is pushed to a branch regularly followed by by others, it should  never  be rebased. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/02/2012", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "11/05/2012", "id": "303", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why would I want to do git rebase?", "parent_id": "13193787", "comment_count": 5, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "1600898", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "user4815162342", "owner_user_id": "1600898"},{"body": " (Ignoring whole bunch of text/code in question that does not seem to be related to question in title) \n\n You can debug both ends of web application written using ASP.Net by using Visual Studio.  \n\n Browser side debugging with VS is limited to IE, but generally it is not a problem as all modern browsers for desktop systems include developer tools (usually avaialble by clicking F12). \n\n Server portion can be directly debugged on either built in Web server or on IIS. In case if you dont use default deployment you can simply attach VS debugger to w3wp process that contains app pool for given site. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/03/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "304", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to debug web site/application via VS not using extra programs", "parent_id": "13205047", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Alexei Levenkov", "owner_user_id": "477420"},{"body": " Ive had great success with Justin Domkes  JGMT . It is written in C++ and can be used from Matlab. I would recommend you look at this library first. \n\n There are plenty of other options:  CRFSuite  which is written in C++ but easily accesible from Python and stuff. \n\n There is also  CRF++  which is written in C++ and does have bindings for Python and Ruby. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/04/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/04/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "305", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "code for CRF implementation in C++ or Matlab for images", "parent_id": "13211690", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "carlosdc", "owner_user_id": "183251"},{"body": " Your  reduce  function should be summing up the  count  values, not just adding  1  for each value.  Otherwise the output of a  reduce  cant properly be used as input back into another  reduce .  Try this instead: \n\n  var R = function (key, values) &123;\n  var sum = 0;\n  values.forEach(function(x) &123;\n    sum += x.count;\n  &125;);\n  var result = &123;\n    count : sum \n  &125;;\n  return result;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/10/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "306", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "MapReduce results seem limited to 100?", "parent_id": "13318791", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "JohnnyHK", "owner_user_id": "1259510"},{"body": " I would simply create a \"Model\" class that holds those vars and pass the model class from one view controller to the next. Once its linked in view1 &amp; view2 during transition from view1 to view2, then its automatically updated when transitioning back from view2 to view1. Use @property (assign) int shours so you have setters and getters created. \n\n With this approach, using segues will work just fine. You dont need to use NSUserDefaults or NSNotificationCenter. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/15/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "307", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Pass values from a UIViewController to another", "parent_id": "13399380", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "HM1", "owner_user_id": "567276"},{"body": " Inside the function, make a vector  positions = [0,1,2,3...] \nSort positions with the comparator  (int x, int y)&123;return data[x]&lt;data[y];&125; .   \n\n Then iterate over positions , doing  result.push_back(index[*it]);  \n\n This assumes the values in  index  can be arbitrary.  If it is guaranteed to already be  [0,1,2..]  as in your example, then you dont to make the  positions  array, just use  index  in its place and skip the last copy.  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/28/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "308", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "std::sort to sort an array and a list of index?", "parent_id": "13609797", "comment_count": 0, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "AShelly", "owner_user_id": "10396"},{"body": " There isnt really such a thing as  collision prone object , because this thing is dependent on the hash function you use. Assuming the objects are not identical - there is some feature that can be utilized to create an informative hash function to be used. \n\n Assuming you have some knowledge on your data - and you know it is likely to have a lot of collision for some hash function  h1()  - then you should find and use a different hash function  h2()  which is better suited for this task. \n\n \n\n That said, there are other issues as well why to favor tree based data structures over hash bases (such as latency and the size of the set), some are covered by  my answer in this thread . \n", "last_activity_date": "11/10/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/10/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "309", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Selection of map or unordered_map based on keys&#39;s type", "parent_id": "13323683", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "amit", "owner_user_id": "572670"},{"body": "  map  is a lazy operation i.e it is not executed until required. When called from repl the repl cause it to evaluate as it needs the returned values to be printed. \n\n You can use  doall  to force the execution of lazy operation. \n\n  (doall (map ... ))\n  \n\n Even better would be to use  doseq  rather than  map .  map  is for transforming a set of values to another set of values and  doseq  is to perform a operation on a set of values and that what you want to do. \n\n  (doseq [ch (:channels server)]\n  (write conn (str \"JOIN \" ch)))\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/12/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "310", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Use of map within the scope of cond", "parent_id": "13337729", "comment_count": 2, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Ankur", "owner_user_id": "553209"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " That may be an HTTP header problem (e.g. missing  Accept  header); observe the headers sent by FF (you can use Firebug for that) and try to replicate them in your script ( setRequestHeader ). \n\n Otherwise, that may be a \"same origin policy\" problem. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/12/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "311", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "XML accessible from URL line but not from script", "parent_id": "13341712", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Julien Royer", "owner_user_id": "1783295"},{"body": " My 1st advice would be to forget about TCP/IP and sockets here. You definitely can do it with that technology stack, but you would also get a lot of headache implementing all the things you want. And the reason is it too low level technology for such a class of tasks. I would go with tcp/ip and sockets only for academic interest, or if I need tremendous control over the communication, or if I have very high performance requirements. \n\n So, my 2nd advice would be to look at WCF technology. Dont be afraid if you havent used it before. Its not that difficult. And if you were ready to use sockets for your app, you can handle WCF definitely. For you task you can create basic communication withing 1-2 hours from scratch using any WCF tutorial. \n\n So, I would create a server WCF service which will have some API functions containing your business logic. It can be hosted within a windows service, IIS, or even a console application.\nAnd your clients would use that WCF service, calling their functions like its functions from another local class in your project. WCF could also help you do the events which you want (its a little bit more advanced topic though). And you can even forget about threading here, most of the things will be working out of the box. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/12/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "312", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Networked Client-Server application advice", "parent_id": "13346216", "comment_count": 2, "score": 7, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Max Shmelev", "owner_user_id": "650927"},{"body": " Try this, surround the sub-query with bracket \n\n  SELECT X.vname, X.id, CONCAT(X.vname, .. ,(SELECT T.id FROM T WHERE T.x_id=X.id LIMIT 1), .., some_text) FROM xtable\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/12/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "313", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "CONCAT a subquery result and fixed strings", "parent_id": "13353154", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "codingbiz", "owner_user_id": "1267263"},{"body": " My advice: construct a dict mapping the country to the things it produces, and split each line on the \"E&#39\\\\&#39t\" \n\n  file=open(\"exports.txt\",r)\ndict = &123;&125;\n\nfor i in file:\n    spl_line = i.split(\"E&#39\\\\&#39t\")\n    dict[spl_line[0]] = spl_line[1].split(\" \")\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/14/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/14/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "314", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How do I print something and then its list?", "parent_id": "13382293", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Cameron Sparr", "owner_user_id": "1426673"},{"body": " another solution, based on a common method for your controller: \n\n Your controllers all of them must extend from CController, but, when you build a new fresh yii application Gii creates a base Controller on /protected/components/Controller.php so all your controllers derives from it.   \n\n So, put a main attribute on it, named: \n\n  &lt;?php\nclass Controller extends CController &123;\n  public $is_main_front_page;\n  public function setMainFrontPage()&123; $this-&gt;is_main_front_page = true; &125;\n  public function getIsMainFrontPage()&123; returns $this-&gt;is_main_front_page==true; &125;\n&125;\n?&gt;\n  \n\n well, when you render your main front page action, set up this core varible to true: \n\n  &lt;?php\nclass YoursController extends Controller &123;\n   public function actionPrimaryPage()&123;\n      $this-&gt;setMainFrontPage();\n      $this-&gt;render(primarypage);\n   &125;\n   public function actionSecondaryPage()&123;\n      $this-&gt;render(secondarypage);\n   &125;\n&125;\n  \n\n next, in any view, you could check for it: \n\n  &lt;?php // views/yours/primaryview.php \n   echo \"&lt;h1&gt;Main Page&lt;/h1&gt;\";\n   echo \"is primary ? \".$this-&gt;getIsMainFrontPage();  // must say: \"is primary ? true\"\n?&gt;\n\n&lt;?php // views/yours/secondaryview.php \n   echo \"&lt;h1&gt;Secondary Page&lt;/h1&gt;\";\n   echo \"is primary ? \".$this-&gt;getIsMainFrontPage();  // must say: \"is primary ? false\"\n?&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/14/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/14/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "315", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How do you check if the current page is the frontpage using YII?", "parent_id": "13378499", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "christian", "owner_user_id": "937815"},{"body": " You can hide GIFs with CSS (or JS replacing them with a placeholder) and when GIFs are loaded you can fire show() \n\n  $(img[src$=\".gif\"]).load(function()&123;$(this).show())  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/15/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "316", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Start gif animation not until it&#39;s completely loaded", "parent_id": "13399564", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "banzsh", "owner_user_id": "1600864"},{"body": " See iphlpapi.h: IpReleaseAddress and IpRenewAddress  \n\n OpenNetCF has a .net wrapper for this and AFAIK there is also a MS wrapper available. \n\n If you look for a free tool:  http://www.cambridgevx.com/vxipconfig.html  \n", "last_activity_date": "02/15/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "02/15/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "317", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "windows mobile force dhcp renew", "parent_id": "14883063", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "josef", "owner_user_id": "1479943"},{"body": " You need to include the event object in your clickhandler: \n\n   $(\".delete\").live(click,function(e)\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "01/25/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "01/25/2013", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "318", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Uncaught TypeError: Object has no method &#39;stopImmediatePropagation&#39;", "parent_id": "14514790", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "John Conde", "owner_user_id": "250259"},{"body": " No one has answered your actual question, except maybe AProgrammer. \n\n The C/C++ standard is defined as Griwes described.  This allows the C and the C++ language to be implemented where the compiler vendor can define the sizes most convenient to the computer architecture.  For a while, (for Windows 3.1 and before, that is, before Windows 95), C code for windows had a 16 bit int whereas many UNIX platforms, such as Solaris, HPUX, and AIX had a 32 bit int. \n\n However, modern microcomputers (since the 386), have full 32 bit registers, and addressing memory aligned to 32 bits is much faster then accessing 16 bit increments.  Thus code is much more efficient with a 32 bit int, especially for int arrays, than it might be with a 16 bit int. \n\n To simulate a 16 bit int in a 32 bit register, you also have to overflow at the 16th bit, instead of the 32nd.  So its just easier with a 32 bit int, even if you only have 32 bits available for long. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/15/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/15/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "319", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Why are C++ int and long types both 4 bytes?", "parent_id": "13398630", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Marlin Pierce", "owner_user_id": "831564"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " You can set the  SolidColorBrush  resources in a style that only targets  ListBoxItem . \n\n Since  ComboBoxItem  inherits from  ListBoxItem , the ComboBox will still be affected though, so its also necessary to create a style for  ComboBoxItem  to apply the default colors. \n\n  &lt;ListBox.Resources&gt;\n    &lt;Style TargetType=\"ListBoxItem\"&gt;\n        &lt;Style.Resources&gt;\n            &lt;SolidColorBrush x:Key=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.ControlBrushKey&125;\" Color=\"Transparent\" /&gt;\n            &lt;SolidColorBrush x:Key=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.HighlightBrushKey&125;\" Color=\"Transparent\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/Style.Resources&gt;\n    &lt;/Style&gt;\n\n    &lt;Style TargetType=\"ComboBoxItem\"&gt;\n        &lt;Style.Resources&gt;\n            &lt;SolidColorBrush x:Key=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.HighlightBrushKey&125;\" Color=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.HighlightColor&125;\"/&gt;\n             &lt;SolidColorBrush x:Key=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.ControlBrushKey&125;\" Color=\"&123;x:Static SystemColors.ControlColor&125;\"/&gt;\n        &lt;/Style.Resources&gt;\n    &lt;/Style&gt;\n&lt;/ListBox.Resources&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/15/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "11/17/2012", "id": "320", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Remove Control Highlight From ListBoxItems but not children controls", "parent_id": "13406697", "comment_count": 5, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "564495", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Peter Hansen", "owner_user_id": "564495"},{"body": " Are these requests legitimate at all? Why is someone making ad requests to your site? is it spammy? It helps to know how real they are. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/16/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/16/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "321", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Drupal lots of spam page not found errors in my watchdog logs", "parent_id": "13411582", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Antonio Torres", "owner_user_id": "524091"},{"body": " In case your XQuery processor does not support  group by , you will need to perform an (implicit) join. Very similar to your query, but fetch all reviewers and for each, query the reviewers using a predicate. \n\n  &lt;query2&gt;\n  &lt;output&gt;\n    &123;\n      for $reviewer in distinct-values(doc(\"reviews.xml\")/reviews/review/reviewer)\n      return &lt;reviewer&gt;\n               &123;\n                 /reviews/review[reviewer = $reviewer]/movie_title\n               &125;\n             &lt;/reviewer&gt;\n    &125;\n  &lt;/output&gt;\n&lt;/query2&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/17/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/17/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "322", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Xquery using FLOWR Expression Query", "parent_id": "13434344", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Jens Erat", "owner_user_id": "695343"},{"body": " Because I had the same problem and this is one of the first Google hits looking for it, I will give an answer although its been some time now since you asked the question.\nThese are the steps to build Xerces-c in Visual Studio (worked in VS10 for me) with ICU: \n\n \n Download and build ICU as described. \n Open the xerces-all.sln solution file with VS. \n Select the ICU Debug/Release build configuration - it sets  XERCES_USE_TRANSCODER_ICU  for you. \n Add the include and library paths for ICU to the porperties of the XercesLib project, add the icu libs in the additional linker dependencies of that project. \n Build and be happy - no need to exclude WIN32TransService.cpp \n \n", "last_activity_date": "11/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/22/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "323", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "build xerces c++ version 3 with icu", "parent_id": "9409213", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Arne Mertz", "owner_user_id": "1838266"},{"body": " You could create your own definition for require and then call it conditionally within your code. \n\n This example is very basic, Im declaring require as  any  and Im allowing x to be  any , which doesnt give me the strong typing I want - but you could expand the definition of require as you need it and add a reference a  .d.ts  file for  SomeModule  (which can be auto-generated using the ` \n\n For the most part, these are hand-created. For the things that have an external well-defined speclike the DOM (see lib.d.ts), the .d.ts file was generated using a script, but for more fluid stuff like JQuery, its just a matter of sitting down with the documentation and typing it out. There might be automated tools to help with this in the future, but none exist yet. \n\n If you have an existing TypeScript library that you want to generate a .d.ts file for, you can use the  --declaration  flag with the compiler. \n\n  declare var require: any;\n\nmodule MyModule &123;\n    export class SomeStuff &123;\n        doSomeStuff(condition: bool) &123;\n            if (condition) &123;\n                var x = require(./SomeModule);\n                var y = new x.MyClass();\n            &125;\n        &125;\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/19/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/19/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "324", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "TypeScript - conditional module import/export", "parent_id": "13444064", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Steve Fenton", "owner_user_id": "75525"},{"body": " Since it was suggested in the comments I will put up an answer. The call to  \n\n  glEnableClientState(GL_TEXTURE_COORD_ARRAY);\n  \n\n causes OpenGL to expect a pointer to an array of texture coordinates. When none was specified it threw a null pointer exception (attempt to read 0x00000000). The lesson here being dont enable client states unless you plan on defining the appropriate pointer. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/27/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "325", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Getting data from vector in an std::map", "parent_id": "13521367", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Pat", "owner_user_id": "894333"},{"body": "  INVEN_AMOUNT  is not validto be used with  having , But  SUM(INVEN_AMOUNT)  is vaild.  Having  is used for aggregate functions like sum(),avg() and max() etc otherwise use of  where  is better \n\n  SELECT PRODUCT_ID, SUM(INVEN_AMOUNT) as INVEN_AMOUNT,\nSUM(INVEN_MAX_STOCK), SUM(INVEN_REORDER_POINT) FROM INVENTORY\nGROUP BY PRODUCT_ID Having SUM(INVEN_AMOUNT) &gt; 900;