curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " you can create redirection with javascript \n\n  &lt;select name=\"abc\" onchange=\"redirect(this.value)\"&gt;\n     &lt;!-- your options here --&gt;\n&lt;/select&gt;\n\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;\n\nfunction redirect(value)&123;\n    window.location.href = \"http://www.yourdomain.com/\"+value;\n&125;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n  \n\n or you can try jquery. \n\n  &lt;select name=\"abc\" id=\"abc\"&gt;\n     &lt;!-- your options here --&gt;\n&lt;/select&gt;\n\n\n&lt;script type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;\n   $(document).ready(function()&123;\n        $(\"#abc\").change(function()&123;\n             window.location.href = $(this).val();\n        &125;);\n   &125;);\n&lt;/script&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/24/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/24/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "336", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "redirect to a specific page in php by getting data from 3 dropdown lists", "parent_id": "13540875", "comment_count": 15, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Vipan Kumar", "owner_user_id": "1645055"},{"body": " Assuming you know the number of elements in advance (or are recalculating your css on the fly somehow), then essentially what you have works if  put into a loop structure  which I originally discovered  here on stack overflow . \n\n  LESS Code  \n\n  .loop(@index) when (@index &gt; 0) &123;\n     //set top amount\n    &amp;:nth-of-type(@index) &123;\n        top: @index * 20px;\n    &125;\n\n     // next iteration\n     .loop(@index - 1);\n&125;\n\n// end the loop when index is 0\n.loop(0) &123;&125;\n\n.yourElem &123;\n    @n: 6; //num of elements (could skip this and just put number in)\n    .loop(@n);\n&125;\n  \n\n  Outputs  \n\n  .yourElem:nth-of-type(6) &123;\n  top: 120px;\n&125;\n.yourElem:nth-of-type(5) &123;\n  top: 100px;\n&125;\n.yourElem:nth-of-type(4) &123;\n  top: 80px;\n&125;\n.yourElem:nth-of-type(3) &123;\n  top: 60px;\n&125;\n.yourElem:nth-of-type(2) &123;\n  top: 40px;\n&125;\n.yourElem:nth-of-type(1) &123;\n  top: 20px;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "11/25/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/25/2012", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "337", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "less mixin or selector to change position based on sibling index?", "parent_id": "13554978", "comment_count": 1, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "ScottS", "owner_user_id": "369707"},{"body": " Your biggest problem in the database is here: \n\n   yearPublished  varchar(4) CHARACTER SET utf8 COLLATE utf8_bin DEFAULT NULL,  \n\n YearPublished should at least be an Integer or better an actual Date datatype. \n\n Using a varchar datatype, which is a string datatype, this SQL never returns any values: \n\n  $sqlQuery = mysql_query(\"SELECT yearPublished FROM books WHERE yearPublished &lt; $strBookPubYear\");  \n\n The less than symbol,  &lt;  cannot compare if a string value is \"less than\" some other string value. \n\n  Update  \n\n If you cant alter the structure of the table, you can use MySQLs  CONVERT function  to convert between data types. \n\n So something like this should work: \n\n  $sqlQuery = mysql_query(\"SELECT yearPublished FROM books WHERE CONVERT(yearPublished, SIGNED) &lt; CONVERT($strBookPubYear, SIGNED)\");  \n\n Since  $strBookPubYear  is a string coming in from the form submit, youll need to convert that too. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/27/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/27/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "11/27/2012", 