body": " The company I work for has recently released a GCM push notification service for Android to handle the server side complexity. The service is called AirBop - www.airbop.com. Its free to try and use for a small number of devices. I just thought Id mention it as another potential solution. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/30/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/30/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "349", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Do I must create my own server side to use google cloud messaging?", "parent_id": "13336316", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "hnatch", "owner_user_id": "1821022"},{"body": " I solved this problem straitforward - using pixel manipulation. \n\n Here is graphical answer: \n\n   \n\n Here is code: \n\n      function textHeight (text, font) &123;\n\n    var fontDraw = document.createElement(\"canvas\");\n\n    var height = 100;\n    var width = 100;\n\n    // here we expect that font size will be less canvas geometry\n    fontDraw.setAttribute(\"height\", height);\n    fontDraw.setAttribute(\"width\", width);\n\n    var ctx = fontDraw.getContext(2d);\n    // black is default\n    ctx.fillRect(0, 0, width, height);\n    ctx.textBaseline = top;\n    ctx.fillStyle = white;\n    ctx.font = font;\n    ctx.fillText(text/*Eg*/, 0, 0);\n\n    var pixels = ctx.getImageData(0, 0, width, height).data;\n\n    // row numbers where we first find letter end where it ends \n    var start = -1;\n    var end = -1;\n\n    for (var row = 0; row &lt; height; row++) &123;\n        for (var column = 0; column &lt; width; column++) &123;\n\n            var index = (row * width + column) * 4;\n\n            // if pixel is not white (background color)\n            if (pixels[index] == 0) &123;\n                // we havent met white (font color) pixel\n                // on the row and the letters was detected\n                if (column == width - 1 &amp;&amp; start != -1) &123;\n                    end = row;\n                    row = height;\n                    break;\n                &125;\n                continue;\n            &125;\n            else &123;\n                // we find top of letter\n                if (start == -1) &123;\n                    start = row;\n                &125;\n                // ..letters body\n                break;\n            &125;\n\n        &125;\n\n    &125;\n   /*\n    document.body.appendChild(fontDraw);\n    fontDraw.style.pixelLeft = 400;\n    fontDraw.style.pixelTop = 400;\n    fontDraw.style.position = \"absolute\";\n   */\n\n    return end - start;\n\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "12/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/05/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "12/05/2012", "id": "350", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How can you find the height of text on an HTML canvas?", "parent_id": "1134586", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "1290529", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Anton Putov", "owner_user_id": "1290529"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " If your running under Unix/Linux use Mono.UnixSignal \n\n I use this on my Linux apps. The advantage is that it will also detect a reboot or system shutdown. \n\n This example comes from  this Mono FAQ page  \n\n  // Catch SIGINT and SIGUSR1\nUnixSignal[] signals = new UnixSignal [] &123;\n    new UnixSignal (Mono.Unix.Native.Signum.SIGINT),\n    new UnixSignal (Mono.Unix.Native.Signum.SIGUSR1),\n&125;;\n\nThread signal_thread = new Thread (delegate () &123;\n    while (true) &123;\n        // Wait for a signal to be delivered\n        int index = UnixSignal.WaitAny (signals, -1);\n\n        Mono.Unix.Native.Signum signal = signals [index].Signum;\n\n        // Notify the main thread that a signal was received,\n    // you can use things like:\n    //    Application.Invoke () for Gtk#\n    //    Control.Invoke on Windows.Forms\n    //    Write to a pipe created with UnixPipes for server apps.\n    //    Use an AutoResetEvent\n\n    // For example, this works with Gtk#    \n    Application.Invoke (delegate () &123; ReceivedSignal (signal); &125;\n    &125;);\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "12/12/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/30/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "12/12/2012", "id": "351", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Add keyboard shortcuts to console application - mono compatible", "parent_id": "10283860", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "115425", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "FlappySocks", "owner_user_id": "115425"},{"body": " I do not think this is possible.  Try to remember the numbers you already generatedin a list and use it to generate more random numbersuntil you find one that is not in your list. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/01/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/01/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "352", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "random number generator from a range for continuos analysis", "parent_id": "13657426", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "sorencito", "owner_user_id": "1782868"},{"body": " Id recommend  writing a custom CellProcessor  to achieve this. The following processor can be placed at the start of each CellProcessor chain - it will simply delegate to the processor chained after it, and will suppress any cell processing exceptions.  \n\n  package example;\n\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.List;\nimport org.supercsv.cellprocessor.CellProcessorAdaptor;\nimport org.supercsv.cellprocessor.ift.CellProcessor;\nimport org.supercsv.exception.SuperCsvCellProcessorException;\nimport org.supercsv.util.CsvContext;\n\npublic class SuppressException extends CellProcessorAdaptor &123;\n\n    public static List&lt;SuperCsvCellProcessorException&gt; SUPPRESSED_EXCEPTIONS = \n            new ArrayList&lt;SuperCsvCellProcessorException&gt;();\n\n    public SuppressException(CellProcessor next) &123;\n        super(next);\n    &125;\n\n    public Object execute(Object value, CsvContext context) &123;\n        try &123;\n            // attempt to execute the next processor\n            return next.execute(value, context);\n\n        &125; catch (SuperCsvCellProcessorException e) &123;\n            // save the exception\n            SUPPRESSED_EXCEPTIONS.add(e);\n\n            // and suppress it (null is written as \"\")\n            return null;\n        &125;\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n\n And here it is in action: \n\n  package example;\n\nimport java.io.StringWriter;\nimport java.util.Arrays;\nimport java.util.List;\n\nimport org.supercsv.cellprocessor.constraint.NotNull;\nimport org.supercsv.cellprocessor.constraint.StrMinMax;\nimport org.supercsv.cellprocessor.ift.CellProcessor;\nimport org.supercsv.exception.SuperCsvCellProcessorException;\nimport org.supercsv.io.CsvBeanWriter;\nimport org.supercsv.io.ICsvBeanWriter;\nimport org.supercsv.prefs.CsvPreference;\n\npublic class TestSuppressExceptions &123;\n\n    private static final CellProcessor[] PROCESSORS = &123;\n            new SuppressException(new StrMinMax(0, 4)),\n            new SuppressException(new NotNull()) &125;;\n\n    private static final String[] HEADER = &123; \"name\", \"age\" &125;;\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception &123;\n\n        final StringWriter stringWriter = new StringWriter();\n        ICsvBeanWriter beanWriter = null;\n        try &123;\n            beanWriter = new CsvBeanWriter(stringWriter,\n                    CsvPreference.STANDARD_PREFERENCE);\n\n            beanWriter.writeHeader(HEADER);\n\n            // set up the data\n            Person valid = new Person(\"Rick\", 43);\n            Person nullAge = new Person(\"Lori\", null);\n            Person totallyInvalid = new Person(\"Shane\", null);\n            Person valid2 = new Person(\"Carl\", 12);\n            List&lt;Person&gt; people = Arrays.asList(valid, nullAge, totallyInvalid,\n                    valid2);\n\n            for (Person person : people) &123;\n                beanWriter.write(person, HEADER, PROCESSORS);\n\n                if (!SuppressException.SUPPRESSED_EXCEPTIONS.isEmpty()) &123;\n                    System.out.println(\"Suppressed exceptions for row \"\n                                        + beanWriter.getRowNumber() + \":\");\n                    for (SuperCsvCellProcessorException e :\n                                        SuppressException.SUPPRESSED_EXCEPTIONS) &123;\n                        System.out.println(e);\n                    &125;\n                    // clear ready for next row\n                    SuppressException.SUPPRESSED_EXCEPTIONS.clear();\n                &125;\n\n            &125;\n\n        &125; finally &123;\n            beanWriter.close();\n        &125;\n\n        // CSV will have empty columns for invalid data\n        System.out.println(stringWriter);\n\n    &125;\n\n&125;\n  \n\n Heres the suppressed exceptions output (row 4 has two exceptions, one for each column): \n\n  Suppressed exceptions for row 3:\norg.supercsv.exception.SuperCsvConstraintViolationException: null value \nencountered processor=org.supercsv.cellprocessor.constraint.NotNull\ncontext=&123;lineNo=3, rowNo=3, columnNo=2, rowSource=[Lori, null]&125;\nSuppressed exceptions for row 4:\norg.supercsv.exception.SuperCsvConstraintViolationException: the length (5) \nof value Shane does not lie between the min (0) and max (4) values (inclusive)\nprocessor=org.supercsv.cellprocessor.constraint.StrMinMax\ncontext=&123;lineNo=4, rowNo=4, columnNo=2, rowSource=[Shane, null]&125;\norg.supercsv.exception.SuperCsvConstraintViolationException: null value \nencountered processor=org.supercsv.cellprocessor.constraint.NotNull\ncontext=&123;lineNo=4, rowNo=4, columnNo=2, rowSource=[Shane, null]&125;\n  \n\n And the CSV output \n\n  name,age\nRick,43\nLori,\n,\nCarl,12\n  \n\n Notice how the invalid values were written as  \"\"  because the  SuppressException  processor returned  null  for those values (not that youd use the CSV output anyway, as its not valid!). \n", "last_activity_date": "12/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/01/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "12/02/2012", "id": "353", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Validate every field in a single pass with SuperCSV", "parent_id": "13646982", "comment_count": 8, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "1068649", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Hound Dog", "owner_user_id": "1068649"},{"body": " Assuming you have an array of  char *  and that you know the length of the array: \n\n Loop on the array, and swap the element at position  i  with the element at position  n - i - 1 , where  n  is the length of the array. \n\n For  n  = 10, you get: \n\n  i = 0, n - i - 1 = 9\ni = 1, n - i - 1 = 8\ni = 2, n - i - 1 = 7\ni = 3, n - i - 1 = 6\ni = 4, n - i - 1 = 5\n  \n\n Remember to stop looping when you reach  n / 2 . \n", "last_activity_date": "12/03/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/03/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "354", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Reverse string list order", "parent_id": "13692854", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Danilo Piazzalunga", "owner_user_id": "238421"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Got it to work. I guess it needed an argument to work: \n\n  C#  \n\n          String method = \"&lt;invoke name=E&#39\\\\&#39\"NewFilenameE&#39\\\\&#39\" returntype=E&#39\\\\&#39\"xmlE&#39\\\\&#39\"&gt;&lt;arguments&gt;&lt;string&gt;\"+sfd.FileName+\"&lt;/string&gt;&lt;/arguments&gt;&lt;/invoke&gt;\";\n        mainFlashControl.CallFunction(method);\n  \n\n  AS3  \n\n      public function Main():void \n    &123;\n        if (stage) init();\n        else addEventListener(Event.ADDED_TO_STAGE, init);\n    &125;\n\n    private function init(e:Event = null):void \n    &123;\n        removeEventListener(Event.ADDED_TO_STAGE, init);\n        _mainState = new MainState();\n        addChild(_mainState);\n        _editState = new EditState();\n        addChild(_editState);\n        _selectKeyState = new SelectKeyState();\n        addChild(_selectKeyState);\n\n        if (ExternalInterface.available)\n        &123;\n            ExternalInterface.addCallback (\"NewFilename\",NewFilename);\n        &125;   \n    &125;\n\n\n    public function NewFilename(s:String):Boolean\n    &123;\n        _mainState.visible = false;\n        var th:TextHandle = new TextHandle(s, 100);\n        th.y = 200;\n        this.addChild(th);\n        return true;\n    &125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "12/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/05/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "355", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Getting HRESULT E_FAIL when trying to call a method in AS3 from C#", "parent_id": "13715739", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "joon", "owner_user_id": "514534"},{"body": " See, \n\n  http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/UserGuide/JPA/Basic_JPA_Development/Caching  \n\n For the same EntityManager JPA always requires that one==two, so this is correct, not matter your caching options (this is the L1 cache, or transactional cache, which enforces your transaction isolation and maintains object identity). \n\n To force the query to refresh (and revert any changes you have made) you can use the query hint \"eclipselink.refresh\"=\"true\".  Or probably better, use a new EntityManager for each query/request, or call clear() on your EntityManager. \n\n  &lt;property name=\"eclipselink.cache.shared.default\" value=\"false\"/&gt;\n  \n\n Is the correct way to disable the shared cache (L2 cache).  Please remove all your other settings as they are not correct, and can cause issues. \n\n EclipseLink does not maintain a query cache by default, so those settings will have no affect. CacheUsage is also not correct, do not use this (it is for in-memory querying). \n", "last_activity_date": "12/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/05/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "356", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Disable caching in JPA (eclipselink)", "parent_id": "2809275", "comment_count": 1, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "James", "owner_user_id": "416206"},{"body": "  template&lt;template&lt;class T, class A&gt; class container&gt;\nstd::ostream&amp; opertaor &lt;&lt; ( std::ostream&amp;, const container&lt;X, std::allocator&lt;X&gt; &gt; &amp;)\n&123;\n&125;\n  \n\n This wont work if on your implementation vector, list, etc. have more than 2 template parameters. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/05/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "357", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to write a streaming &#39;operator&lt;&lt;&#39; that can take arbitary containers (of type &#39;X&#39;)?", "parent_id": "13724766", "comment_count": 4, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Armen Tsirunyan", "owner_user_id": "469935"},{"body": "  -  First makes sure you have added  ErrorScreen Activity  in the  AndroidManifest.xml  file. \n\n  -  I am not sure when you are calling this  init()  method, but i am sure this piece of code should be triggered as soon as you check the condition, for example inside the  onClick()  method of  OnClickListener . \n", "last_activity_date": "12/14/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/14/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "358", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Failed to display an error message page in my Android program", "parent_id": "13871294", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Kumar Vivek Mitra", "owner_user_id": "1293744"},{"body": " You can do this with the  HTML5 Video  tag and JavaScript \n\n  &lt;video id=\"videoClip\" width=\"111\" height=\"63\" controls=\"controls\" autoplay=\"autoplay\"&gt;\n  &lt;source src=\"video/videoclip.m4v\" type=\"video/m4v\"&gt;\n&lt;/video&gt;\n  \n\n This JavaScript will wait until the video is loaded, then start at 2 sec. \n\n  document.getElementById(videoClip).addEventListener(loadedmetadata, function() &123;\n  this.currentTime = 2;\n&125;, false);\n  \n\n The video tag can be styled using CSS to make it look like you iframe solution. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/05/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/05/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "359", "favorite_