curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " If you use linux, feel free to try  erl -man ModuleName , e.g.  erl -man erlang  \n", "last_activity_date": "03/20/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/20/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "566", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Searchable, offline Erlang documentation?", "parent_id": "15514617", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "danechkin", "owner_user_id": "570726"},{"body": "  Denormalization  has its place. For example a table with forum topics also has a  PostCount  column, opposed to doing a  COUNT(posts)  for every topic. If you are worried about consistency, and you should, you can schedule regular checks (for example on each transaction from or to a given user) where you test if each users  Balance  matches the sum of their transactions. \n", "last_activity_date": "03/21/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/21/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "567", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Best practice for storing credit balance in web application", "parent_id": "15543462", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "CodeCaster", "owner_user_id": "266143"},{"body": " Without being a Mongo expert and without knowing your db fields Id come up with something like this. Perhaps you can build upon this: \n\n  db.aggregData.aggregate(\n&123; \n    $project:&123; \n        CrawledTweets: 1,\n        groupedTime: &123; \n            year:&123;$year:\"$_id\"&125;, \n            month: &123;$month:\"$_id\"&125;, \n            day: &123;$dayOfMonth:\"$_id\"&125;, \n            hour: &123;$hour: \"$_id\"&125;, \n            min: &123;$minute: \"$_id\"&125;\n        &125;   \n    &125;   \n&125;,\n&123; \n    $group: &123;\n        _id: &123; groupedTime: \"$CrawledTweets\" &125;,\n        tweets: &123; $sum: \"$tweets\"&125;\n    &125;   \n&125;\n)\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "03/21/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/21/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "03/21/2013", "id": "568", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Aggregation Framework on Date", "parent_id": "15527270", "comment_count": 3, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "431012", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "pitseeker", "owner_user_id": "1611362"},{"body": " Im not quite sure, but I think youre asking what the difference between calling the jQuery  .on()  method and the jQuery  .click()  method, right? \n\n As in: \n\n  $someEl.on(click, someFunc);\n// or\n$someEl.click(someFunc);\n  \n\n Like this, both are pretty much equivalent. However with the .on() method you have the opportunity to introduce namespacing (explained in the first link) to your elements events. Like so: \n\n  $someEl.on(click.do1, someFunc1);\n$someEl.on(click.do2, someFunc2);\n  \n\n So if in a later progress you want to remove or trigger only one of your callback functions (someFunc1, someFunc2), youll be able to do so by calling: \n\n  $someEl.off(click.do1);\n$someEl.trigger(click.do2);\n  \n\n Hope this helps \n", "last_activity_date": "03/21/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/21/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "569", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What are the pros and cons of calling jQuery functionality via these 2 different methods?", 