: 0, "author_name": "Oleksandr Pshenychnyy", "owner_user_id": "543591"},{"body": " If you are constrained to using .Net2.0, then dont bother trying to load assemblies targeting later versions of .Net. Its doomed to failure. If you want to use Linq, target > =.Net3.5, if you need to target .Net2.0, dont use Linq. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/10/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/10/2013", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "596", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Unable to load .dll?", "parent_id": "15924299", "comment_count": 0, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "spender", "owner_user_id": "14357"},{"body": " If you just want to get rid of the 1k label, you can keep the max:1000, but add a custom formatter function like this: \n\n  yAxis: &123;\n            endOnTick: false,\n            type: logarithmic,\n            minorTickInterval: 0.1,\n            min: 1,\n            max: 1000,\n            labels:&123;\n                formatter:function() &123;\n                    if (this.value==1000) &123;\n                        return \"\";\n                    &125; else &123;\n                        return this.value;\n                    &125;\n                &125;\n            &125;\n        &125;,\n  \n\n  http://jsfiddle.net/hA9yF/  \n\n This still wont work if you set max:999, but may be a suitable work-around for you. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/11/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/11/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "597", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "HighChart using min max on logarithmic axis lack minor ticks grid", "parent_id": "15945117", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "SteveP", "owner_user_id": "1386720"},{"body": " Im guessing it does exactly what every other GUI toolkit does, which is try to execute that function for every button press. If you dont want that, then there are several approaches you can take: \n\n \n Disable the button until the function finishes \n Use a sentinel value, like self.running, and add a check to see if it is True. If so, return. Otherwise, set it to True and execute. Just remember to set it back to False at the end of the function \n Do what you mentioned and disconnect the function from the signal \n \n\n Those are the main ones. Im sure there are some more esoteric solutions out there too though. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/11/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/11/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "598", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Preventing PySide from Outrunning Python", "parent_id": "15914992", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mike Driscoll", "owner_user_id": "393194"},{"body": " change  \n\n   ddlLocation.Items.Insert(0, \"----Select an Item----\");\n  \n\n to \n\n  ddlLocation.Items.Insert(0, new ListItem(\"----Select an Item----\", \"1\"));\n  \n\n because you have given initial value of  RequiredFieldValidator  as 1  \n\n You can give initial value which will not in the data you bind to drop down list  \n\n If you insert item without creating list item, the value field of that item will be null value. then you cant give value to initial value field of the  RequiredFieldValidator  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/12/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/12/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "04/12/2013", "id": "599", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to ignore the first index in required field validation", "parent_id": "15962580", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "2558060", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Damith", "owner_user_id": "2558060"},{"body": " The  Run  method  must  block. From  the docs : \n\n \n   If you do override the Run method, your code should block indefinitely. If the Run method returns, the role is automatically recycled by raising the Stopping event and calling the OnStop method so that your shutdown sequences may be executed before the role is taken offline. \n \n\n A simple solution is to just do this: \n\n  public override void Run()\n&123;\n  RunAsync().Wait();\n&125;\n\npublic async Task RunAsync()\n&123;\n  while (true)\n  &123;\n    await Task.Delay(60000);\n  &125;\n&125;\n  \n\n Alternatively, you can use   AsyncContext  from my AsyncEx library : \n\n  public override void Run()\n&123;\n  AsyncContext.Run(async () =&gt;\n  &123;\n    while (true)\n    &123;\n      await Task.Delay(60000);\n    &125;\n  &125;);\n&125;\n  \n\n Whichever option you choose,  Run  should  not  be  async . Its kind of like  Main  for a Console app ( see my blog for why  async Main  is not allowed ). \n", "last_activity_date": "04/13/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/13/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "04/13/2013", "id": "600", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Async/await in azure worker role causing the role to recycle", "parent_id": "15991287", "comment_count": 3, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "263693", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Stephen Cleary", "owner_user_id": "263693"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Ive written a  UIGestureRecognizer  subclass for that purpose once. It only tracks the vertical translation. Maybe that helps you. You can use it as any other gesture recognizer, just set the threshold and track the translation in the its targets action method. \n\n VerticalPanGestureRecognizer.h \n\n  #import &lt;UIKit/UIKit.h&gt;\n#import &lt;UIKit/UIGestureRecognizerSubclass.h&gt;\n\n@interface VerticalPanGestureRecognizer : UIGestureRecognizer\n\n@property (assign, nonatomic)float translation;\n@property (assign, nonatomic)float offsetThreshold;\n\n@end\n  \n\n VerticalPanGestureRecognizer.m \n\n  #import \"VerticalPanGestureRecognizer.h\"\n\n@interface VerticalPanGestureRecognizer ()\n&123;\n    CGPoint _startPoint;\n&125;\n@end\n\n@implementation VerticalPanGestureRecognizer\n\n- (void)touchesBegan:(NSSet *)touches withEvent:(UIEvent *)event\n&123;\n    if ([touches count] &gt; 1) &123;\n        self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateFailed;\n    &125;\n    else\n    &123;\n        _startPoint = [[touches anyObject] locationInView:self.view];\n    &125;\n&125;\n\n- (void)touchesMoved:(NSSet *)touches withEvent:(UIEvent *)event\n&123;\n    if (self.state == UIGestureRecognizerStateFailed || self.state == UIGestureRecognizerStateCancelled) &123;\n        return;\n    &125;\n    CGPoint currentLocation = [[touches anyObject] locationInView:self.view];\n    CGPoint translation;\n    translation.x = currentLocation.x - _startPoint.x;\n    translation.y = currentLocation.y - _startPoint.y;        \n\n    if (self.state == UIGestureRecognizerStatePossible)\n    &123;\n        //if the x-translation is above our threshold the gesture fails \n        if (fabsf(translation.x) &gt; offsetThreshold)\n            self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateFailed;\n        //if the y-translation has reached the threshold the gesture is recognized and the we start sending action methods\n        else if (fabsf(translation.y) &gt; offsetThreshold)\n            self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateBegan;\n\n        return;                \n    &125;        \n    //if we reached this point the gesture was succesfully recognized so we now enter changed state\n    self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateChanged;\n\n    //we are just insterested in the vertical translation\n    self.translation = translation.y;\n&125;\n\n- (void)touchesEnded:(NSSet *)touches withEvent:(UIEvent *)event\n&123;\n    //if at this point the state is still possible the threshold wasnt reached at all so we fail\n    if (self.state == UIGestureRecognizerStatePossible)\n    &123;\n        self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateFailed;\n    &125;\n    else\n    &123;\n        CGPoint currentLocation = [[touches anyObject] locationInView:self.view];\n        CGPoint translation;\n        translation.x = _startPoint.x - currentLocation.x;\n        translation.y = _startPoint.y - currentLocation.y;\n        self.translation = translation.y;\n        self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateEnded;\n    &125;\n\n&125;\n\n- (void)touchesCancelled:(NSSet *)touches withEvent:(UIEvent *)event\n&123;\n    self.state = UIGestureRecognizerStateCancelled;\n&125;\n\n- (void)reset\n&123;\n    [super reset];\n    _startPoint = CGPointZero;\n&125;\n\n@end\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/14/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/14/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "601", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "I&#39;ve made UIPanGestureRecognizer only detect mostly vertical pans, how do I make it only detect REALLY vertical pans?", "parent_id": "16003613", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Tobi", "owner_user_id": "384916"},{"body": " Python doesnt support wildcards directly in filenames to the  open()  call. Youll need to use the   glob  module  instead to load files from a single level of subdirectories, or use   os.walk()   to walk an arbitrary directory structure. \n\n Opening all text files in all subdirectories, one level deep: \n\n  import glob\n\nfor filename in glob.iglob(os.path.join(Test, *, *.txt)):\n    with open(filename) as f:\n        # one file open, handle it, next loop will present you with a new file.\n  \n\n Opening all text files in an arbitrary nesting of directories: \n\n  import os\nimport fnmatch\n\nfor dirpath, dirs, files in os.walk(Test):\n    for filename in fnmatch.filter(files, *.txt):\n        with open(os.path.join(dirpath, filename)):\n            # one file open, handle it, next loop will present you with a new file.\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/15/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/15/2013", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "04/15/2013", "id": "602", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Python: Reading all files in all directories", "parent_id": "16015955", "comment_count": 2, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "1219006", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Martijn Pieters", "owner_user_id": "100297"},{"body": " In case there is no answer to this.. I discovered I can work around this relatively easily by simply inventing a new pat on the server that is specifically for updating the record I am interested in and using POST for that one also. That means that Create and Update record can both use POST but to different URLs.\nCormac \n", "last_activity_date": "04/23/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/23/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "603", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Want to update a record via a PUT REST API", "parent_id": "16150777", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "cormackeogh", "owner_user_id": "2298589"},{"body": " When your jQuery adds a new row, increment a counter variable in your form, then in your perl code use that to loop through your vars (this will work best as a post but you can use a get if you need to) and read up each line you need. \n\n Put another way, in your HTML form create an input field that is hidden named tierCount\nThen in your jQuery to add a new row update it to the number in place \nYou also need to only use 1 increment variable when adding the new rows  \n\n then in your perl script you read the form value of tierCount and loop through the form vars reading them in one set at a time \n\n  &lt;input type=\"hidden\" name=\"tierCount\" value=\"1\" /&gt;  \nE&#39\\\\&#39$(&lt;tr id=\"inctier+ (raisetierid++) +\"&gt;&lt;TD ALIGN=left&gt;&lt;font color=\"#ADD8E6\"&gt;Tier + (raisetierid) + Rate&lt;/TD&gt;&lt;TD ALIGN=left&gt;&lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"tierrate+ (raisetierid) +\" size=10 value=\"00.00\" &gt;&lt;/TD&gt;&lt;TD ALIGN=left&gt;&lt;font color=\"#ADD8E6\"&gt;Tier + (raisetierid) + Range&lt;/TD&gt;&lt;TD ALIGN=left&gt;&lt;font color=\"#ADD8E6\"&gt;Minimum&amp;nbsp;&lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"rangemin+ (raisetierid) +\" size=10 value=\"\" &gt;&lt;font color=\"#ADD8E6\"&gt;&amp;nbsp;Maximum&amp;nbsp;&lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"rangemax+ (raisetierid) +\" size=10 value=\"\" &gt;&lt;/TD&gt;).appendTo(\"#inctier1\");  \n\n$(#tierCount).val(raisetierid);\n\nmy $tierCount = $form&123;\"tierCount\"&125;\n# Since we start with tier 1 start at 1 instead of the usual 0\nfor (my $i = 1; $i &lt;= $tierCount; $i++)\n&123;\n    my $rate = $form&123;\"rateField\" . $i&125;;\n    my $range = $form&123;\"rangeField\" . $i&125;;\n    # Etc, etc\n    # then do your insert here for that row\n&125;  \n  \n\n Note that the code above does not have any error checking in place  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/15/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/15/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "604", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Perl using Jquery to display html onclick looped database insert", "parent_id": "15352796", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "dougis", "owner_user_id": "1630860"},{"body": " The  enum  keyword is part of the Java language.  Enum  is the name of the  Class  object that represents an  enum ; that is, it is the common base class for all  enum  values. It defines the methods that all enum objects inherit:  name() ,  ordinal() , etc. Think of it like an analogy question from the old SAT:  enum  is to  Enum  as  class  is to  Object . \n\n Always use  enum  in your code for declaring enumerations. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/15/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/15/2013", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "605", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Difference between uppercase Enum and lowercase enum", "parent_id": "16018528", "comment_count": 3, "score": 6, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Ted Hopp", "owner_user_id": "535871"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Local database access vs. remote will show a significant difference in speed.  Since youve not provided any specifics I cant zero in on the issue but I can make a suggestion: \n\n Try  caching  your queries and views as much as possible.  This will reduce the amount of queries you need to do.  This works well especially for static data like menus. \n\n  Optimization  is the key.  Make sure you eliminate as many unnecessary queries as you can, and those queries you make only request the fields you need using the  select  method. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/15/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/15/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "606", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Slow remote queries", "parent_id": "16022045", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Richard Brown", "owner_user_id": "704832"},{"body": "  #inner  using a percentage height means it is based off of the height of its parent  #outer , which is not specified as an exact  %  or  px : \n\n  #area &123;\n    position: absolute;\n    top:0;\n    left:0;\n    right:0;\n    bottom:0;\n    padding: 20px;\n    box-sizing: border-box;\n&125;\n\n#outer,#inner &123;\n    min-width: 100%;\n    min-height: 100%;\n&125;\n\n#outer &123;\n    height:100%;\n    overflow: auto;\n&125;\n  \n\n  jsFiddle provided here , which shows with color that  #inner  gets the full height of  #outer . \n\n I also took a few liberties. I set your  #area  CSS to be a more proper full height/width setup, and i made your scrolling component  #outer  instead of  #area , since  #inner  will be the content that overflows it. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/16/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/16/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "04/16/2013", "id": "607", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "nested min-height does not work", "parent_id": "16043519", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1968099", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "PlantTheIdea", "owner_user_id": "1968099"},{"body": " You can use: \n\n \n  Screen.PrimaryScreen  \n  Screen.WorkingArea  \n \n\n \n\n  System.Drawing.Rectangle workingRectangle = Screen.PrimaryScreen.WorkingArea;\nthis.Left = workingRectangle.Width - this.Width;\nthis.Top = workingRectangle.Height - this.Height;\nthis.Show();\n  \n\n Above code need to be called whenever notification icon is clicked. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/16/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/16/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "608", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Creating a Notify Icon Form", "parent_id": "16043679", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Abhinav", "owner_user_id": "1589074"},{"body": " You have an array of char* called command.  But you havent allocated any memory for the pointers in the array, or even set them to null.  SO theyre random values, pointing to random memory locations.  Strcpy is then overwriting those random locations, causing a seg fault.  You need to allocate memory for those pointers by  command[i]=new char[80]  on all 5 rows first. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/17/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "609", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "C++ Assignment, strcpy and strlen with character arrays n pointers", "parent_id": "16051136", "comment_count": 1, "score": 4, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Gabe Sechan", "owner_user_id": "1631193"},{"body": " You can setup all the tables you need to query in your big database as copies of the data in the other 3 through replication. The linked question does not work at all if you have data on separate machines (\"databases\" is kind of ambiguous since it could mean schemas or machines). Personally I would go with the replication route if you are aggregating data from multiple machines. You can ready more about replication here:  http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.5/en/replication.html  \n\n if you have multiple schemas in one machine you need to query then the answer is very simple and in the linked question above. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/18/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/18/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "610", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What is the best practice to have one large database with fed information from other 3 databases?", "parent_id": "16094411", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Daniel Williams", "owner_user_id": "1698887"},{"body": " You are looking for  Kleene star . Not tested, but seems that  RLTK  gem can give you such functionality. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/24/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/24/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "611", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Rails loop through &#39;A..Z&#39; and beyond?", "parent_id": "16181831", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "fotanus", "owner_user_id": "413494"},{"body": " You could make the root logger TRACE level (all messages) and put a ThresholdFilter on the Console so that only some messages are displayed on the console. \n\n This configuration will log only ERROR messages to the console, and at the same time will log all messages (TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, ERROR...) to the debug.txt file. Error and higher messages are logged both in the console and in the file: \n\n  &lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n&lt;configuration status=\"ERROR\"&gt;\n    &lt;appenders&gt;\n        &lt;Console name=\"CONSOLE\" target=\"SYSTEM_OUT\"&gt;\n            &lt;ThresholdFilter level=\"ERROR\" onMatch=\"ACCEPT\" onMismatch=\"DENY\"/&gt;\n            &lt;PatternLayout pattern=\"%d %-5p %C&123;2&125; (%F:%L) - %m%n\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/Console&gt;\n        &lt;File name=\"DEBUG_FILE\" fileName=\"debug.txt\"&gt;\n            &lt;PatternLayout pattern=\"%d %-5p %C&123;2&125; (%F:%L) - %m%n\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/File&gt;\n    &lt;/appenders&gt;\n    &lt;loggers&gt;\n        &lt;root level=\"trace\"&gt;\n            &lt;appender-ref ref=\"CONSOLE\" /&gt;\n            &lt;appender-ref ref=\"DEBUG_FILE\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/root&gt;\n    &lt;/loggers&gt; \n&lt;/configuration&gt;\n  \n\n By the way, please be aware that your pattern layout contains conversion patterns that require location information ( %C, %F and %L , to be exact).\nThis means that for every log message, log4j2 needs to take a snapshot of the stack, and then walk the stack trace to find the class and method that did the logging. \n\n This is  very, very slow .  \n\n Logging will be 2-5 times slower for synchronous logging and 4-20 times slower for asynchronous logging. \n\n If performance is not an issue then it doesnt matter, but it is definitely something to be aware of. Personally I just use %c (the logger name) and my apps log messages are unique enough that I can quickly find where the message came from. Just my 2 cents. \n\n --- update 04/27/2013 ---\nI have since learned a simpler way to do this: you can set a level on the appender-ref. \n\n  &lt;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?&gt;\n&lt;configuration status=\"debug\"&gt;\n    &lt;appenders&gt;\n        &lt;Console name=\"CONSOLE\" target=\"SYSTEM_OUT\"&gt;\n            &lt;PatternLayout pattern=\"%d %-5p %c&123;2&125; - %m%n\" /&gt; &lt;!--without location--&gt;\n        &lt;/Console&gt;\n        &lt;File name=\"DEBUG_FILE\" fileName=\"debug.txt\"&gt;\n            &lt;PatternLayout pattern=\"%d %-5p %c&123;2&125; - %m%n\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/File&gt;\n    &lt;/appenders&gt;\n    &lt;loggers&gt;\n        &lt;root level=\"debug\"&gt;\n            &lt;appender-ref ref=\"CONSOLE\" level=\"INFO\" /&gt;\n            &lt;appender-ref ref=\"DEBUG_FILE\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/root&gt;\n    &lt;/loggers&gt; \n&lt;/configuration&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/27/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "04/27/2013", "id": "612", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "log4j2 configuration", "parent_id": "16042628", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "1446916", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Remko Popma", "owner_user_id": "1446916"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I recommend not using default scope for conditions, just for ordering. \n\n So I would add a named scope in each model and then use that scope for most queries, e.g. \n\n Rails 3 \n\n  scope :confirmed, :conditions =&gt; &123; age &lt; ?,100 &125;\n  \n\n Rails 4 \n\n  Some scopes are moving to be class methods (what they basically are anyway) so you can use something like:  \n\n  def age_limit\n  where :age &lt; 100\nend\n  \n\n More info on using scopes at :  http://stackoverflow.com/a/5609947/631619  \n\n Having the same code in more than model is somewhat undry but this is the routes I would take for less than a dozen models.  You could also create a Constant AGE_LIMIT but then system constant are fraught with issues.  You might be better of creating a model perhaps just for age, then have a model for max_age, then refer to that. Something like that. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/17/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "613", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to automatically add extra condition to all Models in Rails?", "parent_id": "9797848", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Michael Durrant", "owner_user_id": "631619"},{"body": " Adding to the excellent answers above, make sure you compare the output of re.match with None: \n\n  &gt;&gt;&gt; timeit(None is None)\n0.03676295280456543\n&gt;&gt;&gt; timeit(bool(None))\n0.1125330924987793\n&gt;&gt;&gt; timeit(re.match(\"a\",\"abc\") is None, import re)\n1.0200879573822021\n&gt;&gt;&gt; timeit(bool(re.match(\"a\",\"abc\")), import re)\n1.134294033050537\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/17/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "614", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Python, fastest way to iterate over regular expressions but stop on first match", "parent_id": "10591068", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Anuj Gupta", "owner_user_id": "1678159"},{"body": " You could also avoid recursion and use in-built predicates for type conversions: \n\n  my_digits(Number, List) :-\n    atomic_list_concat(List, Atom),\n    atom_number(Atom, Number).\n  \n\n The first line converts the list to an atom, and the second line converts this atom to a number, which will give true if that number is the same as that passed in. \n\n I dont know if there is an even more direct way to convert the list into a number (dont think so..), in which case it could be achieved in a single line. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/17/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "615", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Prolog converting integer to a list of digit", "parent_id": "16047339", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "magus", "owner_user_id": "1204362"},{"body": " The problem is that  boost::format  takes arguments by reference (not a copy), and a reference can not be bound to a bitfield. \n\n You can solve this by converting the value to a temporary.  One succinct way would be to apply the unary  operator + . \n\n   cout &lt;&lt; format(\"io = %d E&#39\\\\&#39n\") % +b.io;  // NOW Okay\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/17/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/17/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "616", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to print bit field with boost format", "parent_id": "16069198", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Drew Dormann", "owner_user_id": "16287"},{"body": " Have you tried using  StringEntity ? Above code can be updated to use  StringEntity , Following is the resulting code: \n\n  HttpClient httpclient = new DefaultHttpClient();\nHttpPost httppost = new HttpPost(posturl);\n\n\nhttppost.setEntity(new StringEntity(\"your string\"));    \nHttpResponse resp = httpclient.execute(httppost);\nHttpEntity ent = resp.getEntity();\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/18/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/18/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "617", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Send a string on Android with HttpPost without using nameValuePairs", "parent_id": "16079991", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Praful Bhatnagar", "owner_user_id": "286453"},{"body": " Regular expression  MatchObject  results include indices of the match. What remains is to match repeating characters: \n\n  import re\n\nrepeat = re.compile(r(?P&lt;start&gt;[a-z])(?P=start)+-?)\n  \n\n would match only if a given letter character ( a - z ) is repeated at least once: \n\n  &gt;&gt;&gt; for match in repeat.finditer(\"aaaaabbbbbbbbbbbbbbccccccccccc\"):\n...     print match.group(), match.start(), match.end()\n... \naaaaa 0 5\nbbbbbbbbbbbbbb 5 19\nccccccccccc 19 30\n  \n\n The   .start()   and   .end()   methods on the match result give you the exact positions in the input string. \n\n Dashes are included in the matches, but not non-repeating characters: \n\n  &gt;&gt;&gt; for match in repeat.finditer(\"a-bb-cccccccc\"):\n...     print match.group(), match.start(), match.end()\n... \nbb- 2 5\ncccccccc 5 13\n  \n\n If you want the  a-  part to be a match, simply replace the  +  with a  *  multiplier: \n\n  repeat = re.compile(r(?P&lt;start&gt;[a-z])(?P=start)*-?)\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/18/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/18/2013", "votes_count": 12, "last_edit_date": "04/18/2013", "id": "618", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Python split string by pattern", "parent_id": "16086847", "comment_count": 3, "score": 11, "last_editor_user_id": "100297", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Martijn Pieters", "owner_user_id": "100297"},{"body": " you can use pointer like this \n\n  #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;\n\nint *ptr;\n\n\nint main (void)\n&123;\n  int my_array[] = &123;1,23,17,4,-5,100&125;;\n   ptr=my_array;//you can use ptr++ to get next pointer\n\n for(i=0;i&lt;size_of_array;i++)\n&123;\n\n   printf(\"%dE&#39\\\\&#39n\",*(ptr));\n   prt++;\n&125;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/26/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/26/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "619", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to write a loop and pointer arithmetic", "parent_id": "16232850", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "One Man Crew", "owner_user_id": "2004810"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " I wrote \" On proper performance testing of Java JSON processing \" a while ago, to enumerate common problems I have seen with performance benchmarking. There are lots of relatively simple ways to mess up comparison. I am assuming you are not making any of mistakes mentioned, but it is worth mentioning. \nEspecially part about using raw input: there are very few cases where real JSON data comes as  String  -- so make sure to use  InputStream  /  OutputStream  (or byte arrays). \n\n Second thing to note that is that if you use tree model (like  JsonObject ) you are already adding lots of potentially avoidable overhead: you are building a  Map / List  structures that use 3x memory that POJOs would use; and are slower to operate on.\nIn this case, actual parsing/generation overhead is typically minority component anyway.\nSometimes tree style processing makes sense, and this is acceptable overhead. \n\n So if performance matters a lot, one typically either: \n\n \n Uses streaming API to build your own objects -- not an in-memory tree, or \n Uses data-binding to/from POJOs. This can be close to speed of (1) \n \n\n both of which will be faster than building trees (and to some degree, serializing).\nFor some reason many developers somehow assume that dealing with tree representations is as efficient way to deal with data as any -- this is not the case, and seen in benchmarks like  https://github.com/eishay/jvm-serializers  \n\n I did not see Jackson-related code via link, so I am assuming it works as expected.\nThe main things to look for (wrt performance probs) really are to: \n\n \n Always close  JsonParser  and  JsonGenerator  (needed for some of recycling) and \n Reuse  JsonFactory  and/or  ObjectMapper  instances: they are thread-safe, reuse of some components (symbol tables, serializers) occurs through these objects. \n As mentioned earlier, always use most raw input/output destinations if possible ( InputStream ,  OutputStream ). \n \n", "last_activity_date": "04/21/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/21/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "620", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "jackson vs json simple for stream parsing", "parent_id": "16120560", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "StaxMan", "owner_user_id": "59501"},{"body": " One possible cause (but not necessarily  the  cause) for the discrepancy that you are seeing is that both the  mongo  shell and the  mongod  server  use Googles v8 Javascript engine  by default (though it can be configured to use Spidermonkey as an alternative) for interpreting the commands that you give. \n\n Googles v8 sees hotspots in Javascript code and is likely to JIT code that is frequently used. \n\n On the other hand, vanilla PyMongo is  written in pure Python , which means that it will always be interpreted, which is something that has a considerable overhead. \n\n If you are not doing so already, one possibility would be to use the  PyMongo extension written in C  instead of default one or, if the rest of your application is compatible, use the PyPy JIT interpreter for Python. \n\n If you use any distribution derived from Debian (like Ubuntu), the package  python-pymongo-ext  provides you the precompiled version of the C version of PyMongo. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/22/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/22/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "621", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "MongoDB performance of db.eval() in javascript shell vs. pymongo", "parent_id": "15422243", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "rbrito", "owner_user_id": "962311"},{"body": " Maybe the character encoding messes around. Especially the \"@\" character might get messed up. Writing a batch application echo your argument will show you, if you can exclude this.  \n\n Do u have enclosed the subject in quotes? Otherwise a space might mess up the arguments. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/22/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/22/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "622", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Sending email issue VB.net", "parent_id": "16139127", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Marius", "owner_user_id": "2164448"},{"body": " EDIT: The sample I copy/pasted was not a correct one. The option I was looking to offer is using  CompileAssemblyFromFile . Sample code cold be obtained  here  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/22/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/22/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "04/22/2013", "id": "623", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "C# Compile Visual Studio Program", "parent_id": "16157830", "comment_count": 3, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "14395", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "galets", "owner_user_id": "14395"},{"body": " Have you gone through  Spring Security Core . \nIts nice framework for security purpose.. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/23/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/23/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "624", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Controllers in Grails", "parent_id": "485490", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "swapy", "owner_user_id": "1578304"},{"body": " I was finally able to find the solution in the Google Maps v2 sample code, which is located at  &lt;android-sdk-folder&gt;E&#39\\\\&#39extrasE&#39\\\\&#39googleE&#39\\\\&#39google_play_servicesE&#39\\\\&#39samplesE&#39\\\\&#39mapsE&#39\\\\&#39 . See  https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/android/intro#sample_code . What helped me was the file  srcE&#39\\\\&#39comE&#39\\\\&#39exampleE&#39\\\\&#39mapdemoE&#39\\\\&#39ProgrammaticDemoActivity.java . \n\n What was happening was that the application got shutdown completely, so its  onCreate()  method was called again. There you have to somehow find out whether you have already created the map fragment or not. The solution is to try to find a tag of your map fragment. If it cant be found, it means the activity is running for the first time. You create your fragment and add the tag to it. Then the next time the  onCreate()  gets called, your fragment can be found by the tag and all the settings and listeners are preserved. \n\n So you can for example set a final static variable in your activity:  private static final String MAP_FRAGMENT_TAG = \"map\";  \n\n and then use this code in your  onCreate()  method: \n\n  mapFragment = (MapFragment) getFragmentManager().findFragmentByTag(MAP_FRAGMENT_TAG);\nif (mapFragment == null) &123;\n    mapFragment = MapFragment.newInstance();\n    FragmentTransaction fragmentTransaction = getFragmentManager().beginTransaction();\n    fragmentTransaction.add(R.id.fragment_wrapper, mapFragment, MAP_FRAGMENT_TAG);\n    fragmentTransaction.commit();\n&125;\nsetUpMapIfNeeded();\n  \n\n This in the  onResume()  method: \n\n  setUpMapIfNeeded();\n  \n\n And the  setUpMapIfNeeded()  method could look like this: \n\n  if (map == null) &123;\n    map = mapFragment.getMap();\n    if (map != null) &123;\n        setUpMap();\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n\n (So the map sets up already in  onCreate()  and if not, then in  onResume() .) \n\n Hope this helps someone. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/23/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/23/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "04/23/2013", "id": "625", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Google Maps v2 sometimes reset when resuimg my app", "parent_id": "16149601", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "1274911", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Zabri", "owner_user_id": "1274911"},{"body": " if fetchNew is a callback that gets an array of string, youre actually complicating it too much, a simpler method would be like so: \n\n  function fetchNew(myArray) &123;                           // receive the array as a parameter.\n    var length = myArray.length;                       // Cache the length of array\n    for (i = 0; i &lt; length; i++) &123;                     // loop through the array.\n        var element = $(&lt;li&gt; + myArray[i] + &lt;li&gt;); // concatenate the current value inside an LI and create a dom element.\n        $(.messages).append(element);                // Add element to the parent container\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/23/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/23/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "626", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Adding an array to the DOM with each element as an li", "parent_id": "16176706", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Kenneth", "owner_user_id": "1816704"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Are you asking if it is possible to use the  GHUnit  test runner for regular  OCUnit / SenTestCase  tests? If so, I expect you can based on reading the  documentation . Try creating the test bundle as usual (if you dont already have one), and add the  GHUnit  target  according to the instructions . Then add your  SenTestCase  test files to the  GHUnit  target, and they should get run automatically by  GHUnit . \n", "last_activity_date": "04/24/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/24/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "627", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "GHUnit as test bundle instead of separate target", "parent_id": "16176736", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Greg Haskins", "owner_user_id": "356942"},{"body": " Try use host:  \n\n  $host = \"ssl://smtp.gmail.com\";\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/24/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/24/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "628", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Sending PHP emails via gmail account having non gmail domain", "parent_id": "16185141", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Jiri Zachar", "owner_user_id": "2306588"},{"body": " Firstly, dont mix DOM0 inline event handlers with jQuery.  Separate your markup and your logic. \n\n If you use a  data-  attribute you can put your variables content in your HTML, and then extract that in the event handler: \n\n  &lt;a id=\"test\" data-foo=\"mytitle\" href=\"#\"&gt;Testlink&lt;/a&gt;\n  \n\n and then: \n\n  $(document).ready(function() &123;\n    $(#test).on(click, function() &123;\n        alert($(this).data(foo));\n    &125;\n&125;);\n  \n\n In this code the  alert  wont appear until the link is actually clicked on, of course. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/24/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/24/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "629", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Use JavaScript-Variable in jQuery", "parent_id": "16192187", "comment_count": 4, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Alnitak", "owner_user_id": "6782"},{"body": "  var array = &lt;%= escape_javascript @publisher_list.to_json %&gt;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/25/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/25/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "630", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "ruby array to javascript - Rails", "parent_id": "16210798", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "manoj", "owner_user_id": "1160267"},{"body": " You have to user x:Key, not x:Name for resources.\nThe conversion error occurs when you have the x:Name attribute but not x:Key.\n \n\n  &lt;Color x:Key=\"ButtonForeground\"&gt;#FFFFFFFF&lt;/Color&gt;\n  \n\n  x:Key  is used to identify resources within a ResourceDictionary, whereas  x:Name  is used to name elements (Grid, controls etc)... \n", "last_activity_date": "04/25/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/25/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "631", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Silverlight - Managing Color Resources - Errors", "parent_id": "16144787", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Tonio", "owner_user_id": "1425718"},{"body": " You should change: \n\n  loadSocialGraph: function () &123;\n\n    var result = ko.observableArray();\n    // user id will be loaded dynamically in later steps\n    OData.read(\"/Service_UserProfile(1)/Socialgraph/\", function (data) &123;\n\n        $.each(data.results, function (index, item) &123;                   \n            result.push(new SocialGraph(item));                    \n       &125;);\n    &125;);        \n    return result;\n&125;\n  \n\n and \n\n  function UserProfileModel(item,socialgraphs) &123;\n    this.Id = ko.observable(item.Id),\n    this.Nickname = ko.observable(item.Nickname),\n    this.socialgraphs = socialgraphs\n&125;;\n  \n\n Why: \nAt the line  this.socialgraphs = ko.observableArray(socialgraphs)  \nsocialgraphs in the right part is []. Only after some time interval it\nwill be filled with values. And because of it is not observable array,\nknockout wont notice that some items were pushed in it. I.e. it will stay empty. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/25/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/25/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "632", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Knockout.js use foreach to display object properties", "parent_id": "16214554", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Vladimir Frolov", "owner_user_id": "1786606"},{"body": " As @YourCommonSense already mentioned, raw PDO interface is a little bit clearer, however the problem is probably due to the use of function   PDOStatement::bindParam()   instead of   PDOStatement::bindValue()  . \n\n The difference between those two is that, the first one takes a  variable reference , which is constantly overwritten in your  foreach  loop, while the last one takes the actual value of the variable. \n\n \n\n If youre looking for some more friendly database connection interface, why wont you try  Doctrine DBAL ? \n", "last_activity_date": "04/25/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/25/2013", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "633", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "PDO - bindParam not working", "parent_id": "16218797", "comment_count": 2, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Crozin", "owner_user_id": "252591"},{"body": " Ill start with the servlet. I think what youre looking for is  createSession method  in the servlet. It provides a number of ways to start a user authenticated session on the server. I use it all the time. Some more detail about Domino objects in Java that also covers authentication  here . Even though its a few years old, the Java APIs are still relevant. \n\n But your problem is that you need to send the credentials securely down the line to the server. You can use SSL, and then add  HTTP header fields in the request at the browser , (SSL encrypts headers), and pull the values out in the servlet using  HTTPServletRequest.getHeader . you dont need to copy the default Domino header names if you dont want to as you have a servlet processing the data. You can do anything you want and do not have to specifically need to duplicate the default login form in Domino. \n", "last_activity_date": "04/26/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/26/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "04/26/2013", "id": "634", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Authenticating users programmatically", "parent_id": "16224056", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "193467", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "giulio", "owner_user_id": "193467"},{"body": " in rails 3 you have unobtrusive javascript \n\n so basically, any link you create with  :remote =&gt; true  would call that  controller#action  but with a js.erb ending \n\n so in your case the button would call the  check  action in the  test  controller \n\n if you create a check.js.erb and place it in the  views/test  folder and have inside \n\n  alert(\"UJS!\"); \n  \n\n it should pop up once you press that button \n\n also note that you should have the rails-ujs gem and require it in the application.js manifest \n", "last_activity_date": "04/26/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/26/2013", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "635", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Updating from Rails 2 to Rails 3 with JQuery AJAX", "parent_id": "16238771", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Nick Ginanto", "owner_user_id": "972789"}]'
