te_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Warning: mysql_num_rows() expects parameter 1 to be resource, boolean given in on line 44", "parent_id": "16267425", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Maxime", "owner_user_id": "2329933"},{"body": " I struggled through this issue all day today and final figured out the correct path to altering line items prices. The problem is that, even if you successfully change the line item price to a custom value, on the next page refresh the cart will reset the line items to match the original product price. Take a look at the   commerce_cart_order_refresh()   function for details. This function is executed every time an order/cart is loaded on the page and there is no way around it. \n\n It turns out that the proper way to alter a line item price is to either use Rules or to implement the   hook_commerce_cart_line_item_refresh()   function. Either way, Drupal Commerce need to be able to apply the alteration logic each time the cart/order is loaded. \n\n I ended up creating a custom field in the Line Item where I stored the custom price value I wanted. I then used a Pricing Rule to copy the custom price value to the product price value whenever the cart is refreshed. \n\n The following blog post was very helpful in figuring this out. It shows you how to add a custom field to a line item type and how to setup a pricing rule to copy the custom amount to the unit price. \n\n  http://commerceguys.com/blog/using-custom-line-items-provide-donation-feature-drupal-commerce  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/02/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/02/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "652", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Drupal Commerce Line Items: alter the price?", "parent_id": "13491983", "comment_count": 3, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Nathan Rambeck", "owner_user_id": "179192"},{"body": " Why dont you simply try this \n\n  string upperString = mystring.ToUpper();\n  \n\n If you want to first letter of each word in upper case then you can try this. \n\n  CultureInfo cultureInfo = Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture;\nTextInfo textInfo = cultureInfo.TextInfo;\nstring capitalString=textInfo.ToTitleCase(myString));\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "05/13/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/13/2013", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "05/13/2013", "id": "653", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how can I capitalize words in c# .net", "parent_id": "16529927", "comment_count": 3, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "1041642", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sachin", "owner_user_id": "1041642"},{"body": " Check your command \"cmd.exe /C start ExeFile -t:pass user\" if it works correctly or not.\nI think, ExeFile crashes. \n", "last_activity_date": "05/29/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "05/29/2013", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "654", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to make a truly independent process in WPF C#", "parent_id": "16803483", "comment_count": 6, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Mike", "owner_user_id": "2341535"},{"body": " Like Wubao Li said , this now is supported by android in the DrawerLayout \n\n Here is a tutorial of how to use it \n http://developer.android.com/training/