curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " IMHO there is no dedicated requirements overview for Dynamics CRM 4, but as the mobile interface has not really changed I would say that the requirements for Dynamics CRM 2011 are the same as for Dynamics CRM 4:  http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh367440.aspx  \n\n \n   Mobile Express will only run on a mobile device that has a web browser that supports HTML 4.0 or a later version and JavaScript. \n \n\n As it works on your other devices it could be some network related error. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/22/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/22/2011", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "757", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How can I access Microsoft Dynamics CRM from android device?", "parent_id": "7512496", "comment_count": 2, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "ccellar", "owner_user_id": "315862"},{"body": " You are using method \"POST\" and not providing actual query string. Query string is created only for \"GET\" method and should be the part of the URL, so the fix would be: \n\n  $.ajax(\\{\n    type: \"GET\",\n    url:\"Dbread.aspx?name=salam\",\n    ...\n  \n\n or \n\n  $.ajax(\\{\n    type: \"GET\",\n    url:\"Dbread.aspx\",\n    data: \"name=salam\",\n    ...\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "09/30/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/30/2011", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "758", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "return null with query string whtn i use ajax-jquery", "parent_id": "7613641", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Andrei", "owner_user_id": "728795"},{"body": " It has,  Introduction  \n\n \n   A value is a \n  \n   \n   basic type like string, integer,  float , timestamp, binary, etc., \n   a document, or \n   an array of values \n   \n \n", "last_activity_date": "10/07/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/07/2011", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "759", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Does MongoDB support floating point types?", "parent_id": "7682714", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "lostyzd", "owner_user_id": "979013"},{"body": " yes, if you specify finder_sql, then you will not be able to append scopes. that&#39s because finder_sql is for situations that do not fit the normal activeRecord paradigm.  That being said, the way you have this constructed is incorrect. you should not need to store a select * with no filters in a relationship like that. the purpose of a relationship is to apply a filter to the other model.  so, the way you have it Model.find(params[:id]).somethings is exactly the same as calling Something.all . the scope will work for you in the latter case because .all can be scoped. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/07/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/07/2011", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "760", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Rails has_many with finder_sql and name_scope in combination return nil", "parent_id": "7688280", "comment_count": 0, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Chris Drappier", "owner_user_id": "46717"},{"body": " You dont need a model for the intermediate table if you are only using it for the mapping. \n\n You would need a model in case this table holds other attributes that need to be accessed. \n\n for example considering your many to many relationship between store and inventory. \n\n If you need to add an attribute to the medinventory table, to tell the application when was the relation created (created_time), and later on you need to access that property, then yes, would need to create a model. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/20/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/20/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "761", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Does associative table need model in Yii framework?", "parent_id": "13973466", "comment_count": 3, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Asgaroth", "owner_user_id": "829903"},{"body": " The two are semantically equivalent (among other variations on the theme). One difference is that many users on Stackoverflow are very vocal in expressing their intolerant to &#39old style&#39 inner joins (your SQL 2), to the point where anyone posting them risks being downvoted in addition to being admonished in comments. You&#39re also likely to see the term &#39anti-pattern&#39 applied, which is nonsense. I&#39ve not encountered this style intolerance outside of the SO community. In fact, &#39old style&#39 inner joins are very common in the SQL literature. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/24/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/24/2011", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "762", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What&#39s the difference between the two SQL join notations?", "parent_id": "8251294", "comment_count": 2, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "onedaywhen", "owner_user_id": "15354"},{"body": " When the second statement runs, the element  #create_new_gallery  does not exist yet so it does nothing. \n\n You can do the binding to the click event after you created the element for instance, this ensures the element exists in the DOM: \n\n  $(\"#add_gallery\").click(function() \\{\n    $(\"#new_gallery\").append(&#39&lt;input name=\"new_gallery\" /&gt;&lt;a href=\"#\" id=\"create_new_gallery\"&gt;Add&lt;/a&gt;&#39);\n    $(this).remove();\n    $(\"#create_new_gallery\").on(&#39click&#39, function() \\{\n        alert(&#391&#39);\n    \\});\n\\});\u200b\n  \n\n   DEMO   \n\n \n\n Here is a little bit more optimized version. It&#39s a bit non-sense to append an element and have to re-query for it (event though querying by id is the fastest method. Besides, it&#39s best to use the chaining capabilities of jQuery afterall: \n\n  $(\"#add_gallery\").click(function() \\{\n    var $gallery = $(\"#new_gallery\");\n\n    $(&#39&lt;input name=\"new_gallery\" /&gt;&#39).appendTo($gallery);\n    $(&#39&lt;a href=\"#\" id=\"create_new_gallery\"&gt;Add&lt;/a&gt;&#39)\n        .on(&#39click&#39, function() \\{\n            alert(&#391&#39);\n        \\})\n        .appendTo($gallery);\n\n    $(this).remove();\n\\});\u200b\n  \n\n   DEMO   \n", "last_activity_date": "02/22/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "02/22/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "02/22/2012", "id": "763", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Jquery append input element and send data from that input element", "parent_id": "9392758", "comment_count": 3, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "123127", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Didier Ghys", "owner_user_id": "123127"},{"body": " Yes, but you can&#39t register clicks to HTML that doesn&#39t exist yet, which it might not in this case. That&#39s what that &#39onShow&#39 option is for. If you register events after the modal has shown itself, it should work. You might also want to unbind the new button before binding in case the modal caches that button in HTML (which would result in rebinding and refiring the function multiple times). \n\n or you could just do delegation on the curtain. see JQuery.delegate (they may have updated that recently depending on what version of JQ you&#39re using) \n\n I hope you&#39re not wanting two at the same time. It&#39s probably not set up for that. It would be easy enough to hack but from a UI perspective, ew in most scenarios. \n", "last_activity_date": "03/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/07/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "764", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "call one simple modal while another is still open", "parent_id": "9594441", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Erik  Reppen", "owner_user_id": "450222"},{"body": " Yes, by specializing  Derived . \n\n \n write the generic version without it (it will inherit it from  Base ) \n specialize  Derived  to override \n \n\n Simple scheme, but it works. \n", "last_activity_date": "06/02/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "06/02/2012", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "765", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Overriding a function only for certain types in template", "parent_id": "10863444", "comment_count": 0, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 