e": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "31158", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Jord\u00e3o", "owner_user_id": "31158"},{"body": " The convention is to have only one Window which is declared in your  AppDelegate . Inside of windows you add ViewControllers which can handle all your additional views. So you&#39d create a  LoginViewController  and a  RegisterViewController . \n\n Usually multiple windows are only needed for things like creating an alert (UIAlertView is its own UIWindow) that would be on top of all other views, but even this can be achieved by using  keyWindow . \n", "last_activity_date": "07/28/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "07/28/2012", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "780", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "When should I create a new window instead of using many different views?", "parent_id": "11698951", "comment_count": 8, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "shabzco", "owner_user_id": "253008"},{"body": " My current solution is introducing this AspectJ hack in order to override the singletons factory method \n\n  @Aspect\npublic class MockingAspect &123;\n\n    @Around(\"call(synchronized static OwlApiRepository *(..))\")\n    public OwlApiRepository processGetInstance(ProceedingJoinPoint jp) &123;      \n        System.out.println(\"getting mock\");\n        return MockHolder.getMock();\n    &125;\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "08/06/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/06/2012", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "781", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to mock an aspect", "parent_id": "11825325", "comment_count": 0, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "malejpavouk", "owner_user_id": "508219"},{"body": " I would use a plain ByteBuffer and I would write out the data when the buffer fills. (or do what ever you planed to do with it) \n\n e.g. \n\n  SocketChannel sc = ...\nByteBuffer bb = ByteBuffer.allocateDirect(32 * 1024).order(ByteOrder.LITTLE_ENDIAN);\nfor(int i = 0 ; i &lt; 100000000; i++) &123;\n   float f = i;\n   // move to a checkFree(4) method.\n   if (bb.remaining() &lt; 4) &123;\n       bb.flip();\n       while(bb.remaining() &gt; 0)\n           sc.write(bb);\n   &125;\n   // end of emthod\n   bb.putFloat(f);\n  \n\n &125; \n\n Creating really large buffers can actually be slower than processing the data as you generate it. \n\n Note: this creates almost no garbage. There is only one object which is the ByteBuffer. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/07/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/07/2012", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "782", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "How to create a FloatBuffer dynamically", "parent_id": "11842645", "comment_count": 6, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Peter Lawrey", "owner_user_id": "57695"},{"body": " You need to get the file to get the data inside it. \n\n Have your server delete it afterwards. \n", "last_activity_date": "08/23/2012", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "08/23/2012", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "783", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "how to use online CSV file data as value without downloading the file", "parent_id": "12099662", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post