FireFox. \n\n If a peace of software you searching for is more like form filler, than take a look at  iMacros , thay have a complete browser-side scriptable solution. \n", "last_activity_date": "02/28/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "02/28/2010", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "826", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Automated browsing with javascript?", "parent_id": "2352508", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Sergey Kovalev", "owner_user_id": "96270"},{"body": " The coder need made one branch by feature and pull all branches. You can merge it if you want.\nThe coder not change his master branch and this it always like lead master branch \n", "last_activity_date": "03/11/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/11/2010", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "827", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What&#39s the best way to manage a multi-user project on github?", "parent_id": "2426673", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "shingara", "owner_user_id": "285289"},{"body": " The way you&#39re attempting to use delegates (constructing them with  new , declaring a named delegate type) suggests that you&#39re using C# 1. If you&#39re actually using C# 3, it&#39s much easier than that. \n\n Firstly, your delegate type: \n\n  public delegate List&lt;BaseNode&gt; GetAllNodesDelegate(int k);\n  \n\n Already exists. It&#39s just: \n\n  Func&lt;int, List&lt;BaseNode&gt;&gt;\n  \n\n So you don&#39t need to declare your own version of it. \n\n Secondly, you should think of a delegate as being like an interface with only one method in it, and you can \"implement\" it on the fly, without having to write a named class. Just write a lambda, or assign a method name directly. \n\n  Func&lt;int, List&lt;BaseNode&gt;&gt; getNodesFromInt;\n\n// just assign a compatible method directly\ngetNodesFromInt = DoSomethingWithArgAndReturnList;\n\n// or bind extra arguments to an incompatible method:\ngetNodesFromInt = arg =&gt; MakeList(arg, \"anotherArgument\");\n\n// or write the whole thing specially:\ngetNodesFromInt = arg =&gt;\n    \\{\n        var result = new List&lt;BaseNode&gt;();\n        result.Add(new BaseNode());\n        return result;\n    \\};\n  \n\n A lambda is of the form  (arguments) =&gt; \\{ body; \\} . The arguments are comma-separated. If there&#39s only one, you can omit the parentheses. If it takes no parameters, put a pair of empty parentheses:  () . If the body is only one statement long, you can omit the braces. If it&#39s just a single expression, you can omit the braces and the  return  keyword. In the body, you can refer to practically any variables and methods from the enclosing scope (apart from  ref / out  parameters to the enclosing method). \n\n There&#39s almost never any need to use  new  to create a delegate instance. And rarely a need to declare custom delegate types. Use  Func  for delegates that return a value and  Action  for delegates that return  void . \n\n Whenever the thing you need to pass around is like an object with one method (whether an interface or a class), then use a delegate instead, and you&#39ll be able to avoid a lot of mess. \n\n In particular, avoid defining interfaces with one method. It will just mean that instead of being able to write a lambda to implement that method, you&#39ll have to declare a separate named class for each different implementation, with the pattern: \n\n  class Impl : IOneMethod\n\\{\n    // a bunch of fields\n\n    public Impl(a bunch of parameters)\n    \\{\n        // assign all the parameters to their fields\n    \\}\n\n    public void TheOneMethod()\n    \\{\n        // make use of the fields\n    \\}\n\\}\n  \n\n A lambda effectively does all that for you, eliminating such mechanical patterns from your code. You just say: \n\n  () =&gt; /* same code as in TheOneMethod */\n  \n\n It also has the advantage that you can update variables in the enclosing scope, because you can refer directly to them (instead of working with values copied into fields of a class). Sometimes this can be a disadvantage, if you don&#39t want to modify the values. \n", "last_activity_date": "03/17/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/17/2010", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "828", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "c# delegate and abstract class", "parent_id": "2460451", "comment_count": 5, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Daniel Earwicker", "owner_user_id": "27423"},{"body": "  http://forums.asp.net/p/1344561/3759667.aspx#3759667  \n", "last_activity_date": "03/31/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/31/2010", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "829", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "SQL Reporting Services - Print Button not shown in Mozilla", "parent_id": "951009", "comment_count": 1, "score": 1, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "zeroxs", "owner_user_id": "305656"},{"body": " There is no way to setup global usings for the code-behinds.  You have to put the usings in the code files.  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/16/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/16/2010", "votes_count": 7, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id":