curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " To elaborate on my comment on using custom collections, you&#39d do something like this in your form&#39s module: \n\n    Private mcolGroupABC As New Collection\n\n  Private Sub IntializeCollections()\n    Dim ctl As Control\n\n    If mcolGroupABC.Count = 0 Then\n       For Each ctl in Me.Controls\n         If ctl.Tag = \"GroupABC\" Then\n            mcolGroupABC.Add ctl, ctl.Name\n         End If\n       Next ctl\n       Set ctl = Nothing\n    End If\n  End Sub\n\n  Private Sub Form_Load()\n    Call InitializeCollection\n  End Sub\n\n  Private Sub ShowControls(mcol As Collection, bolShow As Boolean)\n    Dim ctl As Control\n\n    For Each ctl In mcol\n      ctl.Visible = bolShow\n    Next ctl\n    Set ctl = Nothing\n  End Sub\n  \n\n To hide the controls, you&#39d do this: \n\n    Call ShowControls(mcolGroupABC, False)\n  \n\n And to show them: \n\n    Call ShowControls(mcolGroupABC, True)\n  \n\n That&#39s pretty simple, no? \n\n This is the kind of code I use in my apps all the time, and I&#39ve used it ever since the first time I implemented it, about 10 years ago, and noticed that it was clearly noticeably faster to show/hide controls with the custom collection than it was with walking the entire Controls collection. \n\n The only caveat is that if one of the controls has the focus, it will error out if you try to hide it. That&#39s easily enough addressed, since if you&#39re hiding a group of controls, you surely have an appropriate place to set the focus before you do so. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/04/2009", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/03/2009", "votes_count": 2, "last_edit_date": "11/04/2009", "id": "922", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Grouping controls together on an Access form", "parent_id": "1661751", "comment_count": 2, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "9787", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "David-W-Fenton", "owner_user_id": "9787"},{"body": " Look into MSBuild, this runs a script generated by VS i believe. sorry i cant provide more information that this but it might give you that extra \"hint\" required to find what you need. \n", "last_activity_date": "11/17/2009", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "11/17/2009", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "923", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Best way to deploy VB.NET Code / create an assembly on a SQLServer", "parent_id": "1748980", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "WiseGuyEh", "owner_user_id": "212104"},{"body": " Under OS X this is part of the operating system and is automatically updated.  For Windows you must do it yourself. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/02/2009", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/02/2009", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "924", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is there a way to update the JDK without manually downloading the new version?", "parent_id": "1829986", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Thorbj\u00f8rn Ravn Andersen", "owner_user_id": "53897"},{"body": " wrap  smtpClient.Send(fromAddress, toAddress, subject, body);  inside a try catch statment and see what the exception is  \n", "last_activity_date": "12/09/2009", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/09/2009", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "925", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "What am I missing? My app can send e-mail via gmail on my dev box, but not on my server", "parent_id": "1873611", "comment_count": 1, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Yassir", "owner_user_id": "72443"},{"body": " The problem is, if you just write  Const  it is evaluated on Module creation time. You have to use  Module#const_get  instead like this:  const_get(:Const) . This is evaluated at runtime when the method is executed. So this happens in your class and not in your module. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/13/2009", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "12/13/2009", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "926", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "(In Ruby) allowing mixed-in class methods access to class constants", "parent_id": "1897699", "comment_count": 1, "score": 5, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "johannes", "owner_user_id": "174896"},{"body": " After some googling I am able to do that. \n\n  if(p7-&gt;d.sign-&gt;cert != NULL)\\{\n    PEM_write_X509(fp, sk_X509_value(p7-&gt;d.sign-&gt;cert, 0)); \n\\}\n  \n\n where p7 is a pointer to pkcs7 struct and fp is the file pointer to PEM file \n", "last_activity_date": "01/11/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "01/07/2010", "votes_count": 1, "last_edit_date": "01/11/2010", "id": "927", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is there any OpenSSL function to convert PKCS7 file to PEM", "parent_id": "2023046", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "214037", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Vishnu", "owner_user_id": "214037"},{"body": " What do you mean by \"mysql functions and their values do not appear [in phpinfo()]\"? \n\n I know what mysql functions are - but they don&#39t appear in phpinfo() at any time. Function values...? Do you mean the mysql related ini settings? If so then you&#39ve probably not declared the mysql extension in the ini file. \n\n Something like... \n\n  extension_dir=\"C:/php5/ext/\"\nextension=php_mysql.dll\n  \n\n for MSWindows. For everything else, something like: \n\n  extension_dir=\"/usr/lib/php/modules/\"\nextension=mysql.so\n  \n\n HTH \n\n C. \n", "last_activity_date": "02/08/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "02/08/2010", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "928", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "MySQL functions don&#39t load when using custom PHP.ini on windows server", "parent_id": "2215727", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "symcbean", "owner_user_id": "223992"},{"body": " I&#39ve had this happen before when my shapes are small enough or the movements are fast enough for the interval between physics calculation \"ticks\" to be enough to allow the objects to overlap before the collision detection kicks in. \n", "last_activity_date": "12/16/2010", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/04/2010", "votes_count": 0, "last_edit_date": "12/16/2010", "id": "929", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Farseer Physics XNA Geom &#39Tripping&#39", "parent_id": "1812710", "comment_count": 0, "score": 0, "last_editor_user_id": "29553", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "TreeUK", "owner_user_id": "29553"},{"body": " I think you need redesign your schema.\nWhy not?