curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " Three ways to do this \n\n Way one, using a pointer \n\n  - (void)priceFormat:(NSString **)price \\{\n  *price = @\"2\";\n\\}\n  \n\n \n\n Wat two, using an instance variable \n\n What you might want instead is an ivar. In the interface (most often the  h  file) of your class: \n\n  NSString *price;\n  \n\n and in the implementation (the  m  or  mm  file): \n\n  - (void)priceFormat:(NSString *)price \\{\n  price = @\"2\";\n\\}\n  \n\n I have created an example of this  here . \n\n \n\n If you want the price to be available to other objects as well (not just  self ), you might want to create a property for it and synthesize it. Then use  self.price = @\"2\";  instead. More on this here:  http://MacDeveloperTips.com/objective-c/objective-c-properties-setters-and-dot-syntax.html  \n\n  Just make sure you make it a  copy  property (NSString in use)!  \n\n \n\n Way three using  return  \n\n Note, that you can also return directly from a method: \n\n  - (NSString *)priceFormat:(NSString *)price \\{\n  return @\"2\";\n\\}\n\npriceLabel.text = [self priceFormat:@\"1\"];\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "03/10/2011", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "03/10/2011", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "03/10/2011", "id": "994", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "user142019", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Objective C Function Question", "parent_id": "5263278", "comment_count": 3, "score": 3, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "NULL", "owner_user_id": "0"},{"body": " I think the problem is likely that youve added the  MovieClip  cast in the wrong place, as though there were a property MovieClip on the object bars_mc. \n\n This example involves an extra line but should be a bit clearer: \n\n  var myBtnArray = [bmc1, bmc2, bmc3, bmc4, bmc5, bmc6, bmc7, bmc8, bmc9, bmc10, bmc11];\nfor each (var btn:String in myBtnArray) &123;\n    var btnClip:MovieClip = bars_mc[btn] as MovieClip;\n    btnClip.gotoAndPlay(open);\n&125;\n  \n\n And a version closer to your original would be: \n\n  var myBtnArray = [bmc1, bmc2, bmc3, bmc4, bmc5, bmc6, bmc7, bmc8, bmc9, bmc10, bmc11];\nfor each (var btn:String in myBtnArray) &123;\n    MovieClip(bars_mc[btn]).gotoAndPlay(open);\n&125;\n  \n", "last_activity_date": "04/16/2013", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "04/16/2013", "votes_count": 3, "last_edit_date": "01/01/1970", "id": "995", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Converting String values to MovieClip in AS 3.0", "parent_id": "16036301", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "0", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "hanenbro", "owner_user_id": "1579055"},{"body": " The knuth shuffle is an insignificant change compared to the naive shuffle: Just swap with any card in the remaining (unshuffled) section of the deck instead of anywhere in the entire deck. If you think of it as repeatedly choosing the next card in order from the remaining unchosen cards, it&#39s pretty intuitive, too. \n\n Personally, I think teaching students a poor algorithm when the proper one is no more complicated (and easier to visualise!) is a bad approach. \n", "last_activity_date": "09/19/2008", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "09/18/2008", "votes_count": 11, "last_edit_date": "09/19/2008", "id": "996", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "Arachnid", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Real-world problems with naive shuffling", "parent_id": "96840", "comment_count": 1, "score": 11, "last_editor_user_id": "12030", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Nick Johnson", "owner_user_id": "12030"},{"body": " No if you are strictly speaking about reguralr expressions and not including some regular expression implementations that are actually context free grammars.   \n\n There is one limitation of regular expressions which makes it impossible to write a regex that matches a regex.  You cannot match implementations such as braces which are paired.  Regex&#39s use many such constructs, lets take [] as an example.  Whenever there is an [ there must be a matching ].  Simple enough for a regex \"[.*]\". \n\n What makes it impossible for regexe&#39s is that they can be nested.  How can you write a regex that matches nested brackets?  The answer is you can&#39t without an infinitely long regex.  You can match any number of nested parens through brute force but you can&#39t ever match an arbitrarily long set of nested brackets.   \n\n This capability is often referred to as counting (you&#39re counting the depth of the nesting).  A regex by definition does not have the capability to count.  \n\n EDIT:\nEnded up writing a blog post about this:  Regular Expression Limitations  \n", "last_activity_date": "10/15/2008", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/05/2008", "votes_count": 25, "last_edit_date": "10/15/2008", "id": "997", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "JaredPar", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is there a regular expression to detect a valid regular expression?", "parent_id": "172303", "comment_count": 0, "score": 25, "last_editor_user_id": "23283", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "JaredPar", "owner_user_id": "23283"},{"body": " In C you can&#39t define the function inline, so you can&#39t really create a closure.  All you&#39re doing is passing around a reference to some pre-defined method.  In languages that support anonymous methods/closures, the definition of the methods are a lot more flexible. \n\n In the simplest terms, function pointers have no scope associated with then (unless you count the global scope), whereas closures include the scope of the method that&#39s defining them.  With lambdas, you can write a method that writes a method.  Closures allow you to bind \"some arguments to a function and getting a lower-arity function as a result.\" (taken from Thomas&#39s comment). You can&#39t do that in C. \n\n EDIT:  Adding an example (I&#39m going to use Actionscript-ish syntax cause that&#39s what&#39s on my mind right now): \n\n Say you have some method that takes another method as its argument, but doesn&#39t provide a way to pass any parameters to that method when it&#39s called?  Like, say, some method that causes a delay before running the method you passed it (stupid example, but I want to keep it simple). \n\n  function runLater(f:Function):Void \\{\n  sleep(100);\n  f();\n\\}\n  \n\n Now say you want to user runLater() to delay some processing of an object: \n\n  function objectProcessor(o:Object):Void \\{\n  /* Do something cool with the object! */\n\\}\n\nfunction process(o:Object):Void \\{\n  runLater(function() \\{ objectProcessor(o); \\});\n\\}\n  \n\n The function you&#39re passing to process() isn&#39t some staticly defined function anymore.  It&#39s dynamically generated, and is able to include references to variables that were in scope when the method was defined.  So, it can access &#39o&#39 and &#39objectProcessor&#39, even though those aren&#39t in the global scope. \n\n I hope that made sense. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/16/2008", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/16/2008", "votes_count": 13, "last_edit_date": "10/16/2008", "id": "998", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "Herms", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Function pointers, Closures, and Lambda", "parent_id": "208835", "comment_count": 2, "score": 7, "last_editor_user_id": "1409", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Herms", "owner_user_id": "1409"},{"body": " It&#39s a coincidence that it compiles correctly in 32bit; the correct syntax is: \n\n  typedef int (WINAPI *FFuncType)();\nFFuncType m_FuncAddr;\nm_FuncAddr = (FFuncType)::GetProcAddress (somthing);\n  \n\n You need to explicitly cast the result of ::GetProcAddress to the proper function signature. In 32bit, FARPROC happens to work with the signature you have, but probably not in 64bit. \n\n Edit: Yes, in fact, looking at windef.h, the return type is INT_PTR in 64bit, so that&#39s why you got the compiler error. You will still need to cast to the function signature as above for any function which does not happen to match the placeholder for FARPROC, though, so you should be doing it as above in general. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/17/2008", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/17/2008", "votes_count": 4, "last_edit_date": "10/17/2008", "id": "999", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "Nick", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "stdcall over-ride by visual studio?", "parent_id": "210836", "comment_count": 9, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "26240", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Nick", "owner_user_id": "26240"}]'
curl "http://localhost:7049/stackoverflow/docs" -i -X PUT -d '[{"body": " AFAIK, you can&#39t do that. \nBut if the goal is to ensure you declare your actual constant string only once, I suggest you declare the individual strings and then group them in arrays:   \n\n  const\n  MyConst1 = &#39Hi\n  MyConst2 = &#39Foo\n  MyConst3 = &#39Bar\n  MyFirstConstArray: array[0..1] of string = (MyConst1, MyConst2);\n  MySecondConstArrayWhichIncludesTheFirstOne: array[0..2] of string = \n    (MyConst1, MyConst2, MyConst3);\n  \n\n BTW, your syntax is incorrect, you have to precise the type of the array elements. \n", "last_activity_date": "10/31/2008", "accepted_answer_id": "0", "creation_date": "10/29/2008", "votes_count": 5, "last_edit_date": "10/31/2008", "id": "1000", "favorite_count": 0, "last_editor_display_name": "Gamecat", "closed_date": "01/01/1970", "view_count": 0, "title": "Is it possible do Declare a constant array that includes another constant array?", "parent_id": "246969", "comment_count": 1, "score": 2, "last_editor_user_id": "18061", "post_type_id": "2", "community_owned_date": "01/01/1970", "tags": "", "answer_count": 0, "author_name": "Fran\u00e7ois", "owner_user_id": "9842"}]'
